{"title_page": "Veles (god)", "text_new": "{{More citations needed|date=September 2009}}\n{{Infobox deity\n| name              = Veles\n| god_of            = underworld, earth, waters, fertility, trickery, cattle, pasture, snakes, bears, wolves, medicine, music, and magic\n| type              = Slavic\n| image             = File:Veles Volos.jpg\n| caption           = <small>''Veles'', Marek Hapon, 2014</small>\n| abode             = \n| symbol            = Bear, wolf, snake, dragon, owl, willow\n| consort           = \n| parents           = \n| siblings          = \n| children          = \n| mount             = \n| festivals         = The [[Festival of Veles]]\n| Canaanite_equivalent  = [[Baal]]\n| Slavic_equivalent = similar to [[Flins (deity)|Flins]], [[Triglav (deity)|Triglav]]\n}}\n[[File:Zbruch Triglav.PNG|thumb|upright|Probable image of Veles-[[Triglav (mythology)|Triglav]] from lower part of [[Zbruch Idol]]]]\n[[File:Symbol of Veles.svg|thumb|upright|Modern symbol of Veles, used by [[Slavic Native Faith|Rodnovers]]<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.slavorum.org/veles-the-slavic-shapeshifting-god-of-land-water-and-underground/ |title= Veles \u2013 The Slavic Shapeshifting God of Land, Water and Underground |author= Aleksandra Kojic |website= Slavorum |date= 2016-08-18 |access-date= 2017-09-08}}</ref>]]\n[[File:Vel\u00edz, Veles.jpg|thumb|upright|The modern statue of Veles on Vel\u00edz mountain, [[Czech Republic]]]]\n'''Veles''' ([[Cyrillic script|Cyrillic]] [[Bulgarian language|Bulgarian]], [[Macedonian language|Macedonian]], [[Serbian language|Serbian]] and [[Ukrainian language|Ukrainian]]: \u0412\u0435\u043b\u0435\u0441; {{lang-pl|Weles}}; [[Bosnian language|Bosnian]], [[Croatian language|Croatian]], [[Czech language|Czech]], [[Montenegrin language|Montenegrin]], [[Slovak language|Slovak]], [[Slovenian language|Slovenian]]: ''Veles''; [[Ruthenian language|Ruthenian]] and [[Old Church Slavonic]]: \u0412\u0435\u043b\u0435\u0441\u044a; {{lang-be|\u0412\u044f\u043b\u0435\u0441|translit=Vialies}}), also known as '''Volos''' ({{lang-ru|\u0412\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0441}}, \u0412\u043b\u0430\u0441, \u0412\u043b\u0430\u0441\u0438\u0439 listed as a Christian saint, Armenian: \u054d\u0578\u0582\u0580\u0562 \u054e\u056c\u0561\u057d\u056b; germ: Blasius; fr: Blaise; sp: San Blas; port: S\u00e3o Br\u00e1s; it: San Biagio; croat: sv. Bla\u017e; eng: Blase, Wallace;  Greek: \u0386\u03b3\u03b9\u03bf\u03c2 \u0392\u03bb\u03ac\u03c3\u03b9\u03bf\u03c2), is a major [[Slavic pantheon|Slavic god]] of earth, waters, and the [[underworld]]. His attributes are wet, wooly, hairy (bearded), dark and he is associated with cattle, the harvest, wealth, music, [[Magic (paranormal)|magic]], and [[trickster|trickery]]. Believed to be related to the [[Proto-Indo-European religion|Indo-European]] deity of [[Mitra]]. According to reconstruction by some researchers he is the opponent of the supreme [[thunder]] god [[Perun]].<ref name=katicic2008>{{cite book |last=[[Radoslav Kati\u010di\u0107|Kati\u010di\u0107]] |first=Radoslav |title=Bo\u017eanski boj: Tragovima svetih pjesama na\u0161e pretkr\u0161\u0107anske starine |year=2008 |publisher=IBIS GRAFIKA |location=Zagreb |isbn=978-953-6927-41-8 |url=http://ir.nmu.org.ua/bitstream/handle/123456789/120570/96db5654f2d3025b46454ace91716506.pdf |ref=katicic2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151018000746/http://ir.nmu.org.ua/bitstream/handle/123456789/120570/96db5654f2d3025b46454ace91716506.pdf |archivedate=2015-10-18 }}</ref>{{Rp|211\u2013214}} As such he probably has been imagined as a [[Slavic dragon|dragon]], which in the belief of the pagan Slavs is a [[Chimera (mythology)|chimeric]] being, a serpent with a bear's head and drooping hairy ears.<ref name=katicic2008/>{{Rp|141}}<ref name=uspensky1982>{{cite book |url=http://www.gumer.info/bibliotek_Buks/Culture/usp/02.php |title=\u0424\u0438\u043b\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0433\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0435 \u0440\u0430\u0437\u044b\u0441\u043a\u0430\u043d\u0438\u044f \u0432 \u043e\u0431\u043b\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0438 \u0441\u043b\u0430\u0432\u044f\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0445 \u0434\u0440\u0435\u0432\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0435\u0439. \u0420\u0435\u043b\u0438\u043a\u0442\u044b \u044f\u0437\u044b\u0447\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0430 \u0432 \u0432\u043e\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0447\u043d\u043e\u0441\u043b\u0430\u0432\u044f\u043d\u0441\u043a\u043e\u043c \u043a\u0443\u043b\u044c\u0442\u0435 \u041d\u0438\u043a\u043e\u043b\u0430\u044f \u041c\u0438\u0440\u0438\u043b\u0438\u043a\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e |publisher=[[Moscow State University]] |last=[[Boris Uspensky|\u0423\u0441\u043f\u0435\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439]] |first=\u0411\u043e\u0440\u0438\u0441 \u0410\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441\u0430\u043d\u0434\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447 |year=1982 |ref=uspensky1982}}</ref>{{Rp|87,88}} His tree is the willow much like Perun's tree is the oak.{{citation needed|date=December 2018}}\nNo direct accounts survive, but reconstructions speculate that he may directly continue aspects of the [[Proto-Indo-European pantheon]].{{citation needed|date=December 2018}}\n\n==Sources==\nVeles is one of few Slavic gods for which evidence of offerings can be found in all [[Slavic nations]]. The ''[[Primary Chronicle]]'', a historical record of the early [[Kievan Rus]], is the earliest and most important record, mentioning a god named Volos several times. Here, Volos is mentioned as god of cattle and peasants, who will punish oath-breakers with diseases, the opposite of Perun who is described as a ruling god of war who punishes by death in battle. In the later half of the 10th century, Veles or Volos was one of seven gods whose statues [[Vladimir I of Kiev]] had erected in his city. It is very interesting that Veles' statue apparently did not stand next to others, on the hill where the prince's castle was, but lower in the city, in the marketplace. Not only does this indicate that Veles was connected with commerce, but it also shows that worship of Perun and Veles had to be kept separate: while it was proper for Perun's shrines to be built high, on the top of the hill, Veles' place was down, in the lowlands.\n\nA similar pattern can be observed among the [[South Slavs]]. Here the name of Veles appears only in [[toponyms]], the best-known of which is the city of [[Veles, North Macedonia|Veles]] in [[North Macedonia|Macedonia]], over which looms a hill of St. [[Elijah|Elias]] the Thunderer. Also, in [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]], a part of [[Sarajevo]] is called Vele\u0161i\u0107i<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.novosarajevo.ba/stream/article.php?pid%3D118 |accessdate=September 12, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050308193444/http://www.novosarajevo.ba/stream/article.php?pid=118 |archivedate=March 8, 2005 |title=OPIS LOKACIJE MZ UNUTAR OP\u0106INE }}</ref> and a mountain Vele\u017e<ref>[[Vele\u017e (Bosnia and Herzegovina)]]</ref>{{Circular reference|date=November 2017}} near Mostar, Herzegovina. Other examples are Veles in Western Serbia, Velesnica on the Danube and Velestovo in [[Montenegro]] and also the township of Velestino (\u0392\u03b5\u03bb\u03b5\u03c3\u03c4\u03af\u03bd\u03bf, today \u03a6\u03ad\u03c1\u03b5\u03c2), apparently bearing testimony to a Slavic layer in the settlement of Thessaly. Another debatable if not improbable example<ref name=katicic2008/>{{Rp|178}}  is the town of [[Volosko]] in [[Croatia]], situated on the seashore under the peak of Mount [[U\u010dka]], [[nicknamed]] Perun.\n\nAmong [[Western Slavs]], the name can be principally found in 15th and 16th century [[Czech Republic|Czech]] records, where it means either [[dragon]] or [[devil]].\n\n==Etymology==\n[[File:The Mythology of all races (1918) (14578796339).jpg|thumb|\"Weles\" in wolf form, from ''The Mythology of All Races'' (1918).]]\nPresumably it is not possible to conclusively determine a definite etymology for the name of the god Veles, though there are several [[Proto-Indo-European language|Proto-Indo-European]] roots that are all closely related to the nature of Veles and his domains.\n\nOne possibility is that the name derives from the Proto-Indo-European root ''*wel-'', meaning wool.<ref name=\"Belaj\">Vitomir Belaj \"Hod kroz godinu, mitska pozadina hrvatskih narodnih vjerovanja i obicaja\", Golden Marketing, Zagreb 1998., {{ISBN|953-6168-43-X}}</ref> This seems plausible, since in Slavic cosmology Veles in serpentine form is lying in a nest of black wool in the roots of the Tree of the World<ref name=katicic2008/>{{Rp |136,154}} and Veles is the shepherd of the dead. ''Volos'' is also the Russian and Ukrainian word for \"hair\" and Veles is hairy in his beastly form (bear, wolf).\n\nThe Proto-Indo-European root ''*welg-'' also means humid, wet. Nothing is more connected with Veles than humidity and wetness. His domain is down, '\u0443 \u0432\u043e\u0434\u0443 \u043f\u043e\u0442 \u043a\u043e\u0440\u0447 \u043f\u043e\u0442 \u043a\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0434\u0443' (in the water, below the tree stump and the log). That is where Veles is in his place. English word wool has its root in Wolos too.\n\nThere is also the Indo-European word ''*woltus'' meaning meadow which is derived from the same root. And Veles is the shepherd of the dead who was imagined to browse the deceased on green lush meadows in the underworld.<ref name=katicic2008/>{{Rp |171}}<ref name=Ivanov_Toporov1973>{{cite journal |last1=[[Vyacheslav Ivanov (philologist)|Ivanov]] |first1=Vyacheslav | last2=[[Vladimir Toporov|Toporov]] | first2=Vladimir |title=A comparative study of the group of Baltic mythological terms from the root *vel- |year=1973 | publisher=baltistica T.9 Nr.(1) |url=http://www.baltistica.lt/index.php/baltistica/article/view/1802 |ref=Ivanov_Toporov1973}}</ref>\n\nThe name is also related to Slavic terminology for oxen, for which the South Slavs, Russians, and Poles use \"\u0432\u043e\u043b/vol/w\u00f3\u0142\".{{Citation needed|reason=reliable source needed for the whole sentence|date=December 2010}} Volos can also be a derivation from the same root by Eastern Slavic phonetic laws, now considered the most probable explanation for this phonetic form.<ref name=katicic2008/>{{Rp |171}} \n\nIt is probably the same as [[Vala (Vedic)|Vala]], the enemy of the [[Historical Vedic religion|Vedic]] thunder god [[Indra]] and to Velns ([[latvian mythology|Latvian]]) or V\u0117linas ([[Lithuanian mythology|Lithuanian]]), a devil of [[Baltic mythology]] and enemy of the Baltic thunder-god [[Perk\u016bnas]] (cf. Slavic ''Perun'').{{citation needed|date=September 2017}}\n\nWord Volos written in old Russian as ligature may be read Slovo b.o. which means word. Wherefrom derives the original Vedic meaning occulted in other languages of the opening chapter of the Gospel of John thus read In the beginning was Volos, and Volos was with God, and Wolos was God.\n\n==Enemy of Perun and storm myth==\nThe Russian [[philology|philologists]] [[Vyacheslav Ivanov (philologist)|Vyacheslav Ivanov]] and [[Vladimir Toporov]] reconstructed the mythical battle of Perun and Veles through comparative study of various Indo-European mythologies and a large number of Slavic folk stories and songs. A unifying characteristic of all Indo-European mythologies is a story about a battle between a god of thunder and a [[Slavic dragon|huge serpent or a dragon]]. In the Slavic version of the myth, Perun is a god of thunder, while Veles acts as a dragon who opposes him, consistent with the [[Vala (Vedic)|Vala]] etymology; he is also similar to the Etruscan underworld monster Vetha and to the dragon [[Illuyankas]], enemy of the [[Tarhunt|storm god]] of [[Hittites|Hittite]] mythology.\n\nThe reason for the enmity between the two gods is Veles's theft of Perun's son, wife, or, usually, cattle. It is also an act of challenge: Veles, in the form of a huge serpent, slithers from the caves of the underworld and coils upwards the Slavic world tree towards Perun's heavenly domain. Perun retaliates and attacks Veles with his lightning bolts. Veles flees, hiding or transforming himself into trees, animals or people. In the end, he is killed by Perun and in this ritual death, whatever Veles stole is released from his battered body in the form of rain falling from the skies. This \"storm myth\", or \"divine battle\", as it is generally called by scholars today, explained to ancient Slavs the changing of seasons through the year. The dry periods were interpreted as the chaotic results of Veles' thievery. Storms and lightning were seen as divine battles. The ensuing rain was the triumph of Perun over Veles and the re-establishment of world order. On a deeper level, as has been said above, Perun's place is up, high and dry and Veles' down, low and wet. By climbing up into the sphere of Perun, Veles disrupts the equilibrium of the world and needs to be put in his place. Perun does this in a fierce battle by smiting him with his lightning and drives him down into the water under the tree stub and the log and by putting him back in his place Perun restores order. Then they stop being adversaries and remain just opponents until the next time Veles tries to crawl up into Perun's realm.\n\nThe myth was cyclical, repeating itself each year. The death of Veles was never permanent; he would reform himself as a serpent who would shed its old skin and would be reborn in a new body. Although in this particular myth he plays a negative role as bringer of chaos, Veles was not seen as an evil god by ancient Slavs. In fact, in many of the Russian folk tales, Veles, appearing under the Christian guise of [[St. Nicholas]], saves the poor farmer and his cattle from the furious and destructive [[Elias|St. Elias]] the Thunderer, who, of course, represents Perun.{{efn |On rudiments of pagan cults in Slavic [[folk Christianity]] see: {{harv |\u0423\u0441\u043f\u0435\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 |1982 |ref=uspensky1982}}}}\nThe duality and conflict of Perun and Veles does not represent the dualistic clash of good and evil; rather, it is the opposition of the natural principles of earth and water (Veles) against heaven/sky and fire (Perun).\n\nThe Ivanov/Toporov conception of \"the key myth\" of Slavic mythology has been criticized by several authors, including [[Leo Klejn]]<ref>\u041a\u043b\u0435\u0439\u043d \u041b. \u0421. \u0412\u043e\u0441\u043a\u0440\u0435\u0448\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u041f\u0435\u0440\u0443\u043d\u0430. \u041a \u0440\u0435\u043a\u043e\u043d\u0441\u0442\u0440\u0443\u043a\u0446\u0438\u0438 \u0432\u043e\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0447\u043d\u043e\u0441\u043b\u0430\u0432\u044f\u043d\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u044f\u0437\u044b\u0447\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0430. \u2014 Saint Petersburg: \u0415\u0432\u0440\u0430\u0437\u0438\u044f, 2004.</ref> and [[Igor M. Diakonoff]].<ref>\u0414\u044c\u044f\u043a\u043e\u043d\u043e\u0432 \u0418. \u041c. \u0410\u0440\u0445\u0430\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0435 \u043c\u0438\u0444\u044b \u0412\u043e\u0441\u0442\u043e\u043a\u0430 \u0438 \u0417\u0430\u043f\u0430\u0434\u0430. Nauka, 1990</ref> Many, including Klejn, pointed out that Ivanov and Toporov often tended toward unjustified generalizations and considered many of their arguments \"far-fetched\". Supporters of the theory, on the other hand, include [[Boris Uspensky]], T. Sudnik and T. Tsivyan, and others.\n\n==God of magic and musicians==\nAccording to Ivanov and Toporov, Veles' portrayal as having a penchant for mischief is evident both from his role in the storm myth and in carnival customs of Koledari shamans. In his role as a [[trickster]] god, he is in some ways similar to both Greek [[Hermes]] and Scandinavian [[Loki]]. He was connected with magic. The word [[Volhv|''volhov'']], obviously derived from his name, in some Slavic languages still means sorcerer while in the 12th century Ruthenian epic [[The Tale of Igor's Campaign]], the character of Boyan the wizard is called Veles' grandson. Since magic was and is closely linked to music in many societies, particularly earlier ones{{citation needed|date=December 2018}}, Veles was also believed to be protector of travelling musicians. For instance, in some wedding ceremonies of northern [[Croatia]] (which continued up to the 20th century), the music would not start playing unless the bridegroom, when making a toast, spilled some of the wine on the ground, preferably over the roots of the nearest tree. The symbolism of this is clear, even though forgotten long ago by those still performing it: the musicians will not sing until a toast is made to their patron deity.<ref name=\"Belaj\"/>\n\n==Post-Christian Veles==\nAfter the advent of Christianity, Veles was split into several different characters. As a god of the underworld and dragons, he, of course, became identified with the [[Devil]]. His more benevolent sides were transformed to several Christian saints. As a protector of cattle, he became associated with [[Saint Blaise]], popularly known among various Slavic nations as St. Vlaho, St. Blaz, or St. Vlasiy. In [[Yaroslavl]], for example, the first church built on the site of Veles's pagan shrine was dedicated to St Blaise, for the latter's name was similar to Veles and he was likewise considered a heavenly patron of shepherds.<ref name=\"Rybakov\">[[Boris Rybakov]]. ''Ancient Slavic Paganism''. Moscow, 1981</ref> As mentioned already, in many Eastern Slavic folk tales, he was replaced by [[St. Nicholas]], probably because the popular stories of the saint describe him as a giver of wealth and a sort of a trickster.\n\n==Honors==\n[[Veles Bastion]] on [[Brabant Island]], Antarctica is named after the deity.<ref>[https://data.aad.gov.au/aadc/gaz/scar/display_name.cfm?gaz_id=137952 Veles Bastion.] SCAR [[Composite Antarctic Gazetteer]]</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Chaoskampf]], the battle between Indo-European thunder gods and their chaotic serpentine opponents\n* [[Golosov Ravine]]\u2014ancient Veles shrine in [[Moscow]], [[Russia]]\n* [[Jormungandr]], the world-serpent of Norse mythology\n* [[Typhon]], primordial serpent of Greco-Roman mythology\n* [[Vele\u017e Mountain]] in [[Herzegovina]]\n* [[Vritra]], brother of Vala in Hindu myth and enemy of Indra; he steals Usas, the rivers/waters, and cattle, which Indra must free\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\t \n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Slavic religion}}\n{{Slavic mythology}}\n{{hell}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Veles (God)}}\n[[Category:Slavic gods]]\n[[Category:Slovene mythology]]\n[[Category:Animal gods]]\n[[Category:Commerce gods]]\n[[Category:Death gods]]\n[[Category:Earth gods]]\n[[Category:Harvest gods]]\n[[Category:Magic gods]]\n[[Category:Pastoral gods]]\n[[Category:Trickster gods]]\n[[Category:Underworld gods]]\n[[Category:Volcano gods]]\n[[Category:Water gods]]\n[[Category:Dragons]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the city in [[North Macedonia|Macedonia]]|Veles, North Macedonia}}\n{{More citations needed|date=September 2009}}\n{{Infobox deity\n| name              = Veles\n| god_of            = underworld, earth, waters, fertility, trickery, cattle, pasture, snakes, bears, wolves, medicine, music, and magic\n| type              = Slavic\n| image             = File:Veles Volos.jpg\n| caption           = <small>''Veles'', Marek Hapon, 2014</small>\n| abode             = \n| symbol            = Bear, wolf, snake, dragon, owl, willow\n| consort           = \n| parents           = \n| siblings          = \n| children          = \n| mount             = \n| festivals         = The [[Festival of Veles]]\n| Canaanite_equivalent  = [[Baal]]\n| Slavic_equivalent = similar to [[Flins (deity)|Flins]], [[Triglav (deity)|Triglav]]\n}}\n[[File:Zbruch Triglav.PNG|thumb|upright|Probable image of Veles-[[Triglav (mythology)|Triglav]] from lower part of [[Zbruch Idol]]]]\n[[File:Symbol of Veles.svg|thumb|upright|Modern symbol of Veles, used by [[Slavic Native Faith|Rodnovers]]<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.slavorum.org/veles-the-slavic-shapeshifting-god-of-land-water-and-underground/ |title= Veles \u2013 The Slavic Shapeshifting God of Land, Water and Underground |author= Aleksandra Kojic |website= Slavorum |date= 2016-08-18 |access-date= 2017-09-08}}</ref>]]\n[[File:Vel\u00edz, Veles.jpg|thumb|upright|The modern statue of Veles on Vel\u00edz mountain, [[Czech Republic]]]]\n'''Veles''' ([[Cyrillic script|Cyrillic]] [[Bulgarian language|Bulgarian]], [[Macedonian language|Macedonian]], [[Serbian language|Serbian]] and [[Ukrainian language|Ukrainian]]: \u0412\u0435\u043b\u0435\u0441; {{lang-pl|Weles}}; [[Bosnian language|Bosnian]], [[Croatian language|Croatian]], [[Czech language|Czech]], [[Montenegrin language|Montenegrin]], [[Slovak language|Slovak]], [[Slovenian language|Slovenian]]: ''Veles''; [[Ruthenian language|Ruthenian]] and [[Old Church Slavonic]]: \u0412\u0435\u043b\u0435\u0441\u044a; {{lang-be|\u0412\u044f\u043b\u0435\u0441|translit=Vialies}}), also known as '''Volos''' ({{lang-ru|\u0412\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0441}}, \u0412\u043b\u0430\u0441, \u0412\u043b\u0430\u0441\u0438\u0439 listed as a Christian saint, Armenian: \u054d\u0578\u0582\u0580\u0562 \u054e\u056c\u0561\u057d\u056b; germ: Blasius; fr: Blaise; sp: San Blas; port: S\u00e3o Br\u00e1s; it: San Biagio; croat: sv. Bla\u017e; eng: Blase, Wallace;  Greek: \u0386\u03b3\u03b9\u03bf\u03c2 \u0392\u03bb\u03ac\u03c3\u03b9\u03bf\u03c2), is a major [[Slavic pantheon|Slavic god]] of earth, waters, and the [[underworld]]. His attributes are wet, wooly, hairy (bearded), dark and he is associated with cattle, the harvest, wealth, music, [[Magic (paranormal)|magic]], and [[trickster|trickery]]. Believed to be related to the [[Proto-Indo-European religion|Indo-European]] deity of [[Mitra]]. According to reconstruction by some researchers he is the opponent of the supreme [[thunder]] god [[Perun]].<ref name=katicic2008>{{cite book |last=[[Radoslav Kati\u010di\u0107|Kati\u010di\u0107]] |first=Radoslav |title=Bo\u017eanski boj: Tragovima svetih pjesama na\u0161e pretkr\u0161\u0107anske starine |year=2008 |publisher=IBIS GRAFIKA |location=Zagreb |isbn=978-953-6927-41-8 |url=http://ir.nmu.org.ua/bitstream/handle/123456789/120570/96db5654f2d3025b46454ace91716506.pdf |ref=katicic2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151018000746/http://ir.nmu.org.ua/bitstream/handle/123456789/120570/96db5654f2d3025b46454ace91716506.pdf |archivedate=2015-10-18 }}</ref>{{Rp|211\u2013214}} As such he probably has been imagined as a [[Slavic dragon|dragon]], which in the belief of the pagan Slavs is a [[Chimera (mythology)|chimeric]] being, a serpent with a bear's head and drooping hairy ears.<ref name=katicic2008/>{{Rp|141}}<ref name=uspensky1982>{{cite book |url=http://www.gumer.info/bibliotek_Buks/Culture/usp/02.php |title=\u0424\u0438\u043b\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0433\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0435 \u0440\u0430\u0437\u044b\u0441\u043a\u0430\u043d\u0438\u044f \u0432 \u043e\u0431\u043b\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0438 \u0441\u043b\u0430\u0432\u044f\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0445 \u0434\u0440\u0435\u0432\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0435\u0439. \u0420\u0435\u043b\u0438\u043a\u0442\u044b \u044f\u0437\u044b\u0447\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0430 \u0432 \u0432\u043e\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0447\u043d\u043e\u0441\u043b\u0430\u0432\u044f\u043d\u0441\u043a\u043e\u043c \u043a\u0443\u043b\u044c\u0442\u0435 \u041d\u0438\u043a\u043e\u043b\u0430\u044f \u041c\u0438\u0440\u0438\u043b\u0438\u043a\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e |publisher=[[Moscow State University]] |last=[[Boris Uspensky|\u0423\u0441\u043f\u0435\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439]] |first=\u0411\u043e\u0440\u0438\u0441 \u0410\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441\u0430\u043d\u0434\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447 |year=1982 |ref=uspensky1982}}</ref>{{Rp|87,88}} His tree is the willow much like Perun's tree is the oak.{{citation needed|date=December 2018}}\nNo direct accounts survive, but reconstructions speculate that he may directly continue aspects of the [[Proto-Indo-European pantheon]].{{citation needed|date=December 2018}}\n\n==Sources==\nVeles is one of few Slavic gods for which evidence of offerings can be found in all [[Slavic nations]]. The ''[[Primary Chronicle]]'', a historical record of the early [[Kievan Rus]], is the earliest and most important record, mentioning a god named Volos several times. Here, Volos is mentioned as god of cattle and peasants, who will punish oath-breakers with diseases, the opposite of Perun who is described as a ruling god of war who punishes by death in battle. In the later half of the 10th century, Veles or Volos was one of seven gods whose statues [[Vladimir I of Kiev]] had erected in his city. It is very interesting that Veles' statue apparently did not stand next to others, on the hill where the prince's castle was, but lower in the city, in the marketplace. Not only does this indicate that Veles was connected with commerce, but it also shows that worship of Perun and Veles had to be kept separate: while it was proper for Perun's shrines to be built high, on the top of the hill, Veles' place was down, in the lowlands.\n\nA similar pattern can be observed among the [[South Slavs]]. Here the name of Veles appears only in [[toponyms]], the best-known of which is the city of [[Veles, North Macedonia|Veles]] in [[North Macedonia|Macedonia]], over which looms a hill of St. [[Elijah|Elias]] the Thunderer. Also, in [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]], a part of [[Sarajevo]] is called Vele\u0161i\u0107i<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.novosarajevo.ba/stream/article.php?pid%3D118 |accessdate=September 12, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050308193444/http://www.novosarajevo.ba/stream/article.php?pid=118 |archivedate=March 8, 2005 |title=OPIS LOKACIJE MZ UNUTAR OP\u0106INE }}</ref> and a mountain Vele\u017e<ref>[[Vele\u017e (Bosnia and Herzegovina)]]</ref>{{Circular reference|date=November 2017}} near Mostar, Herzegovina. Other examples are Veles in Western Serbia, Velesnica on the Danube and Velestovo in [[Montenegro]] and also the township of Velestino (\u0392\u03b5\u03bb\u03b5\u03c3\u03c4\u03af\u03bd\u03bf, today \u03a6\u03ad\u03c1\u03b5\u03c2), apparently bearing testimony to a Slavic layer in the settlement of Thessaly. Another debatable if not improbable example<ref name=katicic2008/>{{Rp|178}}  is the town of [[Volosko]] in [[Croatia]], situated on the seashore under the peak of Mount [[U\u010dka]], [[nicknamed]] Perun.\n\nAmong [[Western Slavs]], the name can be principally found in 15th and 16th century [[Czech Republic|Czech]] records, where it means either [[dragon]] or [[devil]].\n\n==Etymology==\n[[File:The Mythology of all races (1918) (14578796339).jpg|thumb|\"Weles\" in wolf form, from ''The Mythology of All Races'' (1918).]]\nPresumably it is not possible to conclusively determine a definite etymology for the name of the god Veles, though there are several [[Proto-Indo-European language|Proto-Indo-European]] roots that are all closely related to the nature of Veles and his domains.\n\nOne possibility is that the name derives from the Proto-Indo-European root ''*wel-'', meaning wool.<ref name=\"Belaj\">Vitomir Belaj \"Hod kroz godinu, mitska pozadina hrvatskih narodnih vjerovanja i obicaja\", Golden Marketing, Zagreb 1998., {{ISBN|953-6168-43-X}}</ref> This seems plausible, since in Slavic cosmology Veles in serpentine form is lying in a nest of black wool in the roots of the Tree of the World<ref name=katicic2008/>{{Rp |136,154}} and Veles is the shepherd of the dead. ''Volos'' is also the Russian and Ukrainian word for \"hair\" and Veles is hairy in his beastly form (bear, wolf).\n\nThe Proto-Indo-European root ''*welg-'' also means humid, wet. Nothing is more connected with Veles than humidity and wetness. His domain is down, '\u0443 \u0432\u043e\u0434\u0443 \u043f\u043e\u0442 \u043a\u043e\u0440\u0447 \u043f\u043e\u0442 \u043a\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0434\u0443' (in the water, below the tree stump and the log). That is where Veles is in his place. English word wool has its root in Wolos too.\n\nThere is also the Indo-European word ''*woltus'' meaning meadow which is derived from the same root. And Veles is the shepherd of the dead who was imagined to browse the deceased on green lush meadows in the underworld.<ref name=katicic2008/>{{Rp |171}}<ref name=Ivanov_Toporov1973>{{cite journal |last1=[[Vyacheslav Ivanov (philologist)|Ivanov]] |first1=Vyacheslav | last2=[[Vladimir Toporov|Toporov]] | first2=Vladimir |title=A comparative study of the group of Baltic mythological terms from the root *vel- |year=1973 | publisher=baltistica T.9 Nr.(1) |url=http://www.baltistica.lt/index.php/baltistica/article/view/1802 |ref=Ivanov_Toporov1973}}</ref>\n\nThe name is also related to Slavic terminology for oxen, for which the South Slavs, Russians, and Poles use \"\u0432\u043e\u043b/vol/w\u00f3\u0142\".{{Citation needed|reason=reliable source needed for the whole sentence|date=December 2010}} Volos can also be a derivation from the same root by Eastern Slavic phonetic laws, now considered the most probable explanation for this phonetic form.<ref name=katicic2008/>{{Rp |171}} \n\nIt is probably the same as [[Vala (Vedic)|Vala]], the enemy of the [[Historical Vedic religion|Vedic]] thunder god [[Indra]] and to Velns ([[latvian mythology|Latvian]]) or V\u0117linas ([[Lithuanian mythology|Lithuanian]]), a devil of [[Baltic mythology]] and enemy of the Baltic thunder-god [[Perk\u016bnas]] (cf. Slavic ''Perun'').{{citation needed|date=September 2017}}\n\nWord Volos written in old Russian as ligature may be read Slovo b.o. which means word. Wherefrom derives the original Vedic meaning occulted in other languages of the opening chapter of the Gospel of John thus read In the beginning was Volos, and Volos was with God, and Wolos was God.\n\n==Enemy of Perun and storm myth==\nThe Russian [[philology|philologists]] [[Vyacheslav Ivanov (philologist)|Vyacheslav Ivanov]] and [[Vladimir Toporov]] reconstructed the mythical battle of Perun and Veles through comparative study of various Indo-European mythologies and a large number of Slavic folk stories and songs. A unifying characteristic of all Indo-European mythologies is a story about a battle between a god of thunder and a [[Slavic dragon|huge serpent or a dragon]]. In the Slavic version of the myth, Perun is a god of thunder, while Veles acts as a dragon who opposes him, consistent with the [[Vala (Vedic)|Vala]] etymology; he is also similar to the Etruscan underworld monster Vetha and to the dragon [[Illuyankas]], enemy of the [[Tarhunt|storm god]] of [[Hittites|Hittite]] mythology.\n\nThe reason for the enmity between the two gods is Veles's theft of Perun's son, wife, or, usually, cattle. It is also an act of challenge: Veles, in the form of a huge serpent, slithers from the caves of the underworld and coils upwards the Slavic world tree towards Perun's heavenly domain. Perun retaliates and attacks Veles with his lightning bolts. Veles flees, hiding or transforming himself into trees, animals or people. In the end, he is killed by Perun and in this ritual death, whatever Veles stole is released from his battered body in the form of rain falling from the skies. This \"storm myth\", or \"divine battle\", as it is generally called by scholars today, explained to ancient Slavs the changing of seasons through the year. The dry periods were interpreted as the chaotic results of Veles' thievery. Storms and lightning were seen as divine battles. The ensuing rain was the triumph of Perun over Veles and the re-establishment of world order. On a deeper level, as has been said above, Perun's place is up, high and dry and Veles' down, low and wet. By climbing up into the sphere of Perun, Veles disrupts the equilibrium of the world and needs to be put in his place. Perun does this in a fierce battle by smiting him with his lightning and drives him down into the water under the tree stub and the log and by putting him back in his place Perun restores order. Then they stop being adversaries and remain just opponents until the next time Veles tries to crawl up into Perun's realm.\n\nThe myth was cyclical, repeating itself each year. The death of Veles was never permanent; he would reform himself as a serpent who would shed its old skin and would be reborn in a new body. Although in this particular myth he plays a negative role as bringer of chaos, Veles was not seen as an evil god by ancient Slavs. In fact, in many of the Russian folk tales, Veles, appearing under the Christian guise of [[St. Nicholas]], saves the poor farmer and his cattle from the furious and destructive [[Elias|St. Elias]] the Thunderer, who, of course, represents Perun.{{efn |On rudiments of pagan cults in Slavic [[folk Christianity]] see: {{harv |\u0423\u0441\u043f\u0435\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 |1982 |ref=uspensky1982}}}}\nThe duality and conflict of Perun and Veles does not represent the dualistic clash of good and evil; rather, it is the opposition of the natural principles of earth and water (Veles) against heaven/sky and fire (Perun).\n\nThe Ivanov/Toporov conception of \"the key myth\" of Slavic mythology has been criticized by several authors, including [[Leo Klejn]]<ref>\u041a\u043b\u0435\u0439\u043d \u041b. \u0421. \u0412\u043e\u0441\u043a\u0440\u0435\u0448\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u041f\u0435\u0440\u0443\u043d\u0430. \u041a \u0440\u0435\u043a\u043e\u043d\u0441\u0442\u0440\u0443\u043a\u0446\u0438\u0438 \u0432\u043e\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0447\u043d\u043e\u0441\u043b\u0430\u0432\u044f\u043d\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u044f\u0437\u044b\u0447\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0430. \u2014 Saint Petersburg: \u0415\u0432\u0440\u0430\u0437\u0438\u044f, 2004.</ref> and [[Igor M. Diakonoff]].<ref>\u0414\u044c\u044f\u043a\u043e\u043d\u043e\u0432 \u0418. \u041c. \u0410\u0440\u0445\u0430\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0435 \u043c\u0438\u0444\u044b \u0412\u043e\u0441\u0442\u043e\u043a\u0430 \u0438 \u0417\u0430\u043f\u0430\u0434\u0430. Nauka, 1990</ref> Many, including Klejn, pointed out that Ivanov and Toporov often tended toward unjustified generalizations and considered many of their arguments \"far-fetched\". Supporters of the theory, on the other hand, include [[Boris Uspensky]], T. Sudnik and T. Tsivyan, and others.\n\n==God of magic and musicians==\nAccording to Ivanov and Toporov, Veles' portrayal as having a penchant for mischief is evident both from his role in the storm myth and in carnival customs of Koledari shamans. In his role as a [[trickster]] god, he is in some ways similar to both Greek [[Hermes]] and Scandinavian [[Loki]]. He was connected with magic. The word [[Volhv|''volhov'']], obviously derived from his name, in some Slavic languages still means sorcerer while in the 12th century Ruthenian epic [[The Tale of Igor's Campaign]], the character of Boyan the wizard is called Veles' grandson. Since magic was and is closely linked to music in many societies, particularly earlier ones{{citation needed|date=December 2018}}, Veles was also believed to be protector of travelling musicians. For instance, in some wedding ceremonies of northern [[Croatia]] (which continued up to the 20th century), the music would not start playing unless the bridegroom, when making a toast, spilled some of the wine on the ground, preferably over the roots of the nearest tree. The symbolism of this is clear, even though forgotten long ago by those still performing it: the musicians will not sing until a toast is made to their patron deity.<ref name=\"Belaj\"/>\n\n==Post-Christian Veles==\nAfter the advent of Christianity, Veles was split into several different characters. As a god of the underworld and dragons, he, of course, became identified with the [[Devil]]. His more benevolent sides were transformed to several Christian saints. As a protector of cattle, he became associated with [[Saint Blaise]], popularly known among various Slavic nations as St. Vlaho, St. Blaz, or St. Vlasiy. In [[Yaroslavl]], for example, the first church built on the site of Veles's pagan shrine was dedicated to St Blaise, for the latter's name was similar to Veles and he was likewise considered a heavenly patron of shepherds.<ref name=\"Rybakov\">[[Boris Rybakov]]. ''Ancient Slavic Paganism''. Moscow, 1981</ref> As mentioned already, in many Eastern Slavic folk tales, he was replaced by [[St. Nicholas]], probably because the popular stories of the saint describe him as a giver of wealth and a sort of a trickster.\n\n==Honors==\n[[Veles Bastion]] on [[Brabant Island]], Antarctica is named after the deity.<ref>[https://data.aad.gov.au/aadc/gaz/scar/display_name.cfm?gaz_id=137952 Veles Bastion.] SCAR [[Composite Antarctic Gazetteer]]</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Chaoskampf]], the battle between Indo-European thunder gods and their chaotic serpentine opponents\n* [[Golosov Ravine]]\u2014ancient Veles shrine in [[Moscow]], [[Russia]]\n* [[Jormungandr]], the world-serpent of Norse mythology\n* [[Typhon]], primordial serpent of Greco-Roman mythology\n* [[Vele\u017e Mountain]] in [[Herzegovina]]\n* [[Vritra]], brother of Vala in Hindu myth and enemy of Indra; he steals Usas, the rivers/waters, and cattle, which Indra must free\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\t \n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Slavic religion}}\n{{Slavic mythology}}\n{{hell}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Veles (God)}}\n[[Category:Slavic gods]]\n[[Category:Slovene mythology]]\n[[Category:Animal gods]]\n[[Category:Commerce gods]]\n[[Category:Death gods]]\n[[Category:Earth gods]]\n[[Category:Harvest gods]]\n[[Category:Magic gods]]\n[[Category:Pastoral gods]]\n[[Category:Trickster gods]]\n[[Category:Underworld gods]]\n[[Category:Volcano gods]]\n[[Category:Water gods]]\n[[Category:Dragons]]\n", "name_user": "Srnec", "label": "safe", "comment": "WP:NAMB", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Veles_(god)"}
{"title_page": "Tatsuro Yamashita", "text_new": "{{Expand Japanese|\u5c71\u4e0b\u9054\u90ce|date=January 2014}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name             = Tatsur\u014d Yamashita\n| image            = \n| caption          = Tatsuro Yamashita, 2018\n| birth_name       = {{nihongo|Yamashita Tatsur\u014d|\u5c71\u4e0b \u9054\u90ce}}\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|1953|2|4|mf=y}}<ref name=\"tatsuro\">{{cite web |title=Biography |url=https://www.tatsuro.co.jp/biography/ |website=tatsuro.co.jp |publisher=Smile Company Ltd. |accessdate=2 December 2019}}</ref>\n| death_date       = \n| birth_place      = [[Ikebukuro]], [[Toshima, Tokyo (ward)|Toshima]], [[Tokyo|T\u014dky\u014d-to]], [[Japan]]<ref name=\"tatsuro\"/>\n| occupation       = [[Singer-songwriter]], [[record producer]]\n| spouse           = {{marriage|[[Mariya Takeuchi]]|1982}}\n| children         = 1\n| module = {{Infobox musical artist|embed=yes\n| background       = solo_singer\n| genre            = [[Rock music|Rock]], [[Pop music|pop]], [[kay\u014dkyoku]], [[city pop]], [[soul music|soul]], [[R&B]]\n| years_active     = 1973-present\n| instrument       = [[Singing|Vocals]], [[guitar]]s, [[piano]], [[Keyboard (music)|keyboards]], [[Drum kit|drums]], [[Percussion instrument|percussion]]\n| label            = AIR, Moon, Niagara, Elec, [[RCA]], RVC, [[Warner Music Japan]], [[Nippon Columbia]], EastWest Japan, MMG\n| associated_acts  = Sugar Babe, [[Mariya Takeuchi]], [[Haruomi Hosono]], [[Ryuichi Sakamoto]], [[Eiichi Ohtaki]]\n}}\n| image            = Tatsuro Yamashita autograph.svg\n| caption          = Tatsuro Yamashita's autograph\n| website          = {{URL|https://tatsuro.co.jp}}\n}}\n\n{{nihongo|'''Tatsur\u014d Yamashita'''|\u5c71\u4e0b \u9054\u90ce|Yamashita Tatsur\u014d|born February 4, 1953}}, occasionally credited as '''Tatsu Yamashita'''<ref>{{cite AV media notes |title= Ride on Time (album)|others= Tatsuro Yamashita|year= 1980|type= LP front cover|publisher= [[Bertelsmann Music Group|BMG]]Japan}}</ref> or '''Tats Yamashita''',<ref>{{cite AV media notes |title= Big Wave (Tatsuro Yamashita album)|others= Tatsuro Yamashita|year= 1984|type= LP sleevenotes|publisher= [[Warner Music Group|Warner]]/Moon Records}}</ref> is a [[Japanese people|Japanese]] [[singer-songwriter]] and [[record producer]] who helped pioneer the style of Japanese [[Soft rock|adult-oriented rock/soft rock]] dubbed \"[[city pop]]\".<ref name=\"thejapantimes1\">{{cite news |last1=Hadfield |first1=James |title='Pacific Breeze' collates the slick sound of Japanese city pop |url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/culture/2019/05/01/music/pacific-breeze-collates-slick-sound-japanese-city-pop/ |accessdate=22 November 2019 |publisher=The Japan Times |date=1 May 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"radiomilwaukee\">{{cite news |last1=Doucette |first1=Marcus |title=The unforgettable funk of \u201970s and \u201980s Japanese City Pop |url=https://radiomilwaukee.org/discover-music/sound-travels/japanese-city-pop/ |accessdate=22 November 2019 |publisher=Radio Milwaukee |date=19 February 2019}}</ref> Yamashita produced much city pop music during the 1970s{{ndash}}1980s, and is sometimes considered the \"king\" of the genre.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ed Motta drops exclusive City Pop Vol. 2 mixtape of smooth and funky Japanese AOR - Wax Poetics |url=http://www.waxpoetics.com/blog/music/mixtape/ed-motta-drops-exclusive-city-pop-vol-2-mixtape-smooth-funky-japanese-aor/ |work=[[Wax Poetics]] |date=April 28, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"redbullmusicacademy\"/> He has also collaborated with his wife [[Mariya Takeuchi]], another city pop singer.<ref name=\"thejapantimes2\">{{cite news |last1=St. Michel |first1=Patrick |title=Mariya Takeuchi: The pop genius behind 2018's surprise online smash hit from Japan |url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/culture/2018/11/17/music/mariya-takeuchi-pop-genius-behind-2018s-surprise-online-smash-hit-japan/ |accessdate=22 November 2019 |publisher=The Japan Times |date=17 November 2018}}</ref>\n\nYamashita is also known for the song \"Christmas Eve\", which initially appeared on his album ''[[Melodies (Tatsuro Yamashita album)|Melodies]]'' in 1983 and later became a hit throughout the decades.<ref name=\"christmaseve\">{{cite web| url=http://www.oricon.co.jp/news/ranking/5892/ | title = \u5c71\u4e0b\u9054\u90ce\u3001\u300c\u30af\u30ea\u30b9\u30de\u30b9\u30fb\u30a4\u30d6\u300d\u3067\u5927\u8a18\u9332\u6a39\u7acb\uff01\u300020\u5e74\u9023\u7d9aTOP100\u5165\u308a\uff01 \u30cb\u30e5\u30fc\u30b9-ORICON STYLE-|trans-title=Tatsuro Yamashita's \"Christmas Eve\" set a record! : entering the top 100 on the chart for 20 consecutive years |work=oricon.co.jp|publisher= [[Original Confidence]]|language= Japanese|accessdate=2009-06-26}}</ref><ref name=\"JP1\">[http://www18.ocn.ne.jp/~hbr/JP1_e.htm List of number-one singles on the Japan's Oricon Weekly Charts (1968-)]</ref> It is considered one of the standard Japanese [[Christmas song]]s, winning the Special Prize at the [[45th Japan Record Awards|45th]] [[Japan Record Award]]s 20 years after its release.<ref name=\"45rt\">{{cite web|url=http://www.jacompa.or.jp/45th_awards/tokubetsusyou.html|publisher=Japan Composer's Association|title=The 45th Japan Record Award - Special Prizes winners|language=Japanese|accessdate=2009-08-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070907172758/http://www.jacompa.or.jp/45th_awards/tokubetsusyou.html|archive-date=2007-09-07|url-status=dead}}</ref> In 2007, ''[[Rolling Stone|Rolling Stone Japan]]'' ranked his album ''Spacy'' number 14 on a list of the greatest Japanese rock albums of all time.<ref>{{cite web |title=Finally! \"The 100 Greatest Japanese Rock Albums of All Time\" Listed |url=http://exclaim.ca/News/finally_100_greatest_japanese_rock_albums_of_all_time |work=[[Exclaim!]] |date=2007-11-14 |accessdate=2020-01-02}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nIn 1973, Yamashita formed the band Sugar Babe with musicians including [[Taeko Ohnuki]] and Kunio Muramatsu, and released their sole album ''Songs'' two years later in 1975.<ref name=\"sugarbabebio\">{{cite web|url= http://music.yahoo.co.jp/shop/p/12/22606/|title= Yahoo!\u30df\u30e5\u30fc\u30b8\u30c3\u30af - SUGAR BABE - \u30a2\u30fc\u30c6\u30a3\u30b9\u30c8\u60c5\u5831|trans-title= Yahoo!Music - Sugar Babe - Artist Information|work= music.yahoo.co.jp|publisher= Listen Japan|accessdate= 2009-06-28|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20060527180409/http://music.yahoo.co.jp/shop/p/12/22606|archive-date= 2006-05-27|url-status= dead}}</ref><ref name=\"tatsuro\"/> After the group disbanded in 1976, Yamashita signed to RCA and launched his own career, with release of the solo album ''Circus Town'' the same year. Also the same year he teamed up with [[Eiichi Ohtaki]], who was the producer of Sugar Babe,<ref>{{cite web |title=Happy End's Eiichi Ohtaki Dies at 65 |url=http://exclaim.ca/music/article/happy_ends_eiichi_ohtaki_dies_at_65 |work=[[Exclaim!]] |date=2013-12-31 |accessdate=2017-01-09}}</ref> and brief Sugar Babe member Ginji Ito to release an album titled ''Niagara Triangle Vol. 1'' that was cited by [[MTV]] as one of the finest collaborative efforts from that period.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv81.com/features/lists/6-japanese-super-groups-that-are-changing-j-music-history/|title=6 Japanese Super Groups That are Changing J-music History|publisher=[[MTV81]]|date=2016-03-16|accessdate=2017-01-09}}</ref> His 1979 [[Japan Record Award|award-winning]] album ''Moonglow'' gained moderate success,<ref name=\"22rt\">{{cite web|url=http://www.jacompa.or.jp/rekishi/d1980.htm|publisher=Japan Composer's Association|title=History of the Japan Record Awards - List of the 20th Award Winners|language=Japanese|accessdate=2008-12-28|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080611055622/http://www.jacompa.or.jp/rekishi/d1980.htm|archivedate=2008-06-11}}</ref> but his 1980 song \"Ride on Time\" peaked at #3 on the Japanese Oricon and the same-titled album topped the chart subsequently,<ref name=\"goodluck\">{{cite web|url= http://www.tbs.co.jp/goodluck/themesong.html|title= Description of the theme song for the television drama aired on TBS in 2003|work= tbs.co.jp|publisher= [[Tokyo Broadcasting System]]|language= Japanese|accessdate= 2009-06-26|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20090406223507/http://www.tbs.co.jp/goodluck/themesong.html|archive-date= 2009-04-06|url-status= dead}}</ref><ref name=\"jpno1album80s\">{{cite web|url=http://www007.upp.so-net.ne.jp/k-makoto/datastation/music/oricon/oriconalbum80.htm|script-title=ja:\u30aa\u30ea\u30b3\u30f3\u30fb\u30d2\u30c3\u30c8\u30c1\u30e3\u30fc\u30c8\u3000\uff2e\uff4f\uff0e\uff11\uff21\uff2c\uff22\uff35\uff2d \uff11\uff19\uff18\uff10\uff0d\uff11\uff19\uff18\uff19 -|trans-title=List of the number-one on the Japanese Weekly LP Chart from 1980 to 1989|language=Japanese|accessdate=2009-06-26|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090504085533/http://www007.upp.so-net.ne.jp/k-makoto/datastation/music/oricon/oriconalbum80.htm|archivedate=2009-05-04}}</ref><ref name=\"redbullmusicacademy\">{{cite news |last1=Yokegawa |first1=Tetsuko |title=The Artisian: The Inimitable Genius of Tatsuro Yamashita |url=https://daily.redbullmusicacademy.com/2014/12/tatsuro-yamashita-feature |accessdate=22 November 2019 |publisher=Red Bull Music Academy |date=10 December 2014}}</ref> propelling him to stardom.<ref name=\"tatsuro\"/>\n\nAs a solo artist, Yamashita has released 17 studio albums, 2 live albums, multiple compilations and over 40 singles. He has been one of the most commercially successful Japanese male solo recording artists in the history of the Japanese album chart, selling approximately 9 million albums in total.<ref name=\"makihara\">{{cite web|url=http://www.oricon.co.jp/news/ranking/15054/ | title=\u69c7\u539f\u656c\u4e4b\u3001\u4e95\u4e0a\u967d\u6c34\u629c\u304f\uff01\u30a2\u30eb\u30d0\u30e0\u7dcf\u58f2\u4e0a\u679a\u6570\u7537\u6027\u30bd\u30ed\u6b74\u4ee31\u4f4d\u306b\uff01|trans-title=Noriyuki Makihara become the best-selling male solo artist on the Oricon albums chart, defeating Yosui Inoue|accessdate=2009-05-09}}</ref><ref name=\"oricon album\">{{cite web | url=http://www7a.biglobe.ne.jp/~yamag/album/al_yamasita.html | title=Yamachan Land (Japan's charts archives)  - Albums Chart Daijiten | language=Japanese | accessdate=2008-03-19 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://archive.is/20071111034222/http://www7a.biglobe.ne.jp/~yamag/album/al_yamasita.html | archivedate=2007-11-11 }}</ref> He has also composed for films and television commercials, and worked on records by other artists. He is particularly successful as a musical collaborator for [[Mariya Takeuchi]], whom he married in 1982. They have one daughter.<ref name=\"takeuchibio\">{{cite web| url=http://www.wmg.jp/artist/mariya/profile.html | script-title=ja:\u30d7\u30ed\u30d5\u30a3\u30fc\u30eb  \u7af9\u5185 \u307e\u308a\u3084  \u30ef\u30fc\u30ca\u30fc\u30df\u30e5\u30fc\u30b8\u30c3\u30af\u30fb\u30b8\u30e3\u30d1\u30f3 |trans-title=Biography of Mariya Takeuchi|work=wmg.jp|publisher= [[Warner Music Group]]|language= Japanese |accessdate=2009-06-26}}</ref>\n\n== Discography ==\n\n=== Studio albums ===\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n!Year\n!Album\n!Chart positions<br />([[Oricon|JP]])<ref name=\"oricon album\" />\n!Label\n!Notes\n|-\n|1976\n|''[[Circus Town]]''\n|align=\"center\"|27\n|rowspan=\"4\" align=\"center\"|RVC/RCA\n|rowspan=\"3\"|Peaked the chart at the time of 2002 reissue\n|-\n|1977\n|''[[Spacy (album)|Spacy]]''\n|align=\"center\"|29\n|-\n|1978\n|''[[Go Ahead!]]''\n|align=\"center\"|25\n|-\n|1979\n|''[[Moonglow (Tatsuro Yamashita album)|Moonglow]]''\n|align=\"center\"|20\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|1980\n|''[[Ride On Time (album)|Ride On Time]]''\n|align=\"center\"|1\n|rowspan=\"3\" align=\"center\"|RVC/AIR\n|\n|-\n|''[[On the Street Corner]]''\n|align=\"center\"|13\n|Expanded edition was reissued in later years\n|-\n|1982\n|''[[For You (Tatsuro Yamashita album)|For You]]''\n|align=\"center\"|1\n|\n|-\n|1983\n|''[[Melodies (Tatsuro Yamashita album)|Melodies]]''\n|align=\"center\"|1\n|rowspan=\"5\" align=\"center\"|[[Alfa Records|Alfa Moon]]\n|\n|-\n|1984\n|''[[Big Wave (Tatsuro Yamashita album)|Big Wave]]''\n|align=\"center\"|2\n|Soundtrack for the same-titled motion picture\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|1986\n|''[[Pocket Music (album)|Pocket Music]]''\n|align=\"center\"|1\n|\n|-\n|''[[On the Street Corner 2]]''\n|align=\"center\"|3\n|\n|-\n|1988\n|{{nihongo|''[[Boku no Naka no Shounen]]''|\u50d5\u306e\u4e2d\u306e\u5c11\u5e74}}\n|align=\"center\"|1\n|\n|-\n|1991\n|''[[Artisan (album)|Artisan]]''\n|align=\"center\"|1\n|rowspan=\"2\" align=\"center\"|Moon/MMG\n|\n|-\n|1993\n|''[[Season's Greetings (album)|Season's Greetings]]''\n|align=\"center\"|4\n|align=\"center\"|Christmas Album\n|-\n|1998\n|''[[Cozy (Tatsuro Yamashita album)|Cozy]]''\n|align=\"center\"|1\n|rowspan=\"4\" align=\"center\"|Moon/[[Warner Music Group|Warner]]\n|\n|-\n|1999\n|''[[On the Street Corner 3]]''\n|align=\"center\"|4\n|\n|-\n|2005\n|''[[Sonorite]]''\n|align=\"center\"|2\n|\n|-\n|2011\n|''Ray of Hope''\n|align=\"center\"|1\n|\n|-\n|}\n\n==== Albums recorded with other musicians ====\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n!Year\n!Album\n!Chart positions<br />([[Oricon|JP]])<ref name=\"oricon album2\">{{cite web |url= http://www.oricon.co.jp/search/result.php?cd=22606&types=art&media=album | title=\u691c\u7d22\u7d50\u679c-ORICON STYLE \u30a2\u30fc\u30c6\u30a3\u30b9\u30c8/CD\u691c\u7d22 \u30b7\u30e5\u30ac\u30fc\u30fb\u30d9\u30a4\u30d6|trans-title=Searching results albums by Sugar Babe (available only 1989 to present)|language=Japanese|accessdate=2009-05-20|publisher= Original confidence|work= oricon.co.jp}}</ref><ref name=\"oricon album3\">{{cite web |url= http://www.oricon.co.jp/search/result.php?cd=341317&types=art&media=album | title=\u691c\u7d22\u7d50\u679c-ORICON STYLE \u30a2\u30fc\u30c6\u30a3\u30b9\u30c8/CD\u691c\u7d22 \u5c71\u4e0b\u9054\u90ce\uff0c\u4f0a\u85e4\u9280\u6b21\uff0c\u5927\u7027\u8a60\u4e00|trans-title=Searching results albums by Tatsuro Yamashita, Ginji Ito, Eiichi Otaki (available only 1989 to present)|language=Japanese|accessdate=2009-05-20|publisher= Original confidence|work= oricon.co.jp}}</ref>\n!Label\n!Notes\n|-\n|1975\n|''[[Songs (Sugar Babe album)|Songs]]''\n|align=\"center\"|3\n|align=\"center\"|Elec/Niagara\n|\n* The only studio album by the band Sugar Babe\n* Peaked the chart at the time of 1994 reissue\n|-\n|1976\n|''Niagara Triangle Vol.1''<br /><small>(with [[Eiichi Ohtaki]] and Ginji Ito)</small>\n|align=\"center\"|63\n|align=\"center\"|Niagara/[[Columbia Music Entertainment|Columbia]]\n|\n* Peaked the chart at the time of reissue\n|-\n|1978\n|''[[Pacific (1978 album)|Pacific]]''<br /><small>(with [[Haruomi Hosono]] and [[Shigeru Suzuki]])</small>\n|align=\"center\"|\n|align=\"center\"|[[CBS]]/[[Sony]]\n|\n* First album in the CBS/Sony Sound Image Series\n|}\n\n<!--\n==== Albums recorded with other musicians ====\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n!Year\n!Album\n!Chart positions<br />([[Oricon|JP]])<ref name=\"oricon album2\"/><ref name=\"oricon album3\"/>\n!Label\n!Notes\n|-\n|1975\n|''[[Songs (Sugar Babe album)|Songs]]''\n|align=\"center\"|3\n|align=\"center\"|Elec/Niagara\n|\n* The only studio album by the band Sugar Babe\n* Peaked the chart at the time of 1994 reissue\n|-\n|1976\n|''Niagara Triangle Vol.1''<br /><small>(with Ei-ichi \u014ctaki and Ginji Ito)</small>\n|align=\"center\"|63\n|align=\"center\"|Niagara/[[Columbia Music Entertainment|Columbia]]\n|\n* Peaked the chart at the time of reissue\n|-\n|}\n==== Albums recorded with other musicians ====\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n!Year\n!Album\n!Chart positions<br />([[Oricon|JP]])<ref name=\"oricon album2\">{{cite web |url= http://moe-alternative.net/?p=9112 | title=\u691c\u7d22\u7d50\u679c-ORICON STYLE \u30a2\u30fc\u30c6\u30a3\u30b9\u30c8/CD\u691c\u7d22 \u30b7\u30e5\u30ac\u30fc\u30fb\u30d9\u30a4\u30d6|trans-title=Searching results albums by Sugar Babe (available only 1989 to present)|language=Japanese|accessdate=2009-05-20|publisher= Original confidence|work= oricon.co.jp}}</ref><ref name=\"oricon album3\">{{cite web |url= http://www.oricon.co.jp/search/result.php?cd=341317&types=art&media=album | title=\u691c\u7d22\u7d50\u679c-ORICON STYLE \u30a2\u30fc\u30c6\u30a3\u30b9\u30c8/CD\u691c\u7d22 \u5c71\u4e0b\u9054\u90ce\uff0c\u4f0a\u85e4\u9280\u6b21\uff0c\u5927\u7027\u8a60\u4e00|trans-title=Searching results albums by Tatsuro Yamashita, Ginji Ito, Eiichi Otaki (available only 1989 to present)|language=Japanese|accessdate=2009-05-20|publisher= Original confidence|work= oricon.co.jp}}</ref>\n!Label\n!Notes[http://bloginfo.co.kr/21 .]\n|-\n|1975\n|''Pacific''\n|align=\"center\"|3\n|align=\"center\"|Elec/Niagara\n|\n* The only studio album by the band Sugar Babe\n* Peaked the chart at the time of 1994 reissue\n|-\n|1976\n|''Niagara Triangle Vol.1''<br /><small>(with Ei-ichi \u014ctaki and Ginji Ito)</small>\n|align=\"center\"|63\n|align=\"center\"|Niagara/[[Columbia Music Entertainment|Columbia]]\n-->\n\n=== Live albums ===\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n!Year\n!Album\n!Chart positions<br />([[Oricon|JP]])<ref name=\"oricon album 2\">{{cite web | url=http://www7a.biglobe.ne.jp/~yamag/album/al_yamasita.html | title=Yamachan Land (Japan's charts archives)  - Albumd Chart Daijiten | language=Japanese | accessdate=2008-03-19 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://archive.is/20071111034222/http://www7a.biglobe.ne.jp/~yamag/album/al_yamasita.html | archivedate=2007-11-11 }}</ref>\n!Label\n!Notes\n|-\n|1978\n|''[[It's a Poppin' Time]]''\n|align=\"center\"|28\n|align=\"center\"|RCA/Air\n|Peaked the chart at the time of 2002 reissue\n|-\n|1989\n|''[[Joy: Tatsuro Yamashita Live]]''\n|align=\"center\"|3\n|align=\"center\"|Alfa Moon\n|Double album\n|-\n|}\n\n=== Compilation albums ===\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n!Year\n!Album\n!Chart positions<br />([[Oricon|JP]])<ref name=\"oricon album\"/>\n!Label\n!Notes\n|-\n|1980\n|''Tatsuro from Niagara''\n|align=\"center\"|37\n|rowspan=\"center\"|Niagara/[[Columbia Music Entertainment|Columbia]]\n|Peaked the chart at the time of 2009 reissue\n|-\n|1982\n|''[[Greatest Hits! (Tatsuro Yamashita album)|Greatest Hits! of Tatsuro Yamashita]]''\n|align=\"center\"|2\n|rowspan=\"8\" align=\"center\"|RVC/AIR\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\" align=\"center\"|1980\n|''Come Along''\n|align=\"center\"|32\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\" align=\"center\"|1984\n|''Come Along II''\n|align=\"center\"|8\n|\n|-\n|1985\n|''Tatsuro Collection''\n|align=\"center\"|35\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\" align=\"center\"|1986\n|''Ballad for You''\n|align=\"center\"|37\n|\n|-\n|''Rock'n Funk Tatsu''\n|align=\"center\"|59\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\" align=\"center\"|1990\n|''Best Pack I (1976\u20131979)''\n|align=\"center\"|\u2014\n|\n|-\n|''Best Pack II (1979\u20131982)''\n|align=\"center\"|\u2014\n|\n|-\n|1995\n|''[[Treasures (Tatsuro Yamashita album)|Treasures]]''\n|align=\"center\"|1\n|align=\"center\"|[[East West Records|Moon/East West]]\n|\n|-\n|2002\n|''[[Rarities (Tatsuro Yamashita album)|Rarities]]''\n|align=\"center\"|1\n|rowspan=\"3\" align=\"center\"|Moon/Warner\n|\n|-\n|2012\n|''[[Opus (All Time Best 1975-2012)]]''\n|align=\"center\"|1\n|<ref name=\"hmv\">{{cite news |last1=\u7530\u4ee3 |first1=\u8cb4\u4e4b |title=HMV\u30a4\u30f3\u30bf\u30d3\u30e5\u30fc\u3011 \u5c71\u4e0b\u9054\u90ce \u300eOPUS \uff5eALL TIME BEST 1975-2012\uff5e\u300f Facebook |url=https://www.hmv.co.jp/news/article/1208200027/ |accessdate=22 November 2019 |publisher=HMV |date=14 September 2012}}</ref>\n|-\n|2017\n|''Come Along III''\n|align=\"center\"|\u2014\n|\n|-\n|}\n\n=== Other releases ===\nFollowing materials are not marketed to the record retailers, though they have been available via mail order to his official [[fan club]].<ref name=\"fanclub\">{{cite web |url=http://www.tatsuro.co.jp/fan/ |title=\u5c71\u4e0b\u9054\u90ce OFFICIAL WEB SITE: \u30d5\u30a1\u30f3\u30af\u30e9\u30d6\u901a\u8ca9CD |website=tatsuro.co.jp |language=ja |accessdate=2015-07-30}}</ref>\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n!Album\n!Label\n!Footnotes\n|-\n|''Add Some Music to Your Day''\n|rowspan=\"4\" align=\"center\"|Wild Honey\n|\n* [[Cover album]] that Yamashita and his friends produced and released independently in 1972\n|-\n|''The Works of Tatsuro Yamashita Vol.1''\n|\n* Compilation comprises his compositions written for other artists\n|-\n|''Tatsuro Yamashita CM Collection Vol.1''\n|rowspan=\"2\"|\n* Compilation comprises materials originally used in the advertisements and never issued on his official releases\n|-\n|''Tatsuro Yamashita CM Collection Vol.2''\n|-\n|}\n\n=== Singles ===\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n!Year\n!A-Side\n!B-Side(s) / Double A-Side<br /><ref name=\"singlediscography1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.tatsuro.co.jp/disco/single_01.html |title=\u5c71\u4e0b\u9054\u90ce OFFICIAL WEBSITE {{pipe}} DISCOGRAPHY {{pipe}} SINGLE Part 1 |website=tatsuro.co.jp |language=ja |accessdate=2015-07-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150720201434/http://www.tatsuro.co.jp/disco/single_01.html |archive-date=2015-07-20 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=\"singlediscography2\">{{cite web |url=http://www.tatsuro.co.jp/disco/single_02.html |title=\u5c71\u4e0b\u9054\u90ce OFFICIAL WEBSITE {{pipe}} DISCOGRAPHY {{pipe}} SINGLE Part 2 |website=tatsuro.co.jp |language=ja |accessdate=2015-07-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150801110534/http://www.tatsuro.co.jp/disco/single_02.html |archive-date=2015-08-01 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=\"singlediscography3\">{{cite web |url=http://www.tatsuro.co.jp/disco/single_03.html |title=\u5c71\u4e0b\u9054\u90ce OFFICIAL WEBSITE {{pipe}} DISCOGRAPHY {{pipe}} SINGLE Part 3 |website=tatsuro.co.jp |language=ja |accessdate=2015-07-29}}</ref>\n\n!Chart positions<br />([[Oricon|JP]])<ref name=\"oricon single\">{{cite web | url=http://www7a.biglobe.ne.jp/~yamag/single/yamasita.html|website=Yamachan Land (Japan's charts archives)  - Singles Chart Daijiten - | title=Tatsuro Yamashita | language=Japanese | accessdate=2009-07-01 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https