of the 30th Award Winners|language=Japanese|accessdate=2009-08-04|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080615042153/http://www.jacompa.or.jp/rekishi/d1988.htm|archivedate=2008-06-15}}</ref>\n|align=\"left\"|Excellent Albums\n|<small>(Songwriter, producer, arranger, performer: Yamashita)</small>\n|-\n|!align=\"center\"|1991 <small>(33rd)</small>\n|align=\"left\"|''Artisan''<ref name=\"33rt\">{{cite web|url=http://www.jacompa.or.jp/rekishi/d1991.htm |publisher=Japan Composer's Association|title=History of the Japan Record Awards - List of the 33rd Award Winners|language=Japanese|accessdate=2009-08-04|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080615040106/http://www.jacompa.or.jp/rekishi/d1991.htm|archivedate=2008-06-15}}</ref>\n|align=\"left\"|Excellent Albums\n|<small>(Songwriter, producer, arranger, performer: Yamashita)</small>\n|-\n|!align=\"center\"|1993 <small>(35th)</small>\n|align=\"left\"|''Quiet Life''<ref name=\"35rt\">{{cite web|url=http://www.jacompa.or.jp/rekishi/d1993.htm|publisher=Japan Composer's Association|title=History of the Japan Record Awards - List of the 35th Award Winners|language=Japanese|accessdate=2009-08-04|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080615043009/http://www.jacompa.or.jp/rekishi/d1993.htm|archivedate=2008-06-15}}</ref>\n|align=\"left\"|Greatest Album\n|<small>(Producer and arranger: Yamashita / Performer and songwriter: [[Mariya Takeuchi]])</small>\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|2003 <small>(45th)</small>\n|align=\"left\"|\"Christmas Eve\"<ref name=\"45rt\" />\n|align=\"left\"|Special Prizes\n|<small>(Songwriter, producer, arranger, performer: Yamashita)</small>\n|-\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\"\n|-\n| colspan=4 bgcolor=\"#DDDDDD\" align=center | '''[[Japan Gold Disc Award]]'''\n|-\n!align=\"center\"|Year\n!align=\"center\"|Song\n!align=\"center\"|Category\n!align=\"center\"|Personnel\n|-\n|1994 <small>(9th)</small>\n|align=\"left\"|''Impressions''<ref name=\"09gdt\">{{cite web|url=http://www.golddisc.jp/award/09/middle.html|publisher=Recording Industry Association of Japan|title=List of the 9th Gold Disc Award Winners|language=Japanese|accessdate=2009-08-04|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071110191140/http://www.golddisc.jp/award/09/middle.html|archivedate=2007-11-10}}</ref>\n|align=\"left\"|Grand-prix Album\n|<small>(Producer and arranger: Yamashita / Songwriter and performer: Mariya Takeuchi / arranger: Katsuhisa Hattori / recording engineer: Yasuo Sato)</small>\n|-\n|1998 <small>(13th)</small>\n|align=\"left\"|''Cozy''<ref name=\"09gdt 2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.golddisc.jp/award/013/13th_001.html|publisher=Recording Industry Association of Japan|title=List of the 13th Gold Disc Award Winners|language=Japanese|accessdate=2009-08-04|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090114162456/http://www.golddisc.jp/award/013/13th_001.html|archivedate=2009-01-14}}</ref>\n|align=\"left\"|Pop Albums of the Year\n|<small>(Songwriter, producer, arranger, performer: Yamashita)</small>\n|-\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|3}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Discogs artist|119485-Tatsuro-Yamashita}}\n* {{Official website|https://www.tatsuro.co.jp/}} ([[Japanese language|Japanese]])\n* [http://wmg.jp/tatsuro/ Artist Page in Warner Music Japan]\n* [http://mij-only.com/index.php?id=97 An account of Christmas Eve (Made in Japan ONLY)]{{Dead link|date=August 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} (in English)\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Yamashita, Tatsuro}}\n[[Category:1953 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Japanese male singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:Japanese male pop singers]]\n[[Category:Japanese male rock singers]]\n[[Category:Japanese record producers]]\n[[Category:Singers from Tokyo]]\n[[Category:20th-century Japanese singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Japanese singers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Expand Japanese|\u5c71\u4e0b\u9054\u90ce|date=January 2014}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name             = Tatsur\u014d Yamashita\n| image            = \n| caption          = Tatsuro Yamashita, 2018\n| birth_name       = {{nihongo|Yamashita Tatsur\u014d|\u5c71\u4e0b \u9054\u90ce}}\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|1953|2|4|mf=y}}<ref name=\"tatsuro\">{{cite web |title=Biography |url=https://www.tatsuro.co.jp/biography/ |website=tatsuro.co.jp |publisher=Smile Company Ltd. |accessdate=2 December 2019}}</ref>\n| death_date       = \n| birth_place      = [[Ikebukuro]], [[Toshima, Tokyo (ward)|Toshima]], [[Tokyo|T\u014dky\u014d-to]], [[Japan]]<ref name=\"tatsuro\"/>\n| occupation       = [[Singer-songwriter]], [[record producer]]\n| spouse           = {{marriage|[[Mariya Takeuchi]]|1982}}\n| children         = 1\n| module = {{Infobox musical artist|embed=yes\n| background       = solo_singer\n| genre            = [[Rock music|Rock]], [[Pop music|pop]], [[kay\u014dkyoku]], [[city pop]], [[soul music|soul]], [[R&B]]\n| years_active     = 1973-present\n| instrument       = [[Singing|Vocals]], [[guitar]]s, [[piano]], [[Keyboard (music)|keyboards]], [[Drum kit|drums]], [[Percussion instrument|percussion]]\n| label            = AIR, Moon, Niagara, Elec, [[RCA]], RVC, [[Warner Music Japan]], [[Nippon Columbia]], EastWest Japan, MMG\n| associated_acts  = Sugar Babe, [[Mariya Takeuchi]], [[Haruomi Hosono]], [[Ryuichi Sakamoto]], [[Eiichi Ohtaki]]\n}}\n| website          = {{URL|https://tatsuro.co.jp}}\n}}\n\n{{nihongo|'''Tatsur\u014d Yamashita'''|\u5c71\u4e0b \u9054\u90ce|Yamashita Tatsur\u014d|born February 4, 1953}}, occasionally credited as '''Tatsu Yamashita'''<ref>{{cite AV media notes |title= Ride on Time (album)|others= Tatsuro Yamashita|year= 1980|type= LP front cover|publisher= [[Bertelsmann Music Group|BMG]]Japan}}</ref> or '''Tats Yamashita''',<ref>{{cite AV media notes |title= Big Wave (Tatsuro Yamashita album)|others= Tatsuro Yamashita|year= 1984|type= LP sleevenotes|publisher= [[Warner Music Group|Warner]]/Moon Records}}</ref> is a [[Japanese people|Japanese]] [[singer-songwriter]] and [[record producer]] who helped pioneer the style of Japanese [[Soft rock|adult-oriented rock/soft rock]] dubbed \"[[city pop]]\".<ref name=\"thejapantimes1\">{{cite news |last1=Hadfield |first1=James |title='Pacific Breeze' collates the slick sound of Japanese city pop |url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/culture/2019/05/01/music/pacific-breeze-collates-slick-sound-japanese-city-pop/ |accessdate=22 November 2019 |publisher=The Japan Times |date=1 May 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"radiomilwaukee\">{{cite news |last1=Doucette |first1=Marcus |title=The unforgettable funk of \u201970s and \u201980s Japanese City Pop |url=https://radiomilwaukee.org/discover-music/sound-travels/japanese-city-pop/ |accessdate=22 November 2019 |publisher=Radio Milwaukee |date=19 February 2019}}</ref> Yamashita produced much city pop music during the 1970s{{ndash}}1980s, and is sometimes considered the \"king\" of the genre.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ed Motta drops exclusive City Pop Vol. 2 mixtape of smooth and funky Japanese AOR - Wax Poetics |url=http://www.waxpoetics.com/blog/music/mixtape/ed-motta-drops-exclusive-city-pop-vol-2-mixtape-smooth-funky-japanese-aor/ |work=[[Wax Poetics]] |date=April 28, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"redbullmusicacademy\"/> He has also collaborated with his wife [[Mariya Takeuchi]], another city pop singer.<ref name=\"thejapantimes2\">{{cite news |last1=St. Michel |first1=Patrick |title=Mariya Takeuchi: The pop genius behind 2018's surprise online smash hit from Japan |url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/culture/2018/11/17/music/mariya-takeuchi-pop-genius-behind-2018s-surprise-online-smash-hit-japan/ |accessdate=22 November 2019 |publisher=The Japan Times |date=17 November 2018}}</ref>\n\nYamashita is also known for the song \"Christmas Eve\", which initially appeared on his album ''[[Melodies (Tatsuro Yamashita album)|Melodies]]'' in 1983 and later became a hit throughout the decades.<ref name=\"christmaseve\">{{cite web| url=http://www.oricon.co.jp/news/ranking/5892/ | title = \u5c71\u4e0b\u9054\u90ce\u3001\u300c\u30af\u30ea\u30b9\u30de\u30b9\u30fb\u30a4\u30d6\u300d\u3067\u5927\u8a18\u9332\u6a39\u7acb\uff01\u300020\u5e74\u9023\u7d9aTOP100\u5165\u308a\uff01 \u30cb\u30e5\u30fc\u30b9-ORICON STYLE-|trans-title=Tatsuro Yamashita's \"Christmas Eve\" set a record! : entering the top 100 on the chart for 20 consecutive years |work=oricon.co.jp|publisher= [[Original Confidence]]|language= Japanese|accessdate=2009-06-26}}</ref><ref name=\"JP1\">[http://www18.ocn.ne.jp/~hbr/JP1_e.htm List of number-one singles on the Japan's Oricon Weekly Charts (1968-)]</ref> It is considered one of the standard Japanese [[Christmas song]]s, winning the Special Prize at the [[45th Japan Record Awards|45th]] [[Japan Record Award]]s 20 years after its release.<ref name=\"45rt\">{{cite web|url=http://www.jacompa.or.jp/45th_awards/tokubetsusyou.html|publisher=Japan Composer's Association|title=The 45th Japan Record Award - Special Prizes winners|language=Japanese|accessdate=2009-08-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070907172758/http://www.jacompa.or.jp/45th_awards/tokubetsusyou.html|archive-date=2007-09-07|url-status=dead}}</ref> In 2007, ''[[Rolling Stone|Rolling Stone Japan]]'' ranked his album ''Spacy'' number 14 on a list of the greatest Japanese rock albums of all time.<ref>{{cite web |title=Finally! \"The 100 Greatest Japanese Rock Albums of All Time\" Listed |url=http://exclaim.ca/News/finally_100_greatest_japanese_rock_albums_of_all_time |work=[[Exclaim!]] |date=2007-11-14 |accessdate=2020-01-02}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nIn 1973, Yamashita formed the band Sugar Babe with musicians including [[Taeko Ohnuki]] and Kunio Muramatsu, and released their sole album ''Songs'' two years later in 1975.<ref name=\"sugarbabebio\">{{cite web|url= http://music.yahoo.co.jp/shop/p/12/22606/|title= Yahoo!\u30df\u30e5\u30fc\u30b8\u30c3\u30af - SUGAR BABE - \u30a2\u30fc\u30c6\u30a3\u30b9\u30c8\u60c5\u5831|trans-title= Yahoo!Music - Sugar Babe - Artist Information|work= music.yahoo.co.jp|publisher= Listen Japan|accessdate= 2009-06-28|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20060527180409/http://music.yahoo.co.jp/shop/p/12/22606|archive-date= 2006-05-27|url-status= dead}}</ref><ref name=\"tatsuro\"/> After the group disbanded in 1976, Yamashita signed to RCA and launched his own career, with release of the solo album ''Circus Town'' the same year. Also the same year he teamed up with [[Eiichi Ohtaki]], who was the producer of Sugar Babe,<ref>{{cite web |title=Happy End's Eiichi Ohtaki Dies at 65 |url=http://exclaim.ca/music/article/happy_ends_eiichi_ohtaki_dies_at_65 |work=[[Exclaim!]] |date=2013-12-31 |accessdate=2017-01-09}}</ref> and brief Sugar Babe member Ginji Ito to release an album titled ''Niagara Triangle Vol. 1'' that was cited by [[MTV]] as one of the finest collaborative efforts from that period.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv81.com/features/lists/6-japanese-super-groups-that-are-changing-j-music-history/|title=6 Japanese Super Groups That are Changing J-music History|publisher=[[MTV81]]|date=2016-03-16|accessdate=2017-01-09}}</ref> His 1979 [[Japan Record Award|award-winning]] album ''Moonglow'' gained moderate success,<ref name=\"22rt\">{{cite web|url=http://www.jacompa.or.jp/rekishi/d1980.htm|publisher=Japan Composer's Association|title=History of the Japan Record Awards - List of the 20th Award Winners|language=Japanese|accessdate=2008-12-28|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080611055622/http://www.jacompa.or.jp/rekishi/d1980.htm|archivedate=2008-06-11}}</ref> but his 1980 song \"Ride on Time\" peaked at #3 on the Japanese Oricon and the same-titled album topped the chart subsequently,<ref name=\"goodluck\">{{cite web|url= http://www.tbs.co.jp/goodluck/themesong.html|title= Description of the theme song for the television drama aired on TBS in 2003|work= tbs.co.jp|publisher= [[Tokyo Broadcasting System]]|language= Japanese|accessdate= 2009-06-26|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20090406223507/http://www.tbs.co.jp/goodluck/themesong.html|archive-date= 2009-04-06|url-status= dead}}</ref><ref name=\"jpno1album80s\">{{cite web|url=http://www007.upp.so-net.ne.jp/k-makoto/datastation/music/oricon/oriconalbum80.htm|script-title=ja:\u30aa\u30ea\u30b3\u30f3\u30fb\u30d2\u30c3\u30c8\u30c1\u30e3\u30fc\u30c8\u3000\uff2e\uff4f\uff0e\uff11\uff21\uff2c\uff22\uff35\uff2d \uff11\uff19\uff18\uff10\uff0d\uff11\uff19\uff18\uff19 -|trans-title=List of the number-one on the Japanese Weekly LP Chart from 1980 to 1989|language=Japanese|accessdate=2009-06-26|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090504085533/http://www007.upp.so-net.ne.jp/k-makoto/datastation/music/oricon/oriconalbum80.htm|archivedate=2009-05-04}}</ref><ref name=\"redbullmusicacademy\">{{cite news |last1=Yokegawa |first1=Tetsuko |title=The Artisian: The Inimitable Genius of Tatsuro Yamashita |url=https://daily.redbullmusicacademy.com/2014/12/tatsuro-yamashita-feature |accessdate=22 November 2019 |publisher=Red Bull Music Academy |date=10 December 2014}}</ref> propelling him to stardom.<ref name=\"tatsuro\"/>\n\nAs a solo artist, Yamashita has released 17 studio albums, 2 live albums, multiple compilations and over 40 singles. He has been one of the most commercially successful Japanese male solo recording artists in the history of the Japanese album chart, selling approximately 9 million albums in total.<ref name=\"makihara\">{{cite web|url=http://www.oricon.co.jp/news/ranking/15054/ | title=\u69c7\u539f\u656c\u4e4b\u3001\u4e95\u4e0a\u967d\u6c34\u629c\u304f\uff01\u30a2\u30eb\u30d0\u30e0\u7dcf\u58f2\u4e0a\u679a\u6570\u7537\u6027\u30bd\u30ed\u6b74\u4ee31\u4f4d\u306b\uff01|trans-title=Noriyuki Makihara become the best-selling male solo artist on the Oricon albums chart, defeating Yosui Inoue|accessdate=2009-05-09}}</ref><ref name=\"oricon album\">{{cite web | url=http://www7a.biglobe.ne.jp/~yamag/album/al_yamasita.html | title=Yamachan Land (Japan's charts archives)  - Albums Chart Daijiten | language=Japanese | accessdate=2008-03-19 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://archive.is/20071111034222/http://www7a.biglobe.ne.jp/~yamag/album/al_yamasita.html | archivedate=2007-11-11 }}</ref> He has also composed for films and television commercials, and worked on records by other artists. He is particularly successful as a musical collaborator for [[Mariya Takeuchi]], whom he married in 1982. They have one daughter.<ref name=\"takeuchibio\">{{cite web| url=http://www.wmg.jp/artist/mariya/profile.html | script-title=ja:\u30d7\u30ed\u30d5\u30a3\u30fc\u30eb  \u7af9\u5185 \u307e\u308a\u3084  \u30ef\u30fc\u30ca\u30fc\u30df\u30e5\u30fc\u30b8\u30c3\u30af\u30fb\u30b8\u30e3\u30d1\u30f3 |trans-title=Biography of Mariya Takeuchi|work=wmg.jp|publisher= [[Warner Music Group]]|language= Japanese |accessdate=2009-06-26}}</ref>\n\n== Discography ==\n\n=== Studio albums ===\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n!Year\n!Album\n!Chart positions<br />([[Oricon|JP]])<ref name=\"oricon album\" />\n!Label\n!Notes\n|-\n|1976\n|''[[Circus Town]]''\n|align=\"center\"|27\n|rowspan=\"4\" align=\"center\"|RVC/RCA\n|rowspan=\"3\"|Peaked the chart at the time of 2002 reissue\n|-\n|1977\n|''[[Spacy (album)|Spacy]]''\n|align=\"center\"|29\n|-\n|1978\n|''[[Go Ahead!]]''\n|align=\"center\"|25\n|-\n|1979\n|''[[Moonglow (Tatsuro Yamashita album)|Moonglow]]''\n|align=\"center\"|20\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|1980\n|''[[Ride On Time (album)|Ride On Time]]''\n|align=\"center\"|1\n|rowspan=\"3\" align=\"center\"|RVC/AIR\n|\n|-\n|''[[On the Street Corner]]''\n|align=\"center\"|13\n|Expanded edition was reissued in later years\n|-\n|1982\n|''[[For You (Tatsuro Yamashita album)|For You]]''\n|align=\"center\"|1\n|\n|-\n|1983\n|''[[Melodies (Tatsuro Yamashita album)|Melodies]]''\n|align=\"center\"|1\n|rowspan=\"5\" align=\"center\"|[[Alfa Records|Alfa Moon]]\n|\n|-\n|1984\n|''[[Big Wave (Tatsuro Yamashita album)|Big Wave]]''\n|align=\"center\"|2\n|Soundtrack for the same-titled motion picture\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|1986\n|''[[Pocket Music (album)|Pocket Music]]''\n|align=\"center\"|1\n|\n|-\n|''[[On the Street Corner 2]]''\n|align=\"center\"|3\n|\n|-\n|1988\n|{{nihongo|''[[Boku no Naka no Shounen]]''|\u50d5\u306e\u4e2d\u306e\u5c11\u5e74}}\n|align=\"center\"|1\n|\n|-\n|1991\n|''[[Artisan (album)|Artisan]]''\n|align=\"center\"|1\n|rowspan=\"2\" align=\"center\"|Moon/MMG\n|\n|-\n|1993\n|''[[Season's Greetings (album)|Season's Greetings]]''\n|align=\"center\"|4\n|align=\"center\"|Christmas Album\n|-\n|1998\n|''[[Cozy (Tatsuro Yamashita album)|Cozy]]''\n|align=\"center\"|1\n|rowspan=\"4\" align=\"center\"|Moon/[[Warner Music Group|Warner]]\n|\n|-\n|1999\n|''[[On the Street Corner 3]]''\n|align=\"center\"|4\n|\n|-\n|2005\n|''[[Sonorite]]''\n|align=\"center\"|2\n|\n|-\n|2011\n|''Ray of Hope''\n|align=\"center\"|1\n|\n|-\n|}\n\n==== Albums recorded with other musicians ====\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n!Year\n!Album\n!Chart positions<br />([[Oricon|JP]])<ref name=\"oricon album2\">{{cite web |url= http://www.oricon.co.jp/search/result.php?cd=22606&types=art&media=album | title=\u691c\u7d22\u7d50\u679c-ORICON STYLE \u30a2\u30fc\u30c6\u30a3\u30b9\u30c8/CD\u691c\u7d22 \u30b7\u30e5\u30ac\u30fc\u30fb\u30d9\u30a4\u30d6|trans-title=Searching results albums by Sugar Babe (available only 1989 to present)|language=Japanese|accessdate=2009-05-20|publisher= Original confidence|work= oricon.co.jp}}</ref><ref name=\"oricon album3\">{{cite web |url= http://www.oricon.co.jp/search/result.php?cd=341317&types=art&media=album | title=\u691c\u7d22\u7d50\u679c-ORICON STYLE \u30a2\u30fc\u30c6\u30a3\u30b9\u30c8/CD\u691c\u7d22 \u5c71\u4e0b\u9054\u90ce\uff0c\u4f0a\u85e4\u9280\u6b21\uff0c\u5927\u7027\u8a60\u4e00|trans-title=Searching results albums by Tatsuro Yamashita, Ginji Ito, Eiichi Otaki (available only 1989 to present)|language=Japanese|accessdate=2009-05-20|publisher= Original confidence|work= oricon.co.jp}}</ref>\n!Label\n!Notes\n|-\n|1975\n|''[[Songs (