||3||0||10||0||51||1\n|-\n|[[2003\u201304 Bristol City F.C. season|2003\u201304]]\n|Second Division\n|38||1||1||0||7||0||46||1\n|-\n|[[2004\u201305 Bristol City F.C. season|2004\u201305]]\n|[[EFL League One|League One]]\n|22||2||2||0||3||0||27||2\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!98!!4!!6!!0!!20!!0!!124!!4\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[Blackpool F.C.|Blackpool]]\n|[[2004\u201305 Blackpool F.C. season|2004\u201305]]\n|League One\n|8||0||0||0||0||0||8||0\n|-\n|[[2005\u201306 Blackpool F.C. season|2005\u201306]]\n|League One\n|24||1||0||0||2||0||27||1\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!32!!1!!0!!0!!2!!0!!35!!1\n|-\n|[[Forest Green Rovers F.C.|Forest Green Rovers]]\n|[[2006\u201307 Football Conference|2006\u201307]]<ref>{{soccerbase season|1185|2006|accessdate=1 January 2017}}</ref>\n|[[National League (division)|Conference Premier]]\n|9||2||0||0||0||0||9||2\n|-\n!colspan=\"3\"|Career total\n!475!!13!!24!!0!!58!!2!!558!!15\n|}\n\n==Honours==\n;Gillingham\n*[[Football League Third Division]] runner-up: [[1995\u201396 Gillingham F.C. season|1995\u201396]]\n\n;West Bromwich Albion\n*[[Football League First Division]] runner-up: [[2001\u201302 Football League|2001\u201302]]\n\n;Bristol City\n*[[EFL Trophy|Football League Trophy]] winner: [[2003 Football League Trophy Final|2003]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Butler, Tony}}\n[[Category:1972 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Footballers from Stockport]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football central defenders]]\n[[Category:Gillingham F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Blackpool F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Port Vale F.C. players]]\n[[Category:West Bromwich Albion F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Bristol City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Forest Green Rovers F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Hinckley United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Newport County A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Alfreton Town F.C. players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:National League (English football) players]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=July 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name           = Tony Butler\n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| fullname       = Philip Anthony Butler<ref name=Hugman>{{Hugman|2793|accessdate=22 May 2019}}</ref>\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1972|9|28|df=y}}<ref name=Hugman/>\n| birth_place    = [[Stockport]],<ref name=Hugman/> England\n| death_date     = <!--{{death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|1972|9|28|df=y}}-->\n| height         = {{height|ft=6|in=2}}<ref>{{cite web |title=FootballSquads - Port Vale - 1999/00 |url=http://www.footballsquads.co.uk/eng/1999-2000/d1/portv.htm |website=www.footballsquads.co.uk |accessdate=24 June 2019}}</ref>\n| position       = [[Defender (association football)|Defender]]\n| youthyears1    = | youthclubs1 = \n| years1         = 1991\u20131996| clubs1 = [[Gillingham F.C.|Gillingham]]                    | caps1 = 148| goals1 = 5\n| years2         = 1996\u20131999| clubs2 = [[Blackpool F.C.|Blackpool]]                      | caps2 =  99| goals2 = 0\n| years3         = 1999\u20132000| clubs3 = [[Port Vale F.C.|Port Vale]]                      | caps3 =  19| goals3 = 0\n| years4         = 2000\u20132002| clubs4 = [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]]| caps4 =  70| goals4 = 1\n| years5         = 2002     | clubs5 = \u2192 [[Bristol City F.C.|Bristol City]] (loan)       | caps5 =  11| goals5 = 1\n| years6         = 2002\u20132005| clubs6 = [[Bristol City F.C.|Bristol City]]                | caps6 =  87| goals6 = 3\n| years7         = 2005\u20132006| clubs7 = [[Blackpool F.C.|Blackpool]]                      | caps7 =  32| goals7 = 1\n| years8         = 2006\u20132007| clubs8 = [[Forest Green Rovers F.C.|Forest Green Rovers]]  | caps8 =   9| goals8 = 2\n| years9         = 2006\u20132007| clubs9 = \u2192 [[Newport County A.F.C.|Newport County]] (loan) | caps9 =    | goals9 = \n| years10        = 2007     | clubs10 = [[Hinckley United F.C.|Hinckley United]]         | caps10=    | goals10= \n| years11        = 2007     | clubs11 = [[Alfreton Town F.C.|Alfreton Town]]             | caps11=    | goals11= \n| totalcaps      = 475| totalgoals = 13\n}}\n\n'''Philip Anthony Butler''' (born 28 September 1972) is an English former [[Association football|footballer]]. A [[Defender (association football)|defender]], he made 468 league appearances in a 15-year career in the [[English Football League]].\n\nHe began his career at [[Gillingham F.C.|Gillingham]] in 1991, helping the club to win promotion out of the [[Football League Third Division|Third Division]] in 1995\u201396. He was sold to [[Blackpool F.C.|Blackpool]] in August 1996 for \u00a3225,000, before he was moved on to [[Port Vale F.C.|Port Vale]] for a \u00a3115,000 fee in March 1999. He then joined [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]] in March 2000 for \u00a3140,000, and helped the \"Baggies\" to promotion out of the [[Football League First Division|First Division]] in 2001\u201302. Following this he was allowed to sign with [[Bristol City F.C.|Bristol City]], and he helped his new side to the [[EFL Trophy|League Trophy]] in [[2003 Football League Trophy Final|2003]]. He returned to Blackpool in February 2005, before he signed with Conference club [[Forest Green Rovers F.C.|Forest Green Rovers]] in July 2006. He was loaned out to [[Newport County A.F.C.|Newport County]], before he joined [[Hinckley United F.C.|Hinckley United]] in February 2007. He switched to [[Alfreton Town F.C.|Alfreton Town]] in November 2007.\n\n==Playing career==\n===Gillingham===\nAs a child Butler moved to [[Redcar]] with his family \u2013 his father was a bank manager \u2013 and attended Ryehills School. He started his professional career at [[Gillingham F.C.|Gillingham]] in [[1991\u201392 Gillingham F.C. season|1991\u201392]], who were then a [[Football League Fourth Division|Fourth Division]] under the management of [[Damien Richardson (footballer)|Damien Richardson]]. They finished second-from-bottom in the [[English Football League]] in [[1992\u201393 Gillingham F.C. season|1992\u201393]] under [[Glenn Roeder]], avoiding relegation because they finished just four points ahead of [[Halifax Town A.F.C.|Halifax Town]]. They finished 16th in [[1993\u201394 Football League|1993\u201394]] under [[Mike Flanagan (footballer)|Mike Flanagan]], before dropping to 19th in [[1994\u201395 Gillingham F.C. season|1994\u201395]]. Butler played 42 games in [[1995\u201396 Gillingham F.C. season|1995\u201396]], as new boss [[Tony Pulis]] led the [[Priestfield Stadium]] club to promotion out of the [[Football League Third Division|Third Division]] (fourth tier) in second place. He made 179 appearances for the \"Gills\" in league and cup competitions, scoring seven goals.\n\n===Blackpool===\nButler was sold to [[Blackpool F.C.|Blackpool]] in August 1996 for \u00a3225,000.<ref name=Gillatt>{{cite book|last=Gillatt|first=Peter|title=Blackpool FC On This Day: History, Facts and Figures from Every Day of the Year |publisher=Pitch Publishing Ltd|date=30 November 2009|isbn=1-905411-50-2}}</ref> He played 46 games in [[1996\u201397 Blackpool F.C. season|1996\u201397]] under [[Gary Megson]], as the [[Bloomfield Road]] club finished one place and four points behind [[Crewe Alexandra F.C.|Crewe Alexandra]] in the [[Football League Second Division|Second Division]] play-off zone. New boss [[Nigel Worthington]] played him 43 times in [[1997\u201398 Blackpool F.C. season|1997\u201398]], as the \"Seasiders\" slipped to 12th. He made 23 appearances in [[1998\u201399 Blackpool F.C. season|1998\u201399]], with Blackpool on the way to another mid-table finish.\n\n===Port Vale and West Brom===\nHe signed for [[Port Vale F.C.|Port Vale]] for a \u00a3115,000 fee in March 1999.<ref name=\"B2B\" /> He played just four games, as [[Brian Horton]]'s \"Valiants\" managed to retain their [[Football League First Division|First Division]] status despite a poor start to [[1998\u201399 Port Vale F.C. season|1998\u201399]]. He featured 15 times in [[1999\u20132000 Port Vale F.C. season|1999\u20132000]], before he left [[Vale Park]] for league rivals [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]] in March 2000 for a \u00a3140,000 fee, as one of four deadline-day signings made by manager Gary Megson. Butler featured seven times for the \"Baggies\" in [[1999\u20132000 West Bromwich Albion F.C. season|1999\u20132000]], as Megson steered the club away from the relegation zone \u2013 whilst Port Vale went down. He made 51 appearances in [[2000\u201301 West Bromwich Albion F.C. season|2000\u201301]], as Albion reached the play-offs, only to be defeated by [[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|Bolton Wanderers]] at the semi-final stage. It was in this season that he scored his only goal for the club, in a 2\u20131 loss to [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]].<ref>{{cite news| title = Birmingham 2-1 West Brom| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_1/1173195.stm| publisher = BBC Sport| date = 17 February 2001| accessdate = 27 March 2014}}</ref> He featured 23 times as the club won promotion as runners-up in [[2001\u201302 West Bromwich Albion F.C. season|2001\u201302]], finishing ten points behind champions [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]]. He featured in the \"[[Battle of Bramall Lane]]\" on 16 March 2002, replacing [[L\u00e1rus Sigur\u00f0sson]] (the only \"Baggies\" player to have been booked) 14 minutes before the match was abandoned.  With the club now in the [[Premier League]], he found himself surplus to requirements at [[The Hawthorns]], and was loaned out to [[Bristol City F.C.|Bristol City]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/b/bristol_city/2272617.stm|title=Butler seeks to stay|date=21 September 2002|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=13 May 2009}}</ref> for whom he subsequently signed permanently.\n\n===Bristol City and return to Blackpool===\nHe played for City in the [[2003 Football League Trophy Final|final]] of the [[EFL Trophy|League Trophy]] at the [[Millennium Stadium]], as the \"Robins\" beat [[Carlisle United F.C.|Carlisle United]] 2\u20130.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bristol City sink Carlisle|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/2898425.stm|accessdate=2 April 2012|newspaper=[[BBC Sport]]|date=6 April 2003}}</ref> They also reached the play-offs in [[2002\u201303 Bristol City F.C. season|2002\u201303]], but were beaten by [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]] at the semi-final stage; Butler played 51 games over the course of the campaign. He played 46 games in [[2003\u201304 Bristol City F.C. season|2003\u201304]], including the play-off final at the Millennium Stadium, where [[Danny Wilson (footballer, born 1960)|Danny Wilson]]'s men were [[2004 Football League Second Division play-off final|beaten 1\u20130]] by [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]]. He played 27 games under new boss [[Brian Tinnion]] in [[2004\u201305 Bristol City F.C. season|2004\u201305]], before leaving [[Ashton Gate Stadium|Ashton Gate]] for former club Blackpool on a free transfer in February 2005.<ref name=\"B2B\">{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/b/blackpool/4243551.stm|title=Butler completes Blackpool move |date=7 February 2005|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=13 May 2009}}</ref> They finished the season 16th in [[EFL League One|League One]] under [[Colin Hendry]]. Butler played 26 games in [[2005\u201306 Bristol City F.C. season|2005\u201306]], as Blackpool avoided relegation by just two places and three points, and was released by manager [[Simon Grayson]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/b/blackpool/4989296.stm|title=Six players released by Grayson |date=17 May 2006|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=13 May 2009}}</ref> He scored once for Blackpool, his goal coming in a 4\u20132 win over [[Doncaster Rovers F.C.|Doncaster Rovers]].<ref>{{cite news| title = Blackpool 4-2 Doncaster | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_2/4634374.stm| publisher = BBC Sport| date = 24 January 2006| accessdate = 27 March 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Later career===\nButler joined [[Gary Owers]]' [[Forest Green Rovers F.C.|Forest Green Rovers]] in July 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/f/forest_green_rovers/5158048.stm|title=Forest Green seal triple signing |date=7 July 2006|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=13 May 2009}}</ref> During the [[2006\u201307 Football Conference|2006\u201307]] season he was loaned out to [[National League South|Conference South]] side [[Newport County A.F.C.|Newport County]].<ref>{{cite news|date=13 September 2006|url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/f/forest_green_rovers/5343134.stm|title= Butler leaves Rovers for Newport|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=28 August 2007}}</ref> In February 2007, Butler joined [[Hinckley United F.C.|Hinckley United]] of the [[National League North|Conference North]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/f/forest_green_rovers/6401179.stm|title=Butler ends spell at Forest Green |date=27 February 2007|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=13 May 2009}}</ref> He was released by Hinckley in November 2007, and subsequently signed for league rivals [[Alfreton Town F.C.|Alfreton Town]].<ref>[http://www.nonleaguedaily.com/news/index.php?&newsmode=FULL&nid=46320 Law calls for Butler] ''nonleaguedaily.com''</ref>\n\n==Statistics==\nSource:<ref>{{ENFA}}. Retrieved 11 May 2016.</ref><ref>{{Soccerbase}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Division\n!colspan=\"2\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|FA Cup\n!colspan=\"2\"|Other\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=\"7\"|[[Gillingham F.C.|Gillingham]]\n|[[1990\u201391 Gillingham F.C. season|1990\u201391]]\n|[[Football League Fourth Division|Fourth Division]]\n|6||0||0||0||0||0||6||0\n|-\n|[[1991\u201392 Gilli