\n| July 5, 1987\n| 90 minutes\n|-\n| ''[[Psycho IV: The Beginning]]''\n| 1990\n| N/A (2 critics)<ref>https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/psycho_4_the_beginning/ </ref>\n| {{N/A}}\n| {{N/A}}\n| November 10, 1990\n| 96 minutes\n|-\n| ''[[Psycho (1998 film)|Psycho]]''\n| 1998\n| 38% (78 reviews)<ref>https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/1084964-psycho/ </ref>\n| 47 (23 reviews)<ref>https://www.metacritic.com/movie/psycho </ref>\n| $21,456,130<ref name=\"mojo-p1998\" />\n| December 4, 1998\n| 104 minutes\n|}\n\n===Accolades===\nIn 1960, ''[[Psycho (1960 film)|Psycho]]'' received four [[Academy Award]] nominations including Best Director for [[Alfred Hitchcock]], Best Supporting Actress for [[Janet Leigh]], Best Cinematography and Best Art Direction. All three sequels have been nominated for Saturn Awards. ''[[Psycho II (film)|Psycho II]]'' received a nomination for Best Screenplay for writer [[Tom Holland (director)|Tom Holland]]. ''[[Psycho III]]'' was nominated for Best Horror Film. ''[[Psycho IV: The Beginning]]'' was nominated for Best Genre Television Series.\n\n===Legacy===\n''[[Psycho (1960 film)|Psycho]]'' has become one of the most recognizable films ever made. The shower scene alone has become one of the most iconic cut scenes in cinematic history. ''Psycho'' is frequently referenced, given homage to or spoofed in television shows such as ''[[The Simpsons]]'', ''[[South Park]]'', ''[[American Dad!]]'', ''[[The Mary Tyler Moore Show]]'' and more. Films such as ''[[Scream 2]]'', ''[[Charlie and the Chocolate Factory (film)|Charlie and the Chocolate Factory]]'', ''[[Throw Momma from the Train]]'', ''[[Scary Movie]]'' and more have referenced the film. Many critics and filmmakers have cited ''Psycho'' as the film that modernized the horror genre. Horror writer David. J. Schow stated (in ''[[The Psycho Legacy]]'') \"It brought the idea that the killer in a horror film was not a mutant, didn't have dents in his head; he could look like that nice young boy from next door\". The film also brought in a new level of acceptable violence and sexuality in movies. Both [[Anthony Perkins]] and [[Janet Leigh]] spent the rest of their careers being typecasted by the film. Even [[Alfred Hitchcock]]'s films began to decline in critical and financial popularity after the release of ''Psycho''. Hitchcock film scholars argue that for the rest of his career, Hitchcock's films were constantly being compared to ''Psycho''. The \"Psycho\" films still maintain a very large fanbase. Various websites dedicated to the franchise such as ''The Psycho Movies.com'' have appeared on the Internet. Books detailing the making and impact of the film such as ''Alfred Hitchcock and The Making of Psycho'', ''The Moment of Psycho'', Janet Leigh's ''Psycho: Behind The Scenes of the Classic Thriller'' have been published over the years. Two retrospective documentaries have been released detailing the making of all four films including ''The Making of Psycho'' (1997) and ''[[The Psycho Legacy]]'' (2010). The film also spawned the show ''[[Alfred Hitchcock: The Art of Making Movies]]'' at [[Universal Studios Florida]], with part of the show detailing how the shower scene was filmed. In 1992, ''Psycho'' was added to the [[National Film Registry]] by the [[Library of Congress]].\n\nA musical stage adaptation was performed January-February 2019 at PULP Black Box Theatre in Atlanta, GA. <ref>https://www.facebook.com/events/1973956552682770/</ref>\n\n==Other media and merchandise==\n\nVarious ''Psycho'' related merchandise has been sold ever since the release of the original film. Merchandise includes T-shirts, posters, DVDs, books, stationery, shot glasses, shower curtains, action figures, model house kits, pens and more. Much of the merchandise is related to the fictional Bates Motel where items commonly found in an actual motel have the Bates Motel logo on them. A Bates Motel light up sign was released in 2009. To coincide with the 50th anniversary of the release of the original film, a Psycho house model kit was released in the U.S. Props from all the films are also sold occasionally on [[eBay]]. The original one sheet poster for ''[[Psycho (1960 film)|Psycho]]'' is worth around $3000 in mint condition. The original one sheets for ''[[Psycho II (film)|Psycho II]]'', ''[[Psycho III]]'' and ''[[Psycho IV: The Beginning]]'' are worth around $50 each.\n\n===Graphic novels===\nIn 1992, a series of [[graphic novel]]s based on the original ''[[Psycho (1960 film)|Psycho]]'' was published by the Innovation Comics group. Today, the novels are out of print and are very rare to find.{{citation needed|date=August 2016}}\n\n===The ''Psycho'' House and Bates Motel sets===\nThe Bates House and Motel were constructed on the backlot at Universal City Studios in 1959 for the production of ''Psycho''. It has been said that the house, designed by art director's Joseph Hurley and Robert Clathworthy, was loosely based on an Edward Hopper painting called \"House by the Railroad\". The house and motel sets were actually empty shells, also known as facades. When the house was originally built, there was no right side of the house, since the right side is never seen on camera in the original ''Psycho'' film. Interiors of the Bates house and motel were constructed on Sound stage 18-A at Universal, just a short walk from the actual exterior locations making production convenient for all involved. After production had wrapped on ''[[Psycho (1960 film)|Psycho]]'', the house was featured in several television productions including ''The Virginian'' and ''Boris Karloff's Mystery Theater''.\n\nIn 1964, Universal Studios opened its patented Studio Tram Tour. The right side of the house was then added and the set was unceremoniously dubbed \"The Psycho House\". The house and even the motel went on to appear in several shows such as ''[[Night Gallery]]'', ''[[The Hardy Boys]]'' and even in films such as ''[[Invitation to a Gunfighter]]'' and ''[[Modern Problems]]''. The motel was torn down in 1979 and the house was moved to an alternate location on the backlot to accommodate the new tour. In 1982, Richard Franklin and Hilton A. Green announced plans to film ''[[Psycho II (film)|Psycho II]]''. The house was then moved to a location that best matched the original hill and only about 40 feet of the motel was actually re-built. The rest of the motel in the film was a matte painting. TV shows during the '80s promoted the Universal Tour and prominently featured the Psycho House including ''[[Amazing Stories]]'', ''[[Knight Rider (1982 TV series)|Knight Rider]]'', ''[[Welcome to My Nightmare]]'', and ''[[Diff'rent Strokes]]''.\n\nIn 1985, the Bates Motel was fully re-built for the filming of ''[[Psycho III]]''. In 1987, the NBC-TV network announced plans for the TV pilot ''[[Bates Motel (film)|Bates Motel]]''. The motel in the film was re-modeled to look very Spanish like. This version of the set remained until 1994 when the new renovations were taken away and the motel was put back to look the way it did in the original Psycho. An episode of ''[[Murder, She Wrote]]'' from the early 1990s featured the Psycho House and Bates Motel as key locations in the popular Angela Lansbury series.\n\nIn 1988, plans for ''[[Psycho IV: The Beginning]]'' were underway at Universal. Plans to shoot the movie in Orlando, Florida were set into motion and the film crew constructed a full-scale replica of the Bates Motel and Psycho House at the soon-to-be built Universal Studios Florida. The final dressing and painting was done by the Psycho IV art department crew in 1990, but the house and motel was fully built in 1988 long before the production team was assembled for the project. After production wrapped, the sets were left as attractions at the park until 1999 when it was torn down to make room for another attraction.\n\nIn 1998, the Psycho House in California was renovated to preserve the set. All of the rotting wood was replaced and the set had a new paint job. That same year, plans to remake ''Psycho'' were announced. It was originally announced that Gus Van Sant was going to be using the original house and motel sets. However, the production team built a new house directly in front of the old one, and the motel was updated to look like it was from the 1960s. The new house was moved next to the original house and remained there for about three years after production. In 2003, due to popular demand, the remake's house was torn down and the motel was restored to the original way once again. To this day, the house and motel are still standing on the backlot of Universal and continue to be major tourist attractions. The [[Studio Tour|tram tour]] features an actor playing Norman Bates coming out of cabin 1 with a body, putting it in the trunk of a car and then wielding a large knife at the tourists as the tram drives away.\n\n===''24 Hour Psycho''===\nAn art installation, ''[[24 Hour Psycho]]'', created by artist [[Douglas Gordon]] in 1993, and later installed in the [[Museum of Modern Art]] in New York, consists of a silent screening of ''Psycho'', slowed down to two frames per second (from the usual 24), so that it lasts 24 hours rather than 109 minutes. ''24 Hour Psycho'' is featured prominently in [[Don DeLillo]]'s 2010 novel ''[[Point Omega]]''.\n\n===''The Psycho Legacy'' (2010)===\n{{Main|The Psycho Legacy}}\nIn 2010, a direct-to-DVD documentary was released called ''The Psycho Legacy''. It included interviews with cast and crew from all four Psycho films. It also featured interviews with current horror filmmakers who are fans of the series. The documentary was written, produced and directed by horror journalist Robert Galluzzo. Galluzo made the documentary because of the lack of information on the sequels and also to celebrate the 50th anniversary of the release of the original film. The documentary discussed the impact and legacy of the original ''[[Psycho (1960 film)|Psycho]]'' and the production stories of ''[[Psycho II (film)|Psycho II]]'', ''[[Psycho III]]'' and ''[[Psycho IV: The Beginning]]''. To the surprise of some critics and fans, the failed TV pilot ''[[Bates Motel (film)|Bates Motel]]'' and the [[Gus Van Sant]] [[Psycho (1998 film)|remake]] were not discussed in the documentary, however originally in the deleted scenes section on the DVD two short segments on the two films were supposed to be on there, however for unknown reasons they were left off of the DVD when it was released. The documentary sold well, received mostly positive reviews and garnered new interest in the series from horror fans.\n\n===''Hitchcock'' (2012)===\n{{Main|Hitchcock (film)}}\nOn April 13, 2012, production started on a film adaptation of [[Stephen Rebello]]'s non-fiction book ''[[Alfred Hitchcock and the Making of Psycho]]'', which follows the complex relationship between [[Alfred Hitchcock]] and wife [[Alma Reville]] during the filming of ''[[Psycho (1960 film)|Psycho]]'' in 1959. The film is directed by [[Sacha Gervasi]] and stars [[Anthony Hopkins]] as director Alfred Hitchcock, Helen Mirren as his wife [[Alma Reville]], [[Scarlett Johansson]] as [[Janet Leigh]], [[Jessica Biel]] as [[Vera Miles]], and [[James D'Arcy]] as [[Anthony Perkins]]. Produced by [[The Montecito Picture Company]] and distributed by [[Fox Searchlight Pictures]], the film was released on November 23, 2012 in selected cities with a worldwide release on December 14, 2012. The film has received mixed reviews from critics and moderate box office returns, with a worldwide gross of $5,337,378 as of January 3, 2013.\n\n===2017 documentary: \"78/52\"===\n\nA documentary on the production of ''Psycho'' was released on Oct 13, 2017 by director Alexandre O. Philippe running 91 minutes. The cast of participants included Guillermo del Toro, Peter Bogdanovich, Bret Easton Ellis, Jamie Lee Curtis, Karyn Kusama, Eli Roth, Oz Perkins, Leigh Whannell, Walter Murch, Danny Elfman, Elijah Wood, Richard Stanley, and Neil Marshall.<ref>. {{cite web | date = January 24, 2017 | author = Owen Gleiberman | url = https://variety.com/2017/film/reviews/7852-review-psycho-1201966555/ | title = Film Review: \u201878/52: Hitchcock\u2019s Shower Scene\u2019 | work = [[Variety (magazine)|Variety Magazine]] }}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n* [[Janet Leigh|Leigh, Janet]]; Nickens, Christopher (1995). ''Psycho: Behind the Scenes of the Classic Thriller''. Harmony Press.\n* {{Cite book| last=Rebello|first=Stephen|authorlink=Stephen Rebello|year=1990|title=Alfred Hitchcock and the Making of Psycho|publisher=Marion Boyars|isbn=0-7145-3003-4|ref=harv }}\n* {{Cite book |last=Reavill |first=Gil |year=2007 |title=Aftermath, Inc.: Cleaning Up After CSI Goes Home |publisher=Gotham |isbn=978-1-59240-296-0 |ref=harv |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9781592402960 }}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.thepsychomovies.com The Psycho Movies] \u2013 A comprehensive site for the film series\n{{Psycho}}\n\n[[Category:American film series]]\n[[Category:Film series introduced in 1960]]\n[[Category:Films about psychopaths]]\n[[Category:Horror media franchises]]\n[[Category:Media franchises introduced in 1959]]\n[[Category:Psycho (franchise)| ]]\n", "name_user": "Moe1810", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePsycho III (1986)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Psycho_(franchise)"}
{"title_page": "Howard Schultz", "text_new": "{{short description|American businessman}}\n{{for|the American television producer|Howard Schultz (producer)}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Howard Schultz\n| image              = Howard Schultz by Gage Skidmore.jpg\n| caption            = Schultz in 2019\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1953|7|19}}\n| birth_place        = [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], U.S.\n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| alma_mater         = [[Northern Michigan University]]\n| occupation         = {{hlist|Businessman|author|philanthropist}}\n| years_active       = 1986\u2013present\n| known_for          = Introducing [[Third wave of coffee#History|second wave coffee culture]] to the U.S. with leadership of Starbucks\n| networth           = [[US$]]4.1 billion (November 2019)\n| title              = Chairman emeritus, [[Starbucks]]\n| term               = 2018\u2013present\n| predecessor        = [[Orin C. Smith|Orin Smith]]\n| successor          = [[Kevin Johnson (executive)|Kevin Johnson]]\n| party              = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] (before 2019)<br>[[Independent politician|Independent]] (2019\u2013present)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/2020-election/howard-schultz-says-he-s-not-democrat-surprised-party-backlash-n964476 |title=Howard Schultz says he's not a Democrat, surprised by backlash|date=January 30, 2019 |first=Allan |last=Smith |work=MSNBC |accessdate=January 30, 2019}}</ref>\n| spouse             = {{marriage|Sheri Kersch|1982}}\n| children           = 2\n| website            = {{URL|howardschultz.com|Official website}}\n}}\n'''Howard D. Schultz''' (born July 19, 1953)<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.upi.com/Entertainment_News/2019/07/19/Famous-birthdays-for-July-19-Brian-May-Anthony-Edwards/2631563201127/|title= Famous birthdays for July 19: Brian May, Anthony Edwardsl|agency=[[United Press International]]|date=July 19, 2019|accessdate=August 7, 2019|archivedate=July 19, 2019|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20190719123258/https://www.upi.com/Entertainment_News/2019/07/19/Famous-birthdays-for-July-19-Brian-May-Anthony-Edwards/2631563201127/|url-status=live|quote=Businessman Howard Schultz in 1953 (age 66)}}</ref> is an American businessman, author, and philanthropist. He served as the chairman and [[chief executive officer]] (CEO) of the [[Starbucks|Starbucks Coffee Corporation]] for more than two decades; first from 1986 to 2000, and then from 2008 to 2017. After stepping down as CEO, Schultz stayed at the company from 2017 to 2018 as its executive chairman overseeing Starbuck's philanthropic and charitable giving arm. From 2001 to 2006, he owned the [[Seattle SuperSonics]], a basketball franchise that he sold for [[United States dollar|US$]]350 million to [[Clay Bennett (businessman)|Clay Bennett]], who moved the team to Oklahoma creating the [[Oklahoma City Thunder]]. <!--The lack of citations is purposeful. Refer to Wikipedia:Manual of Style/Lead section#Citations for more information. Wikipedia allows there to be little to no citations in the lead area if it is cited within the main body. If there is something in the lede not cited in the main part drop a {{not found in body}} citation needed tag and it will be addressed.--><!--Keep 4 balanced paragraphs (of 4-5 sentences each) per MOS:LAYOUT.-->\n\nBorn and raised in the [[Brooklyn|Brooklyn borough]] of New York, Schultz graduated from [[Northern Michigan University]] in 1975. After briefly selling office equipment door-to-door one of his early clients, the then coffeehouse startup Starbucks, onboarded him as their marketing head in 1982. A business trip to [[Milan|Milan, Italy]] and [[Coffee in Italy|the city's coffee culture]] inspired him to open ''Il Giornale'', a specialty coffeeshop that quickly merged with Starbucks during the late-1980s. Shultz pushed the new company to sell more than [[Coffee bean|coffee beans]] and equipment, quickly establishing a large network of stores that served [[espresso]], [[coffee]], teas, and casual food. Following large-scale distribution deals \u2013 particularly with major hotels, groceries, and bookstores \u2013 Starbucks became [[List of coffeehouse chains|the largest coffee-house chain]] in the world.<!--Cited in body.--> Shultz took the company [[Initial public offering|public]] in 1992 and used a $271 million valuation to double their store count. He stepped down in 2000 to focus on Starbuck's international expansion, succeeded by [[Orin C. Smith|Orin Smith]].<!--Second tenure as CEO, 2008 to 2017.-->\n\nDuring the [[Financial crisis of 2007\u201308|2008 financial crisis]], Schultz returned as chief executive to stabilize the company after years of unsustainable growth. He led a mass-firing of executives, shuttered hundreds of weak stores, and temporarily closed all U.S. stores to retrain employees in making espresso. Shultz orchestrated multiple [[Mergers and acquisitions|acquisitions]] of American and Chinese beverage companies and introduced a national [[loyalty program]]. His aggressive expansion in Chinese markets has been credited with reconciling [[Chinese tea culture|the country's tea-culture]] with [[Coffee production in China|coffee consumption in China]]. Schultz's positioning of Starbucks as a social hub is widely seen as introducing [[Third wave of coffee#History|the second wave]] of coffee culture in the U.S., particularly in Seattle. His second tenure sustained both [[Criticism of Starbucks|significant criticism]] and growth, ultimately adding nearly $100 billion in [[market capitalization]] to the company, a 21,000% increase in [[shareholder value]]. <!--Cited in body.-->Schultz was succeeded by [[Kevin Johnson (executive)|Kevin Johnson]] as CEO in April 2017, and has, since 2018, retained the title \"Chairman emeritus\" of Starbucks. \n\nSchultz was named the [[The World's Billionaires|145th-richest person in the United States]] by ''Forbes'' in 2019 with a [[net worth]] of $4.1 billion (November 2019).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/profile/howard-schultz/#6de1621452c6|title=Howard Schultz|website=Forbes|access-date=April 2, 2019|language=en}}</ref> He is the author of [[Howard Schultz#Books|three books]], ''Pour Your Heart Into It'' (1997), ''Onward'' (2011), and ''From the Ground Up'' (2019). Long known for his outspoken [[Centrism|centrist]], moderate, and independent political views, Schultz explored a run in the [[2020 United States presidential election]] as an independent candidate but declined to formally join the contest for fear of re-electing [[Donald Trump]]. Schultz supports nonpartisan immigration policy, [[free trade]], [[Balanced budget|fiscal discipline]], comprehensive tax reform, gun control, same-sex marriage, and more generally, [[bipartisanship]] across the political spectrum. To further his philanthropic efforts, he established the Schultz Family Foundation which focuses on [[Veteran#Health effects of military service and treatment for veterans|helping military veterans]] and fighting [[youth unemployment]].<!--Leave space for {{TOC}}.-->   \n\n== Early life and education ==\nSchultz was born to a [[American Jews|Jewish]] family<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2003/06/02/business/new-economy-starbucks-was-put-defensive-attack-internet-rumor-mill-that-would.html New York Times: \"New Economy; How Starbucks was put on the defensive by an attack on the Internet rumor mill that would not go away\" By Sherri Day] June 2, 2003</ref> on July 19, 1953, in the [[Brooklyn|Brooklyn borough]] of New York, the son of Elaine (Lederman) and her husband, ex-[[United States Army]] soldier and then truck driver Fred Schultz.<ref name=Mirror22464724>{{cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/top-stories/2010/08/05/starbucks-howard-schultz-on-how-he-became-coffee-king-115875-22464724/|title= Starbucks' Howard Schultz on how he became coffee king|author=Melissa Thompson|publisher=Sunday Mirror|date=August 5, 2010}}</ref><ref name=Koehn>Howard is constantly reminding his team, \"We are not in the coffee business serving people; we are in the people business serving coffee.\"[https://web.archive.org/web/20140104040308/http://skellogg.sdsmt.edu/IE354/Supplement/howars_s.pdf Kellogg School of Management: \"Howard Schultz and Starbucks Coffee Company\" by [[Nancy Koehn|Nancy F. Koehn]]] November 28, 2011. Archived January 4, 2014.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/voices/commentators/howard-schultz-i-raise-my-frappuccino-to-the-brits-1655293.html|title=Howard Schultz: I raise my frappuccino to the Brits|website=Independent.co.uk|accessdate=June 4, 2018}}</ref> His paternal great-grandfather came to the United States in 1892 from [[Belz]], a town on [[Austria-Hungary|Austro-Hungarian Empire]] territory that is now part of [[Ukraine]]. His maternal great-grandparents were originally from [[Russian Empire|Russia]] and emigrated from [[East London]], [[England]] to the U.S. in 1919.{{sfnp|Schultz|Gordon|2019|pp=295-296}}\n\nWith his younger sister, Ronnie, and brother, Michael, Schultz grew up in the [[Canarsie, Brooklyn|Canarsie]] [[Bayview Houses]] of the [[New York City Housing Authority]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www1.nyc.gov/site/nycha/about/press/pr-2017/chair-shola-olatoye-delivers-speech-on-the-future-of-public-housing-at-nahro-conference-in-washington-20170328.page|title= NYCHA Chair Shola Olatoye delivers speech on the future of public housing at NAHRO conference in Washington |date=January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2018/08/12/nycha-was-my-familys-lifeline-but-now-it-needs-to-go/amp/ |title= NYCHA was my family's lifeline \u2014 but now it needs to go |date=August 12, 2018}}</ref> He went to [[Canarsie High School]], from which he graduated in 1971.<ref name=JWL>{{cite web|url= https://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/howard-schultz|title= Howard Schultz|publisher=Jewish Virtual Library|accessdate=June 27, 2019}}</ref> Schultz played high school football and was invited to [[Northern Michigan University]], to compete for a football scholarship. He was not good enough to be quarterback, and didn't want to play another position.<ref>{{Cite book|title=From the Ground Up: A Journey to Reimagine the Promise of America|last=Schultz|first=Howard|publisher=Random House Publishing Group|year=2019|isbn=0525509445|location=|pages=166}}</ref> He paid for college with government loans and money earned from part-time jobs.  He was the first person in his family to go to college. A member of the Theta-Iota chapter of [[Tau Kappa Epsilon]], Schultz received his bachelor's degree in speech communication in 1975.<ref name=Koehn />\n\n==Career==\nAfter graduating, Schultz worked as a salesman for [[Xerox Corporation]] and was quickly promoted to a full sales representative.<ref name=Koehn /> In 1979, he became a general manager for [[Sweden|Swedish]] drip coffee maker manufacturer [[Hammarplast]],<ref name=Mirror22464724/> where he became responsible for their US operations with a staff of twenty.<ref name=Koehn /> In 1981, Schultz visited a client of Hammarplast, a fledgling coffee-bean shop called Starbucks Coffee Company in Seattle, curious as to why it ordered so many plastic cone filters.<ref name=Koehn /> He was impressed with the company's knowledge of coffee and kept in contact over the next year, expressing interest in working with them. A year later, he joined Starbucks as the director of marketing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.successtelevision.com/index2.php?option=com_content&do_pdf=1&id=3676 |title=Howard Schultz Secrets for Success. Dan Skeen. Success Television |accessdate=August 22, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716161518/http://www.successtelevision.com/index2.php?option=com_content&do_pdf=1&id=3676 |archivedate=July 16, 2011 }}</ref> On a buying trip to [[Milan, Italy|Milan]], Italy, for Starbucks, Schultz noted that coffee bars existed on practically every street. He learned that they not only served excellent [[espresso]], they also served as meeting places or public squares; the 200,000 caf\u00e9s in the country were an important element of Italian culture and society.[[File:Howard-Schultz-Starbucks.jpg|thumb|250x250px|Shultz speaking with press about Starbucks' presence in Canada, 2007.|alt=|left]]On his return, he tried to persuade the owners (including cofounder [[Jerry Baldwin]]) to offer traditional espresso beverages in addition to the whole bean coffee, leaf teas and spices they had long offered. After a successful pilot of the cafe concept, the owners refused to roll it out company-wide, saying they did not want to get into the restaurant business. Frustrated, Schultz decided to leave Starbucks in 1985. He needed $400,000 to open the first store and start the business. He did not have the money and his wife was pregnant with their first baby. Jerry Baldwin and Starbucks cofounder [[Gordon Bowker]] offered to help. Schultz also received $100,000 from a doctor who was impressed by Schultz's energy to \"take a gamble\".<ref>{{cite book|last=Mullins|first=John|title=The New Business Road Test|url=https://archive.org/details/newbusinessroadt0000mull|url-access=registration|year=2007}}</ref> By 1986, he had raised all the money he needed to open the first store, \"Il Giornale\", named after [[Il Giornale|the Milanese newspaper]] of the same name. The store offered ice cream in addition to coffee, had little seating, and played opera music in the background to portray an Italian experience. Two years later, the original Starbucks management decided to focus on [[Peet's Coffee & Tea]] and sold its Starbucks retail unit to Schultz and Il Giornale for US$3.8&nbsp;million.\n\nSchultz renamed ''Il Giornale'' with the Starbucks name, and aggressively expanded its reach across the United States. Schultz's insight in real estate and his hard-line focus on growth drove him to expand the company rapidly. Schultz did not believe in [[franchising]], and made a point of having Starbucks retain ownership of every domestic outlet. On June 26, 1992, Starbucks had its initial public offering and trading of its common stock under the stock ticker SBUX. The offering was done by Alex, Brown & Sons Inc. and Wertheim Schroder & Co. Inc.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/STARBUCKS%20COFFEE%20ANNOUNCES%20INITIAL%20PUBLIC%20OFFERING-a012370965|title=STARBUCKS COFFEE ANNOUNCES INITIAL PUBLIC OFFERING - Free Online Library|work=thefreelibrary.com}}</ref> The IPO raised $271 million for the company and financed the doubling of their stores.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nasdaq.com/articles/7-fun-facts-about-starbucks-honor-its-ipos-25th-anniversary-2017-06-26|title=7 Fun Facts about Starbucks In Honor of Its IPO's 25th Anniversary|last=Zacks|first=Publisher|website=www.nasdaq.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n[[File:Starbucks_stores_graph.png|thumb|268x268px|Shultz served as chief executive from 1986 to 2000, and then from 2008 to 2017.<ref name=\"tele40\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/newsbysector/retailandconsumer/8505866/Forty-years-young-A-history-of-Starbucks.html|title=Forty years young: A history of Starbucks|date=May 11, 2011|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph|accessdate=November 13, 2012|location=London}}</ref> ''Pictured'': Starbucks store count from 1971 to 2010.|alt=]]\nOn June 1, 2000, Schultz stepped down as CEO of Starbucks, moving to the new position of chief global strategist to help the company expand internationally.<ref name=\"CNNff2000\">{{cite news |title=Starbucks CEO steps down |url=http://money.cnn.com/2000/04/06/companies/starbucks/ |accessdate=June 5, 2018 |work=[[CNN Money]] |agency=[[CNNfn]] |date=April 6, 2000}}</ref><ref name=\"InvestopediaSchultzGone&Back\">{{cite web |title=Why did Howard Schultz leave Starbucks, only to return eight years later? (SBUX) |url=https://www.investopedia.com/ask/answers/033015/why-did-howard-schultz-leave-starbucks-only-return-eight-years-later.asp |website=[[Investopedia]] |accessdate=June 5, 2018}}</ref> His aggressive expansion in Chinese markets has been credited with reconciling [[Chinese tea culture|the country's tea-culture]] with [[Coffee production in China|coffee consumption in China]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/goatsandsoda/2019/05/17/723193259/what-does-chinas-luckin-coffee-have-that-starbucks-doesnt|title=China's Luckin Coffee Tries To Conquer A Nation Of Tea Drinkers|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fortune.com/2019/12/30/starbucks-china-retail/|title=The Starbucks of China Is Paving a New Future for Retail. Will It Pay Off?|website=Fortune|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> On January 8, 2008, Schultz returned as CEO of Starbucks after an eight-year hiatus.<ref>[http://www.starbucks.com/aboutus/pressdesc.asp?id=818] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080117121159/http://www.starbucks.com/aboutus/pressdesc.asp?id=818|date=January 17, 2008}}</ref> Although the company was growing, that growth was largely dependent on opening new stores, while same-store sales were declining.<ref name=\"InvestopediaSchultzGone&Back\" /> He fired many executives,<ref name=\"InvestopediaSchultzGone&Back\" /><ref name=\"Taylor2016\">{{cite news |last1=Taylor |first1=Kate |title=Here's what happened the last time Howard Schultz stepped down as Starbucks CEO |url=http://www.businessinsider.com/last-time-schultz-stepped-down-as-starbucks-ceo-2016-12 |accessdate=June 5, 2018 |work=[[Business Insider]] |date=December 4, 2016}}</ref> closed down hundreds of weak stores,<ref name=\"InvestopediaSchultzGone&Back\" /><ref name=\"Taylor2016\" /> hired the company's first [[Chief Technology Officer]],<ref name=\"Taylor2016\" /> introduced the Starbucks Reward Card,<ref name=\"Taylor2016\" /> and temporarily closed all US locations to retrain employees in making espresso.<ref name=\"Taylor2016\" /> The company soon returned to [[organic growth]] and investor favor.<ref name=\"Taylor2016\" /> At this time, Schultz was earning a total compensation of $9,740,471, which included a base salary of $1,190,000, and options granted of $7,786,105.<ref>[http://www.equilar.com/CEO_Compensation/Starbucks_Howard_Schultz.php 2008 CEO Compensation for Howard Schultz] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090814181820/http://www.equilar.com/CEO_Compensation/Starbucks_Howard_Schultz.php |date=August 14, 2009 }}, Equilar.com</ref> From 2008 to 2017, Schultz oversaw nearly $100 billion added to the company's [[market capitalization]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/10/16/how-howard-schultz-conquered-self-doubt-to-build-starbucks.html|title=How Howard Schultz conquered self-doubt to build Starbucks into a $100 billion company|last=Scipioni|first=Jade|date=2019-10-16|website=CNBC|language=en|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref> From its IPO in 1992, his tenure saw to a 21,000% increase in [[shareholder value]], according to institutional reports.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://stories.starbucks.com/press/2018/howard-schultz-to-bid-farewell-to-starbucks/|title=Iconic Leader and Visionary Entrepreneur Howard Schultz to Bid Farewell to Starbucks after 40 Years|last=|first=|date=June 4, 2018|website=stories.starbucks.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\nSchultz again stepped down as CEO in December 2016, assuming the position of executive chairman and chief global strategist.<ref name=\"Taylor2016\" /> On June 4, 2018, Schultz announced that he would leave all positions at Starbucks, as he was considering amongst other options a campaign for president.<ref name=\"Meyersohn2018\">{{cite news |last1=Meyersohn |first1=Nathaniel |title=Howard Schultz steps down at Starbucks, may consider run for president |url=http://money.cnn.com/2018/06/04/news/companies/howard-schultz-starbucks/index.html |accessdate=June 5, 2018 |work=[[CNN Money]] |date=June 4, 2018}}</ref> Schultz is known for pioneering Starbucks' partnership with [[Arizona State University]], which allows all employees at Starbucks working 20 or more hours a week to qualify for free tuition through ASU's online courses.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://mastersofscale.com/howard-schultz-how-to-do-good-and-do-good-business/|title=Howard Schultz: How to do good and do good business {{!}} Masters of Scale podcast|work=WaitWhat|access-date=March 20, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> On November 1, 2013, it was announced that Schultz had stepped down from the board of Square, to be replaced by former [[Goldman Sachs]] executive [[David Viniar]].<ref>{{Cite news| url =http://www.entrepreneur.com/article/229728|title=Starbucks CEO Howard Schultz Steps Down From Square's Board of Directors |author=Kate Taylor|publisher=[[Entrepreneur (magazine)|Entrepreneur]] |date =November 1, 2013}}</ref> Schultz is a significant stakeholder in [[Jamba Juice]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.coriolisresearch.com/pdfs/coriolis_jamba_juice.pdf |title=Research Information on Jamba Juice |format=PDF |date= |accessdate=August 22, 2011}}</ref> Schultz's positioning Starbucks as a social hub is widely seen as introducing [[Third wave of coffee#History|the second wave]] of coffee culture in the U.S., particularly in Seattle.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.seattlemag.com/article/seattle-coffee-guide-evolution-coffee|title=Seattle Coffee Guide: The Evolution of Coffee|date=1969-12-31|website=Seattle Magazine|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/venessawong/the-man-who-brought-lattes-to-the-world-is-stepping-down|title=A Farewell To The Father Of The Latte|last=Wong|first=Vanessa|date=April 1, 2017|website=BuzzFeed Business|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\n===Seattle SuperSonics and Seattle Storm===\n{{Further|Seattle SuperSonics relocation to Oklahoma City}}\nIn January 2001, Schultz led a group of ten investors who bought the [[National Basketball Association]]'s [[Seattle SuperSonics]] and the [[Women's National Basketball Association]]'s [[Seattle Storm]] from the [[Ackerley Group]] for $200&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=20010112&slug=sale120|title=Sports - Sonics sale a 'dream' deal for Schultz - Seattle Times Newspaper|website=Community.seattletimes.nwsource.com|accessdate=February 3, 2019}}</ref> During his tenure as the SuperSonics team owner, he was criticized for his na\u00efvet\u00e9 and propensity to run the franchise as a business rather than a sports team.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nba/columns/story?columnist=hughes_frank&id=2525634 |title=Why Schultz tuned out and sold out the Sonics |publisher=Sports.espn.go.com |date=July 21, 2006 |accessdate=August 22, 2011}}</ref> Schultz feuded with player [[Gary Payton]], feeling that Payton disrespected him and the team by not showing up to the first day of training camp in 2002.<ref>{{Cite news| url =http://www.thestreet.com/story/12287415/1/seattle-super-bowl-scores-points-for-paul-allen-sacks-howard-schultz.html|title=Seattle Super Bowl Scores Points for Paul Allen, Sacks Howard Schultz|author=Jason Notte|publisher=[[TheStreet.com]] |date = February 1, 2014}}</ref> In February 2006, he stated that the Sonics needed $200&nbsp;million to renovate [[KeyArena]] or build a new arena for the team, and if the [[Washington State Legislature]] would not approve this, he would look to sell or move the team.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.seattlepi.com/news/article/Sonics-owner-grows-impatient-1194645.php|title=Sonics owner grows impatient|first1=Gary|last1=Washburn|first2=P.-I.|last2=Reporter|date=February 2, 2006|website=Seattlepi.com|accessdate=February 3, 2019}}</ref> On July 18, 2006, Schultz sold the team to [[Clay Bennett (businessman)|Clay Bennett]], chairman of the [[Professional Basketball Club LLC]], an [[Oklahoma City]] ownership group, for $350&nbsp;million, after having failed to convince the city of [[Seattle]] to provide public funding to build a new arena in the Greater Seattle area to replace [[KeyArena]]. At the time of the team's sale, it was speculated that the new owners would move the team to their city some time after the 2006\u20132007 NBA season.<ref>[http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/sports/2003136585_sonics19m.html seattletimes.nwsource.com]. URL last accessed July 18, 2006.</ref>\n\nSchultz filed a lawsuit against Bennett \u2013 in April 2008 \u2013 to rescind the July 2006 sale based on what Schultz claimed was fraud and intentional misrepresentation. However, Schultz dropped the lawsuit in August 2008. When Bennett purchased the SuperSonics and its sister franchise in the WNBA, the Seattle Storm, for $350&nbsp;million, he agreed to a stipulation that he would make a \"good-faith best effort\" for one year to keep both teams in Seattle. The sincerity of the good-faith effort was widely disputed by the way Bennett acted and by direct quotes from his partner [[Aubrey McClendon]]. On January 8, 2008, Bennett sold the Storm to Force 10 Hoops, LLC, an ownership group of four Seattle women, which kept the team in Seattle.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/sonics/2004349361_schultz15.html |work=The Seattle Times |title=Howard Schultz plans to sue Clay Bennett to get Sonics back |first=Percy |last=Allen |date=April 15, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080419015637/http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/sonics/2004349361_schultz15.html |archivedate=April 19, 2008 }}</ref> On July 2, 2008, the city of Seattle reached a settlement with the new ownership group and the SuperSonics [[Seattle SuperSonics relocation to Oklahoma City|moved to Oklahoma City]] and became the [[Oklahoma City Thunder|Thunder]] for the [[2008\u201309 NBA season]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.seattlepi.com/basketball/369313_trial03.html |title=Sonics are Oklahoma City-bound |publisher=seattlepi.com |date=July 2, 2008 |accessdate=August 22, 2011}}</ref> The sale to the out-of-state owners considerably damaged Schultz's popularity in Seattle.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mynorthwest.com/?nid=76&sid=70406 |title=Sonics Settlement |publisher=Mynorthwest.com |date=April 6, 2011 |accessdate=November 24, 2011}}</ref> In a local newspaper poll, Schultz was judged \"most responsible\" for the team leaving the city.<ref>{{cite web|title=Poll Results|url=http://www.seattlepi.com/polls/popup.asp?pollID=2983 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110131185345/http://www.seattlepi.com/polls/popup.asp?pollID=2983 |url-status=dead |archive-date=January 31, 2011 |accessdate=February 13, 2011 }}</ref> In 2019 Schultz accepted some responsibility for what happened to the SuperSonics during his tenure.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/2020-election/schultz-s-reign-nba-owner-was-fiasco-would-2020-campaign-n964026|title=Schultz's reign as an NBA owner was a fiasco. Would a 2020 campaign be any different?|website=NBC News|accessdate=February 3, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Author===\n[[File:Starbucks CEO visits Marines and Sailors at Camp Pendleton 141113-M-MV301-009.jpg|thumb|Schultz signing a copy of ''For Love of Country'' in California's [[Marine Corps Base Camp Pendleton|Camp Pedleton]], 2014.]]\nSchultz has written four books, three of which incorporate [[:Category:Show business memoirs|business memoir]]-style narratives. His first book, ''Pour Your Heart Into It: How Starbucks Built a Company One Cup at a Time'' was written in 1997 with Dori Jones Yang. ''[[Goodreads]]'' gave his first book 4/5 stars, calling it a \"definitive chronicle of [Starbucks].\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.goodreads.com/work/best_book/90329-pour-your-heart-into-it-how-starbucks-built-a-company-one-cup-at-a-tim|title=Pour Your Heart Into It|website=www.goodreads.com|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref> His second book ''Onward: How Starbucks Fought for Its Life Without Losing Its Soul'', co-written with Joanne Gordon, was published in 2011. Jeff Bailey, of the [[Los Angeles Times|''Los Angles Times'']], called the book \"self-flattering\" and criticized its \"mostly perfunctory account of [[Criticism of Starbucks|Starbucks\u2019 actual problems]].\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/books/la-et-book-20110423-story.html|title=Book review: 'Onward: How Starbucks Fought for Its Life Without Losing Its Soul' by Howard Schultz|date=2011-04-23|website=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref> ''Goodreads'' gave his second book 3.8/5 stars.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Yardley|first=William|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/08/27/us/27starbucks.html|title=There\u2019s One on Every Corner, but None Like This|date=2011-08-26|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-13|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.goodreads.com/work/best_book/14030099-onward-how-starbucks-fought-for-its-life-without-losing-its-soul|title=Onward|website=www.goodreads.com|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref> [[Publishers Weekly|Publisher's Weekly]] called the book \"a personal, suspenseful, and surprisingly open account\" of the rise of Starbucks.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.publishersweekly.com/978-1-60529-288-5|title=Nonfiction Book Review: Onward: How Starbucks Fought for Its Life Without Losing Its Soul by Howard Schultz with Joanne Gordon, Rodale, $25.99 (368p) ISBN 978-1-60529-288-5|website=PublishersWeekly.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref> ''[[Kirkus Reviews]]'' praised the book's \"immense detail\" but critiqued Shultz's coverage of \"outside criticisms of his performance\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/howard-schultz/onward-starbucks/|title=Review: Onward: How Starbucks Fought for Its Life Without Losing Its Soul|last=|first=|date=March 2, 2011|website=Kirkus Reviews|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 1, 2020}}</ref> ''[[Fast Company]]'' placed ''Onward'' within the top five books that \"[predicted] the future of workplace leadership\" in 2014.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fastcompany.com/3032122/5-books-that-predict-the-future-of-workplace-leadership|title=5 Books That Predict The Future Of Workplace Leadership|last=Crowley|first=Mark C.|date=2014-06-25|website=Fast Company|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref> All sale proceeds from the book were donated to the Starbucks Foundation, the firm's main charity.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.starbucks.com/onward|title=Onward|last=|first=|date=|website=Starbucks Coffee Company|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 1, 2020|quote=Buy Onward now and all of Howard Schultz's proceeds will go to the Starbucks Foundation}}</ref> His third book ''For Love of Country'', co-written with [[Rajiv Chandrasekaran]], was published in 2014. His first non-business book, ''For Love of Country'' received positive reviews with ''[[The New York Times Book Review]]'' calling it \"well-written\" and \"formidable.\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Wright|first=James|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/03/15/books/review/for-love-of-country-by-howard-schultz-and-rajiv-chandrasekaran.html|title=\u2018For Love of Country,\u2019 by Howard Schultz and Rajiv Chandrasekaran|date=2015-03-12|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-13|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, he published his fourth book, ''From the Ground Up: A Journey to Reimagine the Promise of America''.<ref>{{cite website|url=http://chamberbusinessnews.com/2019/02/04/howard-schultz-visits-asu-shares-his-life-story-encourages-bipartisanship/|publisher=Chamber Business News|title=Howard Schultz visits ASU, shares his life story, encourages bipartisanship|date= February 4, 2019|accessdate= February 5, 2019}}</ref> The book was widely seen as a presidential candidate memoir as it was published right before the [[2020 United States presidential election]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/news/current/howard-schultz-against-the-hecklers|title=Howard Schultz Against the Hecklers|website=The New Yorker|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref> Due to a backlash regarding his possible candidacy [[Spoiler effect|splitting the Democratic vote]], his book received 1.9/5 stars on [[Amazon (company)|Amazon]], after disgruntled Democratic voters took to the comments section to air their grievances, \"largely [unrelated] to the content of the book.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/howard-schultz-book-bad-reviews-amazon-2019-1|title=People are flooding the Amazon page for Howard Schultz's new book with negative comments after the ex-Starbucks CEO said he was 'seriously considering' running for president|last=Hanbury|first=Mary|website=Business Insider|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref> A book promotion stop at [[Harvard University]] led to a small student protest.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thecrimson.com/article/2019/2/6/schultz-presidential-run-book-tour/|title=Former Starbucks CEO Howard Schultz Draws Protesters at Brattle Theatre Talk {{!}} News {{!}} The Harvard Crimson|website=www.thecrimson.com|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref> ''The New York Times'', in line with many newspapers, compared the book with [[Michael Bloomberg]]'s similarly themed book, ''Bloomberg by Bloomberg''.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Fountain|first=Ben|url=https://www.nybooks.com/articles/2019/05/23/howard-schultz-michael-bloomberg-billionaires/|title=O Billionaires!|date=2019-05-23|access-date=2020-04-13|language=en|issn=0028-7504}}</ref> ''From the Ground Up'' was a featured on ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]''<nowiki/>'s bestseller list in February,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/best-selling-books-week-ended-feb-9-11550244453|title=Best-Selling Books Week Ended Feb. 9|date=2019-02-15|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=2020-04-13|language=en-US|issn=0099-9660}}</ref> and was listed as a ''[[The New York Times Best Seller list|The New York Times]]'' [[The New York Times Best Seller list|bestseller]] for 2019.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.nytimes.com/books/best-sellers/2019/02/17/hardcover-nonfiction/|title=Hardcover Nonfiction Books - Best Sellers - Feb. 17, 2019 - The New York Times|date=|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-13|url-status=live|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|quote=From the Ground Up by Howard Schultz with Joanne GordonRandom House: The former chief executive of Starbucks recounts his journey to success and shares the inspirational stories of others.}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.goodhousekeeping.com/life/entertainment/g29811033/best-selling-books-2019/|title=44 Best-Selling Books of 2019 Everyone's Talking About|last=Schumer|first=Lizz|date=2019-12-03|website=Good Housekeeping|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref> ''[[Reuters]]'' rated the book highly, yet called it \"caffeine free\" for its inability to \"harness his business success\" in a potential White House run.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.breakingviews.com/features/review/|title=Caffeine free|last=Chon|first=Gina|date=8 February 2019|website=Reuters|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=3 April 2020|quote=The former Starbucks chief\u2019s tough boyhood and corporate rise inspires in \u201cFrom the Ground Up.\u201d Workers helped by his policies are also stirring. But this message is oddly absent from his White House rollout. The candidate needs to harness his business success more effectively.}}</ref> ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' called the book \"stunningly boring.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/politics/politics-features/howard-schultz-trump-786516/|title=Howard Schultz: America's New Banality Supervillain|last=Taibbi|first=Matt|last2=Taibbi|first2=Matt|date=2019-01-30|website=Rolling Stone|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\n==Political views==\n[[File:Howard Schultz (33059510518).jpg|thumb|Shultz in speaking at [[Arizona State University]] in 2019]]\nIn 2012, Schultz began making public statements that led to press speculation that he would run for [[President of the United States]]. These included an initiative, announced via an [[open letter]] published in various newspapers, that on one day (December 27, 2012), Starbucks employees were asked to write \"come together\" on all cups distributed, to encourage bipartisanship in the federal government.<ref>{{cite web |title=Starbucks CEO Howard Schultz Needs to Run for President Already |url=http://nymag.com/intelligencer/2012/12/howard-schultz-president-starbucks-2016.html |first=Dan |last=Amira |work=New York Magazine Intelligencer blog |date=December 26, 2012}}</ref> That same year, he also had Starbucks express support for [[Washington (state)|Washington state]]'s [[Washington Referendum 74|Referendum 74]], which legalized [[same-sex marriage]] in that state.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/frederickallen/2013/03/22/howard-schultz-to-anti-gay-marriage-starbucks-shareholder-you-can-sell-your-shares/#4aed60586511|title=Howard Schultz to Anti-Gay-Marriage Starbucks Shareholder: 'You Can Sell Your Shares'|last=Allen|first=Frederick E.|website=Forbes|access-date=April 24, 2016}}</ref> There was speculation that he would run in the [[2016 United States presidential election|2016 US presidential election]], but he wrote a ''[[The New York Times|New York Times]]'' op-ed in August 2015 denying this, stating, \"Despite the encouragement of others, I have no intention of entering the presidential fray. I'm not done serving at Starbucks.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Starbucks CEO Howard Schultz Won't Run For President |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/abrambrown/2015/08/06/starbucks-ceo-howard-schultz-says-he-wont-run-for-president/#3632e94716fa |first=Abram |last=Brown |work=Forbes |date=August 6, 2015}}</ref> He ultimately endorsed Democratic candidate [[Hillary Clinton]] in that election.<ref>Long, H. [http://money.cnn.com/2016/09/07/news/economy/howard-schultz-hillary-clinton/ CNN] September 7, 2016.</ref>\n\nDuring his 2019 exploratory bid for the presidency, Schultz framed his candidacy as that of a socially liberal [[deficit hawk]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2019/01/29/howard-schultz-says-he-can-win-support-silent-majority-silent-majority-doesnt-really-exist/|title=Howard Schultz says he can win the support of a \u2018silent majority.\u2019 The \u2018silent majority\u2019 doesn\u2019t really exist.|last=|first=|date=January 29, 2019|work=The Washington Post|access-date=April 9, 2019}}</ref> Schultz supports nonpartisan immigration policy, [[free trade]], [[Balanced budget|fiscal discipline]], comprehensive tax reform, gun control, same-sex marriage, and more generally, [[bipartisanship]] across the political spectrum.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/06/05/howard-schultz-on-hot-political-topics-gun-control-taxes-immigration.html|title=Here's what Howard Schultz says about hot political topics as speculation swirls about a possible presidential run|last=Whitten|first=Sarah|date=2018-06-05|website=CNBC|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Stevens|first=Matt|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/09/06/us/politics/howard-schultz-drops-out-2020.html|title=Howard Schultz, Former Starbucks Chief, Won\u2019t Run for President in 2020|date=2019-09-06|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-13|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> In January 2019, ''The Washington Post'' wrote that Schultz \"has not offered many specifics on his policy proposals.\"<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/budding-independent-howard-schultz-aims-most-of-his-ire-at-democrats/2019/01/30/28210ab4-24a7-11e9-ad53-824486280311_story.html|title=Budding independent Howard Schultz aims most of his ire at Democrats|last=|first=|date=2019|work=The Washington Post|access-date=}}</ref> In June 2018, Schultz stated in an interview that he thought the [[National debt of the United States|national debt]] is \"the greatest threat domestically to the country\" and that \"we have to go after entitlements.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Howard Schultz: The $21 trillion national debt is the \u2018greatest threat domestically to the country\u2019 |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/06/05/howard-schultz-21-trillion-debt-is-biggest-threat-to-us-domestically.html |first=Kevin |last=Breuninger |date=June 5, 2018 |work=CNBC}}</ref> Schultz has described [[Medicare For All]] as \"not American.\"<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/01/29/politics/howard-schultz-medicare-for-all-cnntv/index.html|title=Schultz defends criticism of Medicare-for-all proposal|author=Veronica Stracqualursi|website=CNN|access-date=January 30, 2019}}</ref> Asked in January 2019 what his healthcare proposal was, Schultz answered, \"I don't have a plan today. I'm not yet running for president.\"<ref name=\":0\" /> Schultz opposed [[Alexandria Ocasio-Cortez]]'s proposal to raise the [[marginal tax rate]] on income over $10 million to 70%, saying it was \"punitive\" and contrary to the [[American Dream]].<ref name=\":0\" /> Schultz said he supported \"comprehensive tax reform\".<ref name=\":0\" /> He supported a pathway to citizenship for illegal immigrants who had entered the U.S. as children.<ref name=\":0\" /> He called for greater border security, but opposed President Trump's proposal of a border wall.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n===British economy===\nSpeaking to [[CNBC]] in February 2009 about his concerns over the [[Great Recession|global economic crisis]], Schultz said that \"the place that concerns us the most is western Europe, and specifically the UK. The UK is in a spiral\", expressing concern with the levels of [[Unemployment in the United Kingdom|unemployment]] and [[consumer confidence#GfK Consumer Confidence Barometer (UK)|consumer confidence]] in the [[United Kingdom]].<ref name=\"guardian\">{{Cite news|last=Wintour|first=Patrick|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2009/feb/19/peter-mandelson-starbucks-economy|title=Mandelson and Starbucks clash on UK economy|date=February 19, 2009|work=The Guardian|accessdate=March 18, 2009|location=London}}</ref> [[Peter Mandelson]], then-[[Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy|British Business Secretary]], responded saying that the United Kingdom was \"not spiralling, although I've noticed Starbucks is in a great deal of trouble\", and suggesting that Schultz was projecting his own company's trouble in the United Kingdom onto the wider national economy.<ref name=\"guardian\" /> An official comment from Starbucks read that \"It is a difficult economic situation in the US and around the world. Please be assured that Starbucks has no intention of criticising the economic situation in the UK. We are all in this together and as a global business we are committed to each and every market we serve.\"<ref name=\"guardian\" />\n\n===2020 presidential campaign effort===\nAfter Schultz stepped down from Starbucks, political commentators speculated whether he would run in the [[2020 United States presidential election]],<ref>Gelles, David (June 4, 2018). [https://www.nytimes.com/2018/06/04/business/ceos-president-howard-schultz-starbucks.html Schultz 2020? Other C.E.O.s Will Be Watching Closely] The New York Times. Retrieved December 6, 2018.</ref><ref>Schwartz, Brian (November 9, 2018). [https://www.cnbc.com/2018/11/09/ex-starbucks-ceo-howard-schultz-builds-elite-pr-team-as-he-mulls-white-house-run.html Former Starbucks CEO Howard Schultz assembles an elite PR team as he considers running for president] CNBC. Retrieved December 6, 2018.</ref> including encouragement from a [[draft (politics)|draft movement]] called Ready for Schultz.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://readyforschultz.com/|title=Ready for Schultz 2020|website=Readyforschultz.com}}</ref> On January 27, 2019, he stated in an interview with ''[[60 Minutes]]'' that he was exploring a run for president as an [[independent politician|independent candidate]], and that he considered running as a centrist.<ref name=\"hill\">{{cite news|author=Emily Birnbaum|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/campaign/427184-howard-schultz-makes-twitter-debut-amid-2020-speculation|title=Howard Schultz makes Twitter debut amid 2020 speculation|date=January 27, 2019|work=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]|accessdate=January 27, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/01/21/politics/howard-schultz-starbucks-2020/index.html|title=Former Starbucks chief exploring independent 2020 bid|author1=Eli Watkins|author2=Maeve Reston|author3=Cristina Alesci|author4=Poppy Harlow|work=CNN|date=January 21, 2019|accessdate=January 21, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-47033483|title=Starbucks tycoon roasted over 2020 plan|date=January 29, 2019|access-date=January 30, 2019|language=en-GB}}</ref> Schultz's proposed independent candidacy was widely condemned by Democrats who argued that Schultz's third-party candidacy would help to re-elect President Trump by [[Spoiler effect|splitting the vote of those opposed]] to the president.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://fortune.com/2019/01/27/democrats-worry-howard-schultz-run-president/|title=Democrats Say Possible Howard Schultz Presidential Bid Could Help Trump Win Second Term|website=Fortune.com|language=en|access-date=January 30, 2019}}</ref> President Trump himself appeared to goad Schultz into running, tweeting that Schultz did not have the \"guts.\"<ref name=\":1\" /> University of Virginia political scientist [[Larry Sabato]] said that Schultz's candidacy was likely to benefit Trump.<ref name=\":1\" /> In response to claims that his candidacy would benefit Trump, Schultz said, \"Nobody wants to see Donald Trump removed from office more than me.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/01/29/howard-schultz-says-his-presidential-run-wont-boost-trump.html|title=Howard Schultz says his presidential run won't boost Trump|last=Higgins|first=Tucker|date=January 28, 2019|website=Cnbc.com|access-date=January 30, 2019}}</ref> A February 2019 poll indicated that a Schultz third-party candidacy would strengthen Trump's re-election prospects, as Schultz would draw more support from Democrats than Republicans.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-02-07/schultz-s-independent-bid-in-2020-would-help-trump-poll-finds|title=Schultz's Independent Bid in 2020 Would Help Trump, Poll Finds|website=www.bloomberg.com|access-date=February 10, 2019}}</ref> Later that month, Schultz said he would consider dropping out of the race if the Democrats nominated \"a centrist Democrat.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/howard-schultz-challenge-to-democrats-nominate-a-centrist-for-president-and-ill-abandon-my-independent-campaign/2019/02/14/208c25de-309d-11e9-813a-0ab2f17e305b_story.html|title=Howard Schultz\u2019 challenge to Democrats: Nominate a centrist for president and I\u2019ll abandon my independent campaign|author1=Michael Scherer|author2=Tracy Jan|date=February 14, 2019|work=The Washington Post|access-date=February 17, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAfter announcing that he was exploring a presidential bid in January 2019, Schultz spent most of the time in his first media interviews attacking Democrats' economic and tax policies.\"<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/howard-schultz-calls-alexandria-ocasio-cortez-a-bit-misinformed-when-it-comes-to-taxing-the-wealthy/2019/01/29/b00db19e-23c5-11e9-90cd-dedb0c92dc17_story.html|title=Howard Schultz knocks Ocasio-Cortez, Warren and Harris for \u2018extreme,\u2019 \u2018punitive\u2019 and \u2018not American\u2019 policies|last=|first=|date=2019|work=The Washington Post|access-date=}}</ref> In May 2019, Schultz delayed his 2020 decision, citing [[Joe Biden]] as one of the main reasons.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.foxbusiness.com/business-leaders/howard-schultz-delays-decision-on-2020-biden-the-factor|title=Howard Schultz delays decision on 2020, Biden the factor|first=Charlie|last=Gasparino|date=May 15, 2019|website=FOXBusiness}}</ref> On September 6, Schultz officially ruled out a Presidential run, stating that it wasn't the best way to \"serve our country at this time.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/09/06/politics/howard-schultz-presidential-campaign-2020/index.html|title=Howard Schultz drops plans to run as independent candidate in 2020|first= Veronica|last=Stracqualursi|date=September 6, 2019|website=CNNPolitics}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and honors==\n[[File:Howard Schultz and Leroy Petry 180510-D-SW162-2241 (27170721607).jpg|right|thumb|Schultz receiving the \"Distinguished Business Leadership Award\", during the [[Atlantic Council]]'s Distinguished Leadership Awards dinner in [[Washington, D.C.]], 2018]]\nIn 1998, Schultz received the 'Israel 50th Anniversary Tribute Award'.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19980819&slug=2767425|title=Starbucks' Schultz To Receive Israel Award|date=19 August 1998|work=[[Seattle Times Newspaper]]}}</ref> In 1999 AIDs Action awarded Schultz the National Leadership Award for philanthropic and educational efforts to battle AIDS.<ref>[http://investing.businessweek.com/research/stocks/people/person.asp?personId=194300&symbol=SBUX.O Howard M. Schultz Biography] [[Businessweek]] Data is as current as the most recent Definitive Proxy</ref> Schultz was named ''[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]]'' magazine's 2011 \"Businessperson of the Year\" for his initiatives in the economy and job market.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://money.cnn.com/galleries/2011/fortune/1111/gallery.business_person_year.fortune/2.html|title=2011 Businessperson of the Year - 1. Howard M. Schultz (2) - FORTUNE|date=November 17, 2011|publisher=Money.cnn.com|accessdate=November 24, 2011}}</ref>\n\nSchultz spoke at the 2017 [[Arizona State University]] commencement ceremony and was presented with an [[Honorary degree|honorary]] Doctor of humane letters degree.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://asunow.asu.edu/20170313-asu-news-commencement-speaker-starbucks-ceo-howard-schultz|title=Starbucks Chairman and CEO Howard Schultz to speak at ASU commencement|date=March 13, 2017|work=ASU Now: Access, Excellence, Impact|access-date=March 23, 2017|language=en}}</ref> In November 2017, the [[NAACP Legal Defense and Educational Fund]] presented Schultz with the National Equal Justice Award.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.naacpldf.org/press-release/moment-now-naacp-legal-31st-annual-national-equal-justice-awards|title=The Moment is Now: NAACP legal 31st Annual National Equal Justice Awards|website=Naacpldf.org|language=en|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171222051141/http://www.naacpldf.org/press-release/moment-now-naacp-legal-31st-annual-national-equal-justice-awards|archive-date=December 22, 2017|access-date=December 20, 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Philanthropy ==\nIn 1996, Howard and Sheri Schultz co-founded the Schultz Family Foundation, which currently supports two national initiatives.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/georgeanders/2016/03/01/howard-schultzs-stormy-crusades-the-starbucks-boss-opens-up/|title=Howard Schultz's Stormy Crusades: The Starbucks Boss Opens Up|last=Anders|first=George|work=forbes.com}}</ref> Onward Youth is aimed at promoting employment for young people between the ages of 16 and 24 who are not in school and not working.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/07/13/business/starbucks-and-other-corporations-to-announce-plan-to-curb-unemployment-of-young-people.html|title=Starbucks and Other Corporations to Announce Plan to Curb Unemployment of Young People|date=July 13, 2015|work=The New York Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/07/13/opinion/connecting-young-people-with-jobs.html|title=Connecting Young People With Jobs|date=July 13, 2015|work=The New York Times}}</ref> Onward Veterans aims to help [[post-9/11]] military veterans to successfully transition to civilian life.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://philanthropy.com/article/Starbuckss-Schultz-Opens-New/228699|title=Starbucks's Schultz Opens New Front in Helping Veterans Enter Work Force|date=March 23, 2015|work=philanthropy.com}}</ref> In March 2014, the foundation pledged [[United States dollar|US$]]30 million to veterans' aiming to reintegrate into society.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://philanthropynewsdigest.org/news/schultz-family-foundation-pledges-30-million-for-veterans|title=Schultz Family Foundation Pledges $30 Million for Veterans|last=Candid|website=Philanthropy News Digest (PND)|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> In October 2015 Schultz led an initiative at Starbucks, in conjunction with his foundation, to hire 10,000 veterans and military spouses by 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://philanthropynw.org/news/starbucks-schultz-family-foundation-muster-allies-veterans|title=Starbucks, Schultz Family Foundation Muster Allies for Veterans|date=2015-10-13|website=Philanthropy Northwest|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://stories.starbucks.com/stories/2014/starbucks-and-schultz-family-foundation-give-young-job-seekers-a-roadmap/|title=Starbucks and the Schultz Family Foundation Give Young Job Seekers a Roadmap to Opportunity|last=|first=|date=September 15, 2014|website=stories.starbucks.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 10, 2020}}</ref> A month later, his foundation issued a grant to help 200 veterans attend the Silver School of Social Work at [[New York University]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://socialwork.nyu.edu/news/2015/11/11/grant-from-the-schultz-family-foundation-to-help-300-veterans-and-their-family-members-enroll-and-study-at-nyus-silver-school-of-social-work.html|title=Grant from the Schultz foundation to help 300 veterans and their family members enroll at NYU|last=|first=|date=November 11, 2015|website=New York University|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2017, it awarded a $143,000 grant to the National Association of Veteran-Serving Organizations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.navso.org/news/schultz-family-foundation-awards-143000-grant-navso|title=The Schultz Family Foundation awards $143,000 grant to NAVSO|date=2017-09-08|website=National Association of Veteran Serving Organizations|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> The [[Local Initiatives Support Corporation]] (LISC) received a grant for an undisclosed amount in July 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lisc.org/rural/regional-stories/rural-lisc-receives-grant-support-youth-employment-schultz-family-foundation/|title=Rural LISC Receives Grant to Support Youth Employment from the Schultz Family Foundation {{!}} LISC Rural LISC|website=Local Initiatives Support Corporation|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> In January 2019, the foundation donated $7.5 million to expand care for veterans in the United States.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnybj.com/schultz-family-foundation-donates-to-su-ivmf/|title=Schultz Family Foundation donates $7.5M to SU\u2019s IVMF to expand veteran career-preparation program|website=www.cnybj.com|language=en-us|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> During the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]], the Schultz Family Foundation raised $4 million to help restaurant workers impacted by the pandemic.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bizjournals.com/seattle/news/2020/04/06/howard-schultz-fund-laid-off-workers-seattle.html|title=Howard Schultz launches fund for laid off restaurant workers in King County|last=Payne|first=Patti|date=|website=www.bizjournals.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 2, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.columbian.com/news/2020/apr/06/first-doc-inmate-tests-positive-for-virus-in-washington/|title=First DOC inmate tests positive for virus in Washington|website=The Columbian|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 1982, Schultz married Sheri Kersch with whom he has two children.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.yahoo.com/lifestyle/everything-know-howard-schultzs-wife-183800623.html|title=Everything We Know About Howard Schultz's Wife|accessdate=January 31, 2019}}</ref> They live in Seattle's [[Madison Park, Seattle|Madison Park]] neighborhood, having previously lived near [[Madrona, Seattle|Madrona]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Kugiya |first=Hugo |date=December 15, 1996 |title=Seattle's Coffee King |url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19961215&slug=2365201 |work=The Seattle Times}}</ref> \n\n== Books ==\n\n*{{Citation|author1=Schultz, Howard|author2=Yang, Dori Jones|title=Pour Your Heart Into It: How Starbucks Built a Company One Cup at a Time|place=New York|publisher=Hyperion|year=1997|isbn=0786863153|url=https://archive.org/details/pouryourheartint00howa}}\n*{{Citation|author1=Schultz, Howard|author2=Gordon, Joanne|title=Onward: How Starbucks Fought for Its Life without Losing Its Soul|place=New York|publisher=Rodale|year=2011|isbn=9781605292885|url=https://archive.org/details/onwardhowstarbuc00schu}}\n*{{citation|last1=Schultz|first1=Howard|last2=Gordon|first2=Joanne|title=From the Ground Up: A Journey to Reimagine the Promise of America|place=New York|publisher=Random House|year=2019|isbn=9780525509448}}\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Starbucks#History|History fo Starbucks]]\n* [[Northern Michigan University#Notable alumni|List of Northern Michigan University alumni]]\n* [[The World's Billionaires|List of ''Forbes''<nowiki/>' World Billionaires]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|Howard Schultz}}\n\n* [http://www.schultzfamilyfoundation.org/#tab-switcher-1 Schultz Family Foundation]\n*{{C-SPAN|Howard Schultz}}\n* https://web.archive.org/web/20180928005543/https://www.arte.tv/de/videos/073442-000-A/starbucks-ungefiltert/\n* [https://www.npr.org/2017/09/28/551874532/live-episode-starbucks-howard-schultz How I Built This - Live Episode! Starbucks: Howard Schultz] (audio interview)\n\n{{Starbucks}}\n{{Seattle SuperSonics}}\n{{Seattle Storm}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Schultz, Howard}}\n[[Category:1953 births]]\n[[Category:American billionaires]]\n[[Category:American business writers]]\n[[Category:American chairmen of corporations]]\n[[Category:American chief executives of food industry companies]]\n[[Category:American financial company founders]]\n[[Category:American financiers]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from New York City]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Seattle]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople in coffee]]\n[[Category:Canarsie High School alumni]]\n[[Category:Coffee in Seattle]]\n[[Category:Directors of Starbucks]]\n[[Category:Jewish American sportspeople]]\n[[Category:Jewish American writers]]\n[[Category:LGBT rights activists from the United States]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:New York (state) Independents]]\n[[Category:Northern Michigan University alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Canarsie, Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:Seattle Storm owners]]\n[[Category:Seattle SuperSonics owners]]\n[[Category:Starbucks people]]\n[[Category:Washington (state) Independents]]\n[[Category:Women's National Basketball Association executives]]\n[[Category:Writers from New York City]]\n[[Category:Writers from Seattle]]\n[[Category:American people of Austrian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Russian-Jewish descent]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American businessman}}\n{{for|the American television producer|Howard Schultz (producer)}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Howard Schultz\n| image              = Howard Schultz by Gage Skidmore.jpg\n| caption            = Schultz in 2019\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1953|7|19}}\n| birth_place        = [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], U.S.\n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| alma_mater         = [[Northern Michigan University]]\n| occupation         = {{hlist|Businessman|author|philanthropist}}\n| years_active       = 1986\u2013present\n| known_for          = Introducing [[Third wave of coffee#History|second wave coffee culture]] to the U.S. with leadership of Starbucks\n| networth           = [[US$]]4.1 billion (November 2019)\n| title              = Chairman emeritus, [[Starbucks]]\n| term               = 2018\u2013present\n| predecessor        = [[Orin C. Smith|Orin Smith]]\n| successor          = [[Kevin Johnson (executive)|Kevin Johnson]]\n| party              = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] (before 2019)<br>[[Independent politician|Independent]] (2019\u2013present)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/2020-election/howard-schultz-says-he-s-not-democrat-surprised-party-backlash-n964476 |title=Howard Schultz says he's not a Democrat, surprised by backlash|date=January 30, 2019 |first=Allan |last=Smith |work=MSNBC |accessdate=January 30, 2019}}</ref>\n| spouse             = {{marriage|Sheri Kersch|1982}}\n| children           = 2\n| website            = {{URL|howardschultz.com|Official website}}\n}}\n'''Howard D. Schultz''' (born July 19, 1953)<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.upi.com/Entertainment_News/2019/07/19/Famous-birthdays-for-July-19-Brian-May-Anthony-Edwards/2631563201127/|title= Famous birthdays for July 19: Brian May, Anthony Edwardsl|agency=[[United Press International]]|date=July 19, 2019|accessdate=August 7, 2019|archivedate=July 19, 2019|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20190719123258/https://www.upi.com/Entertainment_News/2019/07/19/Famous-birthdays-for-July-19-Brian-May-Anthony-Edwards/2631563201127/|url-status=live|quote=Businessman Howard Schultz in 1953 (age 66)}}</ref> is an American businessman, author, and philanthropist. He served as the chairman and [[chief executive officer]] (CEO) of the [[Starbucks|Starbucks Coffee Corporation]] for more than two decades; first from 1986 to 2000, and then from 2008 to 2017. After stepping down as CEO, Schultz stayed at the company from 2017 to 2018 as its executive chairman overseeing Starbuck's philanthropic and charitable giving arm. From 2001 to 2006, he owned the [[Seattle SuperSonics]], a basketball franchise that he sold for [[United States dollar|US$]]350 million to [[Clay Bennett (businessman)|Clay Bennett]], who moved the team to Oklahoma creating the [[Oklahoma City Thunder]]. <!--The lack of citations is purposeful. Refer to Wikipedia:Manual of Style/Lead section#Citations for more information. Wikipedia allows there to be little to no citations in the lead area if it is cited within the main body. If there is something in the lede not cited in the main part drop a {{not found in body}} citation needed tag and it will be addressed.--><!--Keep 4 balanced paragraphs (of 4-5 sentences each) per MOS:LAYOUT.-->\n\nBorn and raised in the [[Brooklyn|Brooklyn borough]] of New York, Schultz graduated from [[Northern Michigan University]] in 1975. After briefly selling office equipment door-to-door one of his early clients, the then coffeehouse startup Starbucks, onboarded him as their marketing head in 1982. A business trip to [[Milan|Milan, Italy]] and [[Coffee in Italy|the city's coffee culture]] inspired him to open ''Il Giornale'', a specialty coffeeshop that quickly merged with Starbucks during the late-1980s. Shultz pushed the new company to sell more than [[Coffee bean|coffee beans]] and equipment, quickly establishing a large network of stores that served [[espresso]], [[coffee]], teas, and casual food. Following large-scale distribution deals \u2013 particularly with major hotels, groceries, and bookstores \u2013 Starbucks became [[List of coffeehouse chains|the largest coffee-house chain]] in the world.<!--Cited in body.--> Shultz took the company [[Initial public offering|public]] in 1992 and used a $271 million valuation to double their store count. He stepped down in 2000 to focus on Starbuck's international expansion, succeeded by [[Orin C. Smith|Orin Smith]].<!--Second tenure as CEO, 2008 to 2017.-->\n\nDuring the [[Financial crisis of 2007\u201308|2008 financial crisis]], Schultz returned as chief executive to stabilize the company after years of unsustainable growth. He led a mass-firing of executives, shuttered hundreds of weak stores, and temporarily closed all U.S. stores to retrain employees in making espresso. Shultz orchestrated multiple [[Mergers and acquisitions|acquisitions]] of American and Chinese beverage companies and introduced a national [[loyalty program]]. His aggressive expansion in Chinese markets has been credited with reconciling [[Chinese tea culture|the country's tea-culture]] with [[Coffee production in China|coffee consumption in China]]. Schultz's positioning Starbucks as a social hub is widely seen as introducing [[Third wave of coffee#History|the second wave]] of coffee culture in the U.S., particularly in Seattle. His second tenure sustained both [[Criticism of Starbucks|significant criticism]] and growth, ultimately adding nearly $100 billion in [[market capitalization]] to the company, a 21,000% increase in [[shareholder value]]. <!--Cited in body.-->Schultz was succeeded by [[Kevin Johnson (executive)|Kevin Johnson]] as CEO in April 2017, and has, since 2018, retained the title \"Chairman emeritus\" of Starbucks. \n\nSchultz was named the [[The World's Billionaires|145th-richest person in the United States]] by ''Forbes'' in 2019 with a [[net worth]] of $4.1 billion (November 2019).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/profile/howard-schultz/#6de1621452c6|title=Howard Schultz|website=Forbes|access-date=April 2, 2019|language=en}}</ref> He is the author of [[Howard Schultz#Books|three books]], ''Pour Your Heart Into It'' (1997), ''Onward'' (2011), and ''From the Ground Up'' (2019). Long known for his outspoken [[Centrism|centrist]], moderate, and independent political views, Schultz explored a run in the [[2020 United States presidential election]] as an independent candidate but declined to formally join the contest for fear of re-electing [[Donald Trump]]. Schultz supports nonpartisan immigration policy, [[free trade]], [[Balanced budget|fiscal discipline]], comprehensive tax reform, gun control, same-sex marriage, and more generally, [[bipartisanship]] across the political spectrum. To further his philanthropic efforts, he established the Schultz Family Foundation which focuses on [[Veteran#Health effects of military service and treatment for veterans|helping military veterans]] and fighting [[youth unemployment]].<!--Leave space for {{TOC}}.-->   \n\n== Early life and education ==\nSchultz was born to a [[American Jews|Jewish]] family<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2003/06/02/business/new-economy-starbucks-was-put-defensive-attack-internet-rumor-mill-that-would.html New York Times: \"New Economy; How Starbucks was put on the defensive by an attack on the Internet rumor mill that would not go away\" By Sherri Day] June 2, 2003</ref> on July 19, 1953, in the [[Brooklyn|Brooklyn borough]] of New York, the son of Elaine (Lederman) and her husband, ex-[[United States Army]] soldier and then truck driver Fred Schultz.<ref name=Mirror22464724>{{cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/top-stories/2010/08/05/starbucks-howard-schultz-on-how-he-became-coffee-king-115875-22464724/|title= Starbucks' Howard Schultz on how he became coffee king|author=Melissa Thompson|publisher=Sunday Mirror|date=August 5, 2010}}</ref><ref name=Koehn>Howard is constantly reminding his team, \"We are not in the coffee business serving people; we are in the people business serving coffee.\"[https://web.archive.org/web/20140104040308/http://skellogg.sdsmt.edu/IE354/Supplement/howars_s.pdf Kellogg School of Management: \"Howard Schultz and Starbucks Coffee Company\" by [[Nancy Koehn|Nancy F. Koehn]]] November 28, 2011. Archived January 4, 2014.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/voices/commentators/howard-schultz-i-raise-my-frappuccino-to-the-brits-1655293.html|title=Howard Schultz: I raise my frappuccino to the Brits|website=Independent.co.uk|accessdate=June 4, 2018}}</ref> His paternal great-grandfather came to the United States in 1892 from [[Belz]], a town on [[Austria-Hungary|Austro-Hungarian Empire]] territory that is now part of [[Ukraine]]. His maternal great-grandparents were originally from [[Russian Empire|Russia]] and emigrated from [[East London]], [[England]] to the U.S. in 1919.{{sfnp|Schultz|Gordon|2019|pp=295-296}}\n\nWith his younger sister, Ronnie, and brother, Michael, Schultz grew up in the [[Canarsie, Brooklyn|Canarsie]] [[Bayview Houses]] of the [[New York City Housing Authority]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www1.nyc.gov/site/nycha/about/press/pr-2017/chair-shola-olatoye-delivers-speech-on-the-future-of-public-housing-at-nahro-conference-in-washington-20170328.page|title= NYCHA Chair Shola Olatoye delivers speech on the future of public housing at NAHRO conference in Washington |date=January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2018/08/12/nycha-was-my-familys-lifeline-but-now-it-needs-to-go/amp/ |title= NYCHA was my family's lifeline \u2014 but now it needs to go |date=August 12, 2018}}</ref> He went to [[Canarsie High School]], from which he graduated in 1971.<ref name=JWL>{{cite web|url= https://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/howard-schultz|title= Howard Schultz|publisher=Jewish Virtual Library|accessdate=June 27, 2019}}</ref> Schultz played high school football and was invited to [[Northern Michigan University]], to compete for a football scholarship. He was not good enough to be quarterback, and didn't want to play another position.<ref>{{Cite book|title=From the Ground Up: A Journey to Reimagine the Promise of America|last=Schultz|first=Howard|publisher=Random House Publishing Group|year=2019|isbn=0525509445|location=|pages=166}}</ref> He paid for college with government loans and money earned from part-time jobs.  He was the first person in his family to go to college. A member of the Theta-Iota chapter of [[Tau Kappa Epsilon]], Schultz received his bachelor's degree in speech communication in 1975.<ref name=Koehn />\n\n==Career==\nAfter graduating, Schultz worked as a salesman for [[Xerox Corporation]] and was quickly promoted to a full sales representative.<ref name=Koehn /> In 1979, he became a general manager for [[Sweden|Swedish]] drip coffee maker manufacturer [[Hammarplast]],<ref name=Mirror22464724/> where he became responsible for their US operations with a staff of twenty.<ref name=Koehn /> In 1981, Schultz visited a client of Hammarplast, a fledgling coffee-bean shop called Starbucks Coffee Company in Seattle, curious as to why it ordered so many plastic cone filters.<ref name=Koehn /> He was impressed with the company's knowledge of coffee and kept in contact over the next year, expressing interest in working with them. A year later, he joined Starbucks as the director of marketing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.successtelevision.com/index2.php?option=com_content&do_pdf=1&id=3676 |title=Howard Schultz Secrets for Success. Dan Skeen. Success Television |accessdate=August 22, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716161518/http://www.successtelevision.com/index2.php?option=com_content&do_pdf=1&id=3676 |archivedate=July 16, 2011 }}</ref> On a buying trip to [[Milan, Italy|Milan]], Italy, for Starbucks, Schultz noted that coffee bars existed on practically every street. He learned that they not only served excellent [[espresso]], they also served as meeting places or public squares; the 200,000 caf\u00e9s in the country were an important element of Italian culture and society.[[File:Howard-Schultz-Starbucks.jpg|thumb|250x250px|Shultz speaking with press about Starbucks' presence in Canada, 2007.|alt=|left]]On his return, he tried to persuade the owners (including cofounder [[Jerry Baldwin]]) to offer traditional espresso beverages in addition to the whole bean coffee, leaf teas and spices they had long offered. After a successful pilot of the cafe concept, the owners refused to roll it out company-wide, saying they did not want to get into the restaurant business. Frustrated, Schultz decided to leave Starbucks in 1985. He needed $400,000 to open the first store and start the business. He did not have the money and his wife was pregnant with their first baby. Jerry Baldwin and Starbucks cofounder [[Gordon Bowker]] offered to help. Schultz also received $100,000 from a doctor who was impressed by Schultz's energy to \"take a gamble\".<ref>{{cite book|last=Mullins|first=John|title=The New Business Road Test|url=https://archive.org/details/newbusinessroadt0000mull|url-access=registration|year=2007}}</ref> By 1986, he had raised all the money he needed to open the first store, \"Il Giornale\", named after [[Il Giornale|the Milanese newspaper]] of the same name. The store offered ice cream in addition to coffee, had little seating, and played opera music in the background to portray an Italian experience. Two years later, the original Starbucks management decided to focus on [[Peet's Coffee & Tea]] and sold its Starbucks retail unit to Schultz and Il Giornale for US$3.8&nbsp;million.\n\nSchultz renamed ''Il Giornale'' with the Starbucks name, and aggressively expanded its reach across the United States. Schultz's insight in real estate and his hard-line focus on growth drove him to expand the company rapidly. Schultz did not believe in [[franchising]], and made a point of having Starbucks retain ownership of every domestic outlet. On June 26, 1992, Starbucks had its initial public offering and trading of its common stock under the stock ticker SBUX. The offering was done by Alex, Brown & Sons Inc. and Wertheim Schroder & Co. Inc.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/STARBUCKS%20COFFEE%20ANNOUNCES%20INITIAL%20PUBLIC%20OFFERING-a012370965|title=STARBUCKS COFFEE ANNOUNCES INITIAL PUBLIC OFFERING - Free Online Library|work=thefreelibrary.com}}</ref> The IPO raised $271 million for the company and financed the doubling of their stores.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nasdaq.com/articles/7-fun-facts-about-starbucks-honor-its-ipos-25th-anniversary-2017-06-26|title=7 Fun Facts about Starbucks In Honor of Its IPO's 25th Anniversary|last=Zacks|first=Publisher|website=www.nasdaq.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n[[File:Starbucks_stores_graph.png|thumb|268x268px|Shultz served as chief executive from 1986 to 2000, and then from 2008 to 2017.<ref name=\"tele40\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/newsbysector/retailandconsumer/8505866/Forty-years-young-A-history-of-Starbucks.html|title=Forty years young: A history of Starbucks|date=May 11, 2011|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph|accessdate=November 13, 2012|location=London}}</ref> ''Pictured'': Starbucks store count from 1971 to 2010.|alt=]]\nOn June 1, 2000, Schultz stepped down as CEO of Starbucks, moving to the new position of chief global strategist to help the company expand internationally.<ref name=\"CNNff2000\">{{cite news |title=Starbucks CEO steps down |url=http://money.cnn.com/2000/04/06/companies/starbucks/ |accessdate=June 5, 2018 |work=[[CNN Money]] |agency=[[CNNfn]] |date=April 6, 2000}}</ref><ref name=\"InvestopediaSchultzGone&Back\">{{cite web |title=Why did Howard Schultz leave Starbucks, only to return eight years later? (SBUX) |url=https://www.investopedia.com/ask/answers/033015/why-did-howard-schultz-leave-starbucks-only-return-eight-years-later.asp |website=[[Investopedia]] |accessdate=June 5, 2018}}</ref> His aggressive expansion in Chinese markets has been credited with reconciling [[Chinese tea culture|the country's tea-culture]] with [[Coffee production in China|coffee consumption in China]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/goatsandsoda/2019/05/17/723193259/what-does-chinas-luckin-coffee-have-that-starbucks-doesnt|title=China's Luckin Coffee Tries To Conquer A Nation Of Tea Drinkers|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fortune.com/2019/12/30/starbucks-china-retail/|title=The Starbucks of China Is Paving a New Future for Retail. Will It Pay Off?|website=Fortune|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> On January 8, 2008, Schultz returned as CEO of Starbucks after an eight-year hiatus.<ref>[http://www.starbucks.com/aboutus/pressdesc.asp?id=818] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080117121159/http://www.starbucks.com/aboutus/pressdesc.asp?id=818|date=January 17, 2008}}</ref> Although the company was growing, that growth was largely dependent on opening new stores, while same-store sales were declining.<ref name=\"InvestopediaSchultzGone&Back\" /> He fired many executives,<ref name=\"InvestopediaSchultzGone&Back\" /><ref name=\"Taylor2016\">{{cite news |last1=Taylor |first1=Kate |title=Here's what happened the last time Howard Schultz stepped down as Starbucks CEO |url=http://www.businessinsider.com/last-time-schultz-stepped-down-as-starbucks-ceo-2016-12 |accessdate=June 5, 2018 |work=[[Business Insider]] |date=December 4, 2016}}</ref> closed down hundreds of weak stores,<ref name=\"InvestopediaSchultzGone&Back\" /><ref name=\"Taylor2016\" /> hired the company's first [[Chief Technology Officer]],<ref name=\"Taylor2016\" /> introduced the Starbucks Reward Card,<ref name=\"Taylor2016\" /> and temporarily closed all US locations to retrain employees in making espresso.<ref name=\"Taylor2016\" /> The company soon returned to [[organic growth]] and investor favor.<ref name=\"Taylor2016\" /> At this time, Schultz was earning a total compensation of $9,740,471, which included a base salary of $1,190,000, and options granted of $7,786,105.<ref>[http://www.equilar.com/CEO_Compensation/Starbucks_Howard_Schultz.php 2008 CEO Compensation for Howard Schultz] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090814181820/http://www.equilar.com/CEO_Compensation/Starbucks_Howard_Schultz.php |date=August 14, 2009 }}, Equilar.com</ref> From 2008 to 2017, Schultz oversaw nearly $100 billion added to the company's [[market capitalization]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/10/16/how-howard-schultz-conquered-self-doubt-to-build-starbucks.html|title=How Howard Schultz conquered self-doubt to build Starbucks into a $100 billion company|last=Scipioni|first=Jade|date=2019-10-16|website=CNBC|language=en|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref> From its IPO in 1992, his tenure saw to a 21,000% increase in [[shareholder value]], according to institutional reports.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://stories.starbucks.com/press/2018/howard-schultz-to-bid-farewell-to-starbucks/|title=Iconic Leader and Visionary Entrepreneur Howard Schultz to Bid Farewell to Starbucks after 40 Years|last=|first=|date=June 4, 2018|website=stories.starbucks.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\nSchultz again stepped down as CEO in December 2016, assuming the position of executive chairman and chief global strategist.<ref name=\"Taylor2016\" /> On June 4, 2018, Schultz announced that he would leave all positions at Starbucks, as he was considering amongst other options a campaign for president.<ref name=\"Meyersohn2018\">{{cite news |last1=Meyersohn |first1=Nathaniel |title=Howard Schultz steps down at Starbucks, may consider run for president |url=http://money.cnn.com/2018/06/04/news/companies/howard-schultz-starbucks/index.html |accessdate=June 5, 2018 |work=[[CNN Money]] |date=June 4, 2018}}</ref> Schultz is known for pioneering Starbucks' partnership with [[Arizona State University]], which allows all employees at Starbucks working 20 or more hours a week to qualify for free tuition through ASU's online courses.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://mastersofscale.com/howard-schultz-how-to-do-good-and-do-good-business/|title=Howard Schultz: How to do good and do good business {{!}} Masters of Scale podcast|work=WaitWhat|access-date=March 20, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> On November 1, 2013, it was announced that Schultz had stepped down from the board of Square, to be replaced by former [[Goldman Sachs]] executive [[David Viniar]].<ref>{{Cite news| url =http://www.entrepreneur.com/article/229728|title=Starbucks CEO Howard Schultz Steps Down From Square's Board of Directors |author=Kate Taylor|publisher=[[Entrepreneur (magazine)|Entrepreneur]] |date =November 1, 2013}}</ref> Schultz is a significant stakeholder in [[Jamba Juice]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.coriolisresearch.com/pdfs/coriolis_jamba_juice.pdf |title=Research Information on Jamba Juice |format=PDF |date= |accessdate=August 22, 2011}}</ref> Schultz's positioning Starbucks as a social hub is widely seen as introducing [[Third wave of coffee#History|the second wave]] of coffee culture in the U.S., particularly in Seattle.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.seattlemag.com/article/seattle-coffee-guide-evolution-coffee|title=Seattle Coffee Guide: The Evolution of Coffee|date=1969-12-31|website=Seattle Magazine|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/venessawong/the-man-who-brought-lattes-to-the-world-is-stepping-down|title=A Farewell To The Father Of The Latte|last=Wong|first=Vanessa|date=April 1, 2017|website=BuzzFeed Business|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\n===Seattle SuperSonics and Seattle Storm===\n{{Further|Seattle SuperSonics relocation to Oklahoma City}}\nIn January 2001, Schultz led a group of ten investors who bought the [[National Basketball Association]]'s [[Seattle SuperSonics]] and the [[Women's National Basketball Association]]'s [[Seattle Storm]] from the [[Ackerley Group]] for $200&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=20010112&slug=sale120|title=Sports - Sonics sale a 'dream' deal for Schultz - Seattle Times Newspaper|website=Community.seattletimes.nwsource.com|accessdate=February 3, 2019}}</ref> During his tenure as the SuperSonics team owner, he was criticized for his na\u00efvet\u00e9 and propensity to run the franchise as a business rather than a sports team.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nba/columns/story?columnist=hughes_frank&id=2525634 |title=Why Schultz tuned out and sold out the Sonics |publisher=Sports.espn.go.com |date=July 21, 2006 |accessdate=August 22, 2011}}</ref> Schultz feuded with player [[Gary Payton]], feeling that Payton disrespected him and the team by not showing up to the first day of training camp in 2002.<ref>{{Cite news| url =http://www.thestreet.com/story/12287415/1/seattle-super-bowl-scores-points-for-paul-allen-sacks-howard-schultz.html|title=Seattle Super Bowl Scores Points for Paul Allen, Sacks Howard Schultz|author=Jason Notte|publisher=[[TheStreet.com]] |date = February 1, 2014}}</ref> In February 2006, he stated that the Sonics needed $200&nbsp;million to renovate [[KeyArena]] or build a new arena for the team, and if the [[Washington State Legislature]] would not approve this, he would look to sell or move the team.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.seattlepi.com/news/article/Sonics-owner-grows-impatient-1194645.php|title=Sonics owner grows impatient|first1=Gary|last1=Washburn|first2=P.-I.|last2=Reporter|date=February 2, 2006|website=Seattlepi.com|accessdate=February 3, 2019}}</ref> On July 18, 2006, Schultz sold the team to [[Clay Bennett (businessman)|Clay Bennett]], chairman of the [[Professional Basketball Club LLC]], an [[Oklahoma City]] ownership group, for $350&nbsp;million, after having failed to convince the city of [[Seattle]] to provide public funding to build a new arena in the Greater Seattle area to replace [[KeyArena]]. At the time of the team's sale, it was speculated that the new owners would move the team to their city some time after the 2006\u20132007 NBA season.<ref>[http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/sports/2003136585_sonics19m.html seattletimes.nwsource.com]. URL last accessed July 18, 2006.</ref>\n\nSchultz filed a lawsuit against Bennett \u2013 in April 2008 \u2013 to rescind the July 2006 sale based on what Schultz claimed was fraud and intentional misrepresentation. However, Schultz dropped the lawsuit in August 2008. When Bennett purchased the SuperSonics and its sister franchise in the WNBA, the Seattle Storm, for $350&nbsp;million, he agreed to a stipulation that he would make a \"good-faith best effort\" for one year to keep both teams in Seattle. The sincerity of the good-faith effort was widely disputed by the way Bennett acted and by direct quotes from his partner [[Aubrey McClendon]]. On January 8, 2008, Bennett sold the Storm to Force 10 Hoops, LLC, an ownership group of four Seattle women, which kept the team in Seattle.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/sonics/2004349361_schultz15.html |work=The Seattle Times |title=Howard Schultz plans to sue Clay Bennett to get Sonics back |first=Percy |last=Allen |date=April 15, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080419015637/http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/sonics/2004349361_schultz15.html |archivedate=April 19, 2008 }}</ref> On July 2, 2008, the city of Seattle reached a settlement with the new ownership group and the SuperSonics [[Seattle SuperSonics relocation to Oklahoma City|moved to Oklahoma City]] and became the [[Oklahoma City Thunder|Thunder]] for the [[2008\u201309 NBA season]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.seattlepi.com/basketball/369313_trial03.html |title=Sonics are Oklahoma City-bound |publisher=seattlepi.com |date=July 2, 2008 |accessdate=August 22, 2011}}</ref> The sale to the out-of-state owners considerably damaged Schultz's popularity in Seattle.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mynorthwest.com/?nid=76&sid=70406 |title=Sonics Settlement |publisher=Mynorthwest.com |date=April 6, 2011 |accessdate=November 24, 2011}}</ref> In a local newspaper poll, Schultz was judged \"most responsible\" for the team leaving the city.<ref>{{cite web|title=Poll Results|url=http://www.seattlepi.com/polls/popup.asp?pollID=2983 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110131185345/http://www.seattlepi.com/polls/popup.asp?pollID=2983 |url-status=dead |archive-date=January 31, 2011 |accessdate=February 13, 2011 }}</ref> In 2019 Schultz accepted some responsibility for what happened to the SuperSonics during his tenure.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/2020-election/schultz-s-reign-nba-owner-was-fiasco-would-2020-campaign-n964026|title=Schultz's reign as an NBA owner was a fiasco. Would a 2020 campaign be any different?|website=NBC News|accessdate=February 3, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Author===\n[[File:Starbucks CEO visits Marines and Sailors at Camp Pendleton 141113-M-MV301-009.jpg|thumb|Schultz signing a copy of ''For Love of Country'' in California's [[Marine Corps Base Camp Pendleton|Camp Pedleton]], 2014.]]\nSchultz has written four books, three of which incorporate [[:Category:Show business memoirs|business memoir]]-style narratives. His first book, ''Pour Your Heart Into It: How Starbucks Built a Company One Cup at a Time'' was written in 1997 with Dori Jones Yang. ''[[Goodreads]]'' gave his first book 4/5 stars, calling it a \"definitive chronicle of [Starbucks].\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.goodreads.com/work/best_book/90329-pour-your-heart-into-it-how-starbucks-built-a-company-one-cup-at-a-tim|title=Pour Your Heart Into It|website=www.goodreads.com|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref> His second book ''Onward: How Starbucks Fought for Its Life Without Losing Its Soul'', co-written with Joanne Gordon, was published in 2011. Jeff Bailey, of the [[Los Angeles Times|''Los Angles Times'']], called the book \"self-flattering\" and criticized its \"mostly perfunctory account of [[Criticism of Starbucks|Starbucks\u2019 actual problems]].\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/books/la-et-book-20110423-story.html|title=Book review: 'Onward: How Starbucks Fought for Its Life Without Losing Its Soul' by Howard Schultz|date=2011-04-23|website=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref> ''Goodreads'' gave his second book 3.8/5 stars.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Yardley|first=William|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/08/27/us/27starbucks.html|title=There\u2019s One on Every Corner, but None Like This|date=2011-08-26|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-13|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.goodreads.com/work/best_book/14030099-onward-how-starbucks-fought-for-its-life-without-losing-its-soul|title=Onward|website=www.goodreads.com|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref> [[Publishers Weekly|Publisher's Weekly]] called the book \"a personal, suspenseful, and surprisingly open account\" of the rise of Starbucks.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.publishersweekly.com/978-1-60529-288-5|title=Nonfiction Book Review: Onward: How Starbucks Fought for Its Life Without Losing Its Soul by Howard Schultz with Joanne Gordon, Rodale, $25.99 (368p) ISBN 978-1-60529-288-5|website=PublishersWeekly.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref> ''[[Kirkus Reviews]]'' praised the book's \"immense detail\" but critiqued Shultz's coverage of \"outside criticisms of his performance\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/howard-schultz/onward-starbucks/|title=Review: Onward: How Starbucks Fought for Its Life Without Losing Its Soul|last=|first=|date=March 2, 2011|website=Kirkus Reviews|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 1, 2020}}</ref> ''[[Fast Company]]'' placed ''Onward'' within the top five books that \"[predicted] the future of workplace leadership\" in 2014.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fastcompany.com/3032122/5-books-that-predict-the-future-of-workplace-leadership|title=5 Books That Predict The Future Of Workplace Leadership|last=Crowley|first=Mark C.|date=2014-06-25|website=Fast Company|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref> All sale proceeds from the book were donated to the Starbucks Foundation, the firm's main charity.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.starbucks.com/onward|title=Onward|last=|first=|date=|website=Starbucks Coffee Company|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 1, 2020|quote=Buy Onward now and all of Howard Schultz's proceeds will go to the Starbucks Foundation}}</ref> His third book ''For Love of Country'', co-written with [[Rajiv Chandrasekaran]], was published in 2014. His first non-business book, ''For Love of Country'' received positive reviews with ''[[The New York Times Book Review]]'' calling it \"well-written\" and \"formidable.\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Wright|first=James|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/03/15/books/review/for-love-of-country-by-howard-schultz-and-rajiv-chandrasekaran.html|title=\u2018For Love of Country,\u2019 by Howard Schultz and Rajiv Chandrasekaran|date=2015-03-12|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-13|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, he published his fourth book, ''From the Ground Up: A Journey to Reimagine the Promise of America''.<ref>{{cite website|url=http://chamberbusinessnews.com/2019/02/04/howard-schultz-visits-asu-shares-his-life-story-encourages-bipartisanship/|publisher=Chamber Business News|title=Howard Schultz visits ASU, shares his life story, encourages bipartisanship|date= February 4, 2019|accessdate= February 5, 2019}}</ref> The book was widely seen as a presidential candidate memoir as it was published right before the [[2020 United States presidential election]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/news/current/howard-schultz-against-the-hecklers|title=Howard Schultz Against the Hecklers|website=The New Yorker|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref> Due to a backlash regarding his possible candidacy [[Spoiler effect|splitting the Democratic vote]], his book received 1.9/5 stars on [[Amazon (company)|Amazon]], after disgruntled Democratic voters took to the comments section to air their grievances, \"largely [unrelated] to the content of the book.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/howard-schultz-book-bad-reviews-amazon-2019-1|title=People are flooding the Amazon page for Howard Schultz's new book with negative comments after the ex-Starbucks CEO said he was 'seriously considering' running for president|last=Hanbury|first=Mary|website=Business Insider|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref> A book promotion stop at [[Harvard University]] led to a small student protest.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thecrimson.com/article/2019/2/6/schultz-presidential-run-book-tour/|title=Former Starbucks CEO Howard Schultz Draws Protesters at Brattle Theatre Talk {{!}} News {{!}} The Harvard Crimson|website=www.thecrimson.com|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref> ''The New York Times'', in line with many newspapers, compared the book with [[Michael Bloomberg]]'s similarly themed book, ''Bloomberg by Bloomberg''.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Fountain|first=Ben|url=https://www.nybooks.com/articles/2019/05/23/howard-schultz-michael-bloomberg-billionaires/|title=O Billionaires!|date=2019-05-23|access-date=2020-04-13|language=en|issn=0028-7504}}</ref> ''From the Ground Up'' was a featured on ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]''<nowiki/>'s bestseller list in February,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/best-selling-books-week-ended-feb-9-11550244453|title=Best-Selling Books Week Ended Feb. 9|date=2019-02-15|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=2020-04-13|language=en-US|issn=0099-9660}}</ref> and was listed as a ''[[The New York Times Best Seller list|The New York Times]]'' [[The New York Times Best Seller list|bestseller]] for 2019.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.nytimes.com/books/best-sellers/2019/02/17/hardcover-nonfiction/|title=Hardcover Nonfiction Books - Best Sellers - Feb. 17, 2019 - The New York Times|date=|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-13|url-status=live|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|quote=From the Ground Up by Howard Schultz with Joanne GordonRandom House: The former chief executive of Starbucks recounts his journey to success and shares the inspirational stories of others.}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.goodhousekeeping.com/life/entertainment/g29811033/best-selling-books-2019/|title=44 Best-Selling Books of 2019 Everyone's Talking About|last=Schumer|first=Lizz|date=2019-12-03|website=Good Housekeeping|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref> ''[[Reuters]]'' rated the book highly, yet called it \"caffeine free\" for its inability to \"harness his business success\" in a potential White House run.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.breakingviews.com/features/review/|title=Caffeine free|last=Chon|first=Gina|date=8 February 2019|website=Reuters|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=3 April 2020|quote=The former Starbucks chief\u2019s tough boyhood and corporate rise inspires in \u201cFrom the Ground Up.\u201d Workers helped by his policies are also stirring. But this message is oddly absent from his White House rollout. The candidate needs to harness his business success more effectively.}}</ref> ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' called the book \"stunningly boring.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/politics/politics-features/howard-schultz-trump-786516/|title=Howard Schultz: America's New Banality Supervillain|last=Taibbi|first=Matt|last2=Taibbi|first2=Matt|date=2019-01-30|website=Rolling Stone|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\n==Political views==\n[[File:Howard Schultz (33059510518).jpg|thumb|Shultz in speaking at [[Arizona State University]] in 2019]]\nIn 2012, Schultz began making public statements that led to press speculation that he would run for [[President of the United States]]. These included an initiative, announced via an [[open letter]] published in various newspapers, that on one day (December 27, 2012), Starbucks employees were asked to write \"come together\" on all cups distributed, to encourage bipartisanship in the federal government.<ref>{{cite web |title=Starbucks CEO Howard Schultz Needs to Run for President Already |url=http://nymag.com/intelligencer/2012/12/howard-schultz-president-starbucks-2016.html |first=Dan |last=Amira |work=New York Magazine Intelligencer blog |date=December 26, 2012}}</ref> That same year, he also had Starbucks express support for [[Washington (state)|Washington state]]'s [[Washington Referendum 74|Referendum 74]], which legalized [[same-sex marriage]] in that state.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/frederickallen/2013/03/22/howard-schultz-to-anti-gay-marriage-starbucks-shareholder-you-can-sell-your-shares/#4aed60586511|title=Howard Schultz to Anti-Gay-Marriage Starbucks Shareholder: 'You Can Sell Your Shares'|last=Allen|first=Frederick E.|website=Forbes|access-date=April 24, 2016}}</ref> There was speculation that he would run in the [[2016 United States presidential election|2016 US presidential election]], but he wrote a ''[[The New York Times|New York Times]]'' op-ed in August 2015 denying this, stating, \"Despite the encouragement of others, I have no intention of entering the presidential fray. I'm not done serving at Starbucks.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Starbucks CEO Howard Schultz Won't Run For President |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/abrambrown/2015/08/06/starbucks-ceo-howard-schultz-says-he-wont-run-for-president/#3632e94716fa |first=Abram |last=Brown |work=Forbes |date=August 6, 2015}}</ref> He ultimately endorsed Democratic candidate [[Hillary Clinton]] in that election.<ref>Long, H. [http://money.cnn.com/2016/09/07/news/economy/howard-schultz-hillary-clinton/ CNN] September 7, 2016.</ref>\n\nDuring his 2019 exploratory bid for the presidency, Schultz framed his candidacy as that of a socially liberal [[deficit hawk]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2019/01/29/howard-schultz-says-he-can-win-support-silent-majority-silent-majority-doesnt-really-exist/|title=Howard Schultz says he can win the support of a \u2018silent majority.\u2019 The \u2018silent majority\u2019 doesn\u2019t really exist.|last=|first=|date=January 29, 2019|work=The Washington Post|access-date=April 9, 2019}}</ref> Schultz supports nonpartisan immigration policy, [[free trade]], [[Balanced budget|fiscal discipline]], comprehensive tax reform, gun control, same-sex marriage, and more generally, [[bipartisanship]] across the political spectrum.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/06/05/howard-schultz-on-hot-political-topics-gun-control-taxes-immigration.html|title=Here's what Howard Schultz says about hot political topics as speculation swirls about a possible presidential run|last=Whitten|first=Sarah|date=2018-06-05|website=CNBC|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Stevens|first=Matt|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/09/06/us/politics/howard-schultz-drops-out-2020.html|title=Howard Schultz, Former Starbucks Chief, Won\u2019t Run for President in 2020|date=2019-09-06|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-13|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> In January 2019, ''The Washington Post'' wrote that Schultz \"has not offered many specifics on his policy proposals.\"<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/budding-independent-howard-schultz-aims-most-of-his-ire-at-democrats/2019/01/30/28210ab4-24a7-11e9-ad53-824486280311_story.html|title=Budding independent Howard Schultz aims most of his ire at Democrats|last=|first=|date=2019|work=The Washington Post|access-date=}}</ref> In June 2018, Schultz stated in an interview that he thought the [[National debt of the United States|national debt]] is \"the greatest threat domestically to the country\" and that \"we have to go after entitlements.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Howard Schultz: The $21 trillion national debt is the \u2018greatest threat domestically to the country\u2019 |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/06/05/howard-schultz-21-trillion-debt-is-biggest-threat-to-us-domestically.html |first=Kevin |last=Breuninger |date=June 5, 2018 |work=CNBC}}</ref> Schultz has described [[Medicare For All]] as \"not American.\"<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/01/29/politics/howard-schultz-medicare-for-all-cnntv/index.html|title=Schultz defends criticism of Medicare-for-all proposal|author=Veronica Stracqualursi|website=CNN|access-date=January 30, 2019}}</ref> Asked in January 2019 what his healthcare proposal was, Schultz answered, \"I don't have a plan today. I'm not yet running for president.\"<ref name=\":0\" /> Schultz opposed [[Alexandria Ocasio-Cortez]]'s proposal to raise the [[marginal tax rate]] on income over $10 million to 70%, saying it was \"punitive\" and contrary to the [[American Dream]].<ref name=\":0\" /> Schultz said he supported \"comprehensive tax reform\".<ref name=\":0\" /> He supported a pathway to citizenship for illegal immigrants who had entered the U.S. as children.<ref name=\":0\" /> He called for greater border security, but opposed President Trump's proposal of a border wall.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n===British economy===\nSpeaking to [[CNBC]] in February 2009 about his concerns over the [[Great Recession|global economic crisis]], Schultz said that \"the place that concerns us the most is western Europe, and specifically the UK. The UK is in a spiral\", expressing concern with the levels of [[Unemployment in the United Kingdom|unemployment]] and [[consumer confidence#GfK Consumer Confidence Barometer (UK)|consumer confidence]] in the [[United Kingdom]].<ref name=\"guardian\">{{Cite news|last=Wintour|first=Patrick|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2009/feb/19/peter-mandelson-starbucks-economy|title=Mandelson and Starbucks clash on UK economy|date=February 19, 2009|work=The Guardian|accessdate=March 18, 2009|location=London}}</ref> [[Peter Mandelson]], then-[[Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy|British Business Secretary]], responded saying that the United Kingdom was \"not spiralling, although I've noticed Starbucks is in a great deal of trouble\", and suggesting that Schultz was projecting his own company's trouble in the United Kingdom onto the wider national economy.<ref name=\"guardian\" /> An official comment from Starbucks read that \"It is a difficult economic situation in the US and around the world. Please be assured that Starbucks has no intention of criticising the economic situation in the UK. We are all in this together and as a global business we are committed to each and every market we serve.\"<ref name=\"guardian\" />\n\n===2020 presidential campaign effort===\nAfter Schultz stepped down from Starbucks, political commentators speculated whether he would run in the [[2020 United States presidential election]],<ref>Gelles, David (June 4, 2018). [https://www.nytimes.com/2018/06/04/business/ceos-president-howard-schultz-starbucks.html Schultz 2020? Other C.E.O.s Will Be Watching Closely] The New York Times. Retrieved December 6, 2018.</ref><ref>Schwartz, Brian (November 9, 2018). [https://www.cnbc.com/2018/11/09/ex-starbucks-ceo-howard-schultz-builds-elite-pr-team-as-he-mulls-white-house-run.html Former Starbucks CEO Howard Schultz assembles an elite PR team as he considers running for president] CNBC. Retrieved December 6, 2018.</ref> including encouragement from a [[draft (politics)|draft movement]] called Ready for Schultz.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://readyforschultz.com/|title=Ready for Schultz 2020|website=Readyforschultz.com}}</ref> On January 27, 2019, he stated in an interview with ''[[60 Minutes]]'' that he was exploring a run for president as an [[independent politician|independent candidate]], and that he considered running as a centrist.<ref name=\"hill\">{{cite news|author=Emily Birnbaum|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/campaign/427184-howard-schultz-makes-twitter-debut-amid-2020-speculation|title=Howard Schultz makes Twitter debut amid 2020 speculation|date=January 27, 2019|work=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]|accessdate=January 27, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/01/21/politics/howard-schultz-starbucks-2020/index.html|title=Former Starbucks chief exploring independent 2020 bid|author1=Eli Watkins|author2=Maeve Reston|author3=Cristina Alesci|author4=Poppy Harlow|work=CNN|date=January 21, 2019|accessdate=January 21, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-47033483|title=Starbucks tycoon roasted over 2020 plan|date=January 29, 2019|access-date=January 30, 2019|language=en-GB}}</ref> Schultz's proposed independent candidacy was widely condemned by Democrats who argued that Schultz's third-party candidacy would help to re-elect President Trump by [[Spoiler effect|splitting the vote of those opposed]] to the president.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://fortune.com/2019/01/27/democrats-worry-howard-schultz-run-president/|title=Democrats Say Possible Howard Schultz Presidential Bid Could Help Trump Win Second Term|website=Fortune.com|language=en|access-date=January 30, 2019}}</ref> President Trump himself appeared to goad Schultz into running, tweeting that Schultz did not have the \"guts.\"<ref name=\":1\" /> University of Virginia political scientist [[Larry Sabato]] said that Schultz's candidacy was likely to benefit Trump.<ref name=\":1\" /> In response to claims that his candidacy would benefit Trump, Schultz said, \"Nobody wants to see Donald Trump removed from office more than me.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/01/29/howard-schultz-says-his-presidential-run-wont-boost-trump.html|title=Howard Schultz says his presidential run won't boost Trump|last=Higgins|first=Tucker|date=January 28, 2019|website=Cnbc.com|access-date=January 30, 2019}}</ref> A February 2019 poll indicated that a Schultz third-party candidacy would strengthen Trump's re-election prospects, as Schultz would draw more support from Democrats than Republicans.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-02-07/schultz-s-independent-bid-in-2020-would-help-trump-poll-finds|title=Schultz's Independent Bid in 2020 Would Help Trump, Poll Finds|website=www.bloomberg.com|access-date=February 10, 2019}}</ref> Later that month, Schultz said he would consider dropping out of the race if the Democrats nominated \"a centrist Democrat.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/howard-schultz-challenge-to-democrats-nominate-a-centrist-for-president-and-ill-abandon-my-independent-campaign/2019/02/14/208c25de-309d-11e9-813a-0ab2f17e305b_story.html|title=Howard Schultz\u2019 challenge to Democrats: Nominate a centrist for president and I\u2019ll abandon my independent campaign|author1=Michael Scherer|author2=Tracy Jan|date=February 14, 2019|work=The Washington Post|access-date=February 17, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAfter announcing that he was exploring a presidential bid in January 2019, Schultz spent most of the time in his first media interviews attacking Democrats' economic and tax policies.\"<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/howard-schultz-calls-alexandria-ocasio-cortez-a-bit-misinformed-when-it-comes-to-taxing-the-wealthy/2019/01/29/b00db19e-23c5-11e9-90cd-dedb0c92dc17_story.html|title=Howard Schultz knocks Ocasio-Cortez, Warren and Harris for \u2018extreme,\u2019 \u2018punitive\u2019 and \u2018not American\u2019 policies|last=|first=|date=2019|work=The Washington Post|access-date=}}</ref> In May 2019, Schultz delayed his 2020 decision, citing [[Joe Biden]] as one of the main reasons.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.foxbusiness.com/business-leaders/howard-schultz-delays-decision-on-2020-biden-the-factor|title=Howard Schultz delays decision on 2020, Biden the factor|first=Charlie|last=Gasparino|date=May 15, 2019|website=FOXBusiness}}</ref> On September 6, Schultz officially ruled out a Presidential run, stating that it wasn't the best way to \"serve our country at this time.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/09/06/politics/howard-schultz-presidential-campaign-2020/index.html|title=Howard Schultz drops plans to run as independent candidate in 2020|first= Veronica|last=Stracqualursi|date=September 6, 2019|website=CNNPolitics}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and honors==\n[[File:Howard Schultz and Leroy Petry 180510-D-SW162-2241 (27170721607).jpg|right|thumb|Schultz receiving the \"Distinguished Business Leadership Award\", during the [[Atlantic Council]]'s Distinguished Leadership Awards dinner in [[Washington, D.C.]], 2018]]\nIn 1998, Schultz received the 'Israel 50th Anniversary Tribute Award'.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19980819&slug=2767425|title=Starbucks' Schultz To Receive Israel Award|date=19 August 1998|work=[[Seattle Times Newspaper]]}}</ref> In 1999 AIDs Action awarded Schultz the National Leadership Award for philanthropic and educational efforts to battle AIDS.<ref>[http://investing.businessweek.com/research/stocks/people/person.asp?personId=194300&symbol=SBUX.O Howard M. Schultz Biography] [[Businessweek]] Data is as current as the most recent Definitive Proxy</ref> Schultz was named ''[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]]'' magazine's 2011 \"Businessperson of the Year\" for his initiatives in the economy and job market.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://money.cnn.com/galleries/2011/fortune/1111/gallery.business_person_year.fortune/2.html|title=2011 Businessperson of the Year - 1. Howard M. Schultz (2) - FORTUNE|date=November 17, 2011|publisher=Money.cnn.com|accessdate=November 24, 2011}}</ref>\n\nSchultz spoke at the 2017 [[Arizona State University]] commencement ceremony and was presented with an [[Honorary degree|honorary]] Doctor of humane letters degree.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://asunow.asu.edu/20170313-asu-news-commencement-speaker-starbucks-ceo-howard-schultz|title=Starbucks Chairman and CEO Howard Schultz to speak at ASU commencement|date=March 13, 2017|work=ASU Now: Access, Excellence, Impact|access-date=March 23, 2017|language=en}}</ref> In November 2017, the [[NAACP Legal Defense and Educational Fund]] presented Schultz with the National Equal Justice Award.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.naacpldf.org/press-release/moment-now-naacp-legal-31st-annual-national-equal-justice-awards|title=The Moment is Now: NAACP legal 31st Annual National Equal Justice Awards|website=Naacpldf.org|language=en|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171222051141/http://www.naacpldf.org/press-release/moment-now-naacp-legal-31st-annual-national-equal-justice-awards|archive-date=December 22, 2017|access-date=December 20, 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Philanthropy ==\nIn 1996, Howard and Sheri Schultz co-founded the Schultz Family Foundation, which currently supports two national initiatives.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/georgeanders/2016/03/01/howard-schultzs-stormy-crusades-the-starbucks-boss-opens-up/|title=Howard Schultz's Stormy Crusades: The Starbucks Boss Opens Up|last=Anders|first=George|work=forbes.com}}</ref> Onward Youth is aimed at promoting employment for young people between the ages of 16 and 24 who are not in school and not working.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/07/13/business/starbucks-and-other-corporations-to-announce-plan-to-curb-unemployment-of-young-people.html|title=Starbucks and Other Corporations to Announce Plan to Curb Unemployment of Young People|date=July 13, 2015|work=The New York Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/07/13/opinion/connecting-young-people-with-jobs.html|title=Connecting Young People With Jobs|date=July 13, 2015|work=The New York Times}}</ref> Onward Veterans aims to help [[post-9/11]] military veterans to successfully transition to civilian life.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://philanthropy.com/article/Starbuckss-Schultz-Opens-New/228699|title=Starbucks's Schultz Opens New Front in Helping Veterans Enter Work Force|date=March 23, 2015|work=philanthropy.com}}</ref> In March 2014, the foundation pledged [[United States dollar|US$]]30 million to veterans' aiming to reintegrate into society.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://philanthropynewsdigest.org/news/schultz-family-foundation-pledges-30-million-for-veterans|title=Schultz Family Foundation Pledges $30 Million for Veterans|last=Candid|website=Philanthropy News Digest (PND)|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> In October 2015 Schultz led an initiative at Starbucks, in conjunction with his foundation, to hire 10,000 veterans and military spouses by 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://philanthropynw.org/news/starbucks-schultz-family-foundation-muster-allies-veterans|title=Starbucks, Schultz Family Foundation Muster Allies for Veterans|date=2015-10-13|website=Philanthropy Northwest|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://stories.starbucks.com/stories/2014/starbucks-and-schultz-family-foundation-give-young-job-seekers-a-roadmap/|title=Starbucks and the Schultz Family Foundation Give Young Job Seekers a Roadmap to Opportunity|last=|first=|date=September 15, 2014|website=stories.starbucks.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 10, 2020}}</ref> A month later, his foundation issued a grant to help 200 veterans attend the Silver School of Social Work at [[New York University]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://socialwork.nyu.edu/news/2015/11/11/grant-from-the-schultz-family-foundation-to-help-300-veterans-and-their-family-members-enroll-and-study-at-nyus-silver-school-of-social-work.html|title=Grant from the Schultz foundation to help 300 veterans and their family members enroll at NYU|last=|first=|date=November 11, 2015|website=New York University|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2017, it awarded a $143,000 grant to the National Association of Veteran-Serving Organizations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.navso.org/news/schultz-family-foundation-awards-143000-grant-navso|title=The Schultz Family Foundation awards $143,000 grant to NAVSO|date=2017-09-08|website=National Association of Veteran Serving Organizations|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> The [[Local Initiatives Support Corporation]] (LISC) received a grant for an undisclosed amount in July 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lisc.org/rural/regional-stories/rural-lisc-receives-grant-support-youth-employment-schultz-family-foundation/|title=Rural LISC Receives Grant to Support Youth Employment from the Schultz Family Foundation {{!}} LISC Rural LISC|website=Local Initiatives Support Corporation|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> In January 2019, the foundation donated $7.5 million to expand care for veterans in the United States.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnybj.com/schultz-family-foundation-donates-to-su-ivmf/|title=Schultz Family Foundation donates $7.5M to SU\u2019s IVMF to expand veteran career-preparation program|website=www.cnybj.com|language=en-us|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> During the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]], the Schultz Family Foundation raised $4 million to help restaurant workers impacted by the pandemic.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bizjournals.com/seattle/news/2020/04/06/howard-schultz-fund-laid-off-workers-seattle.html|title=Howard Schultz launches fund for laid off restaurant workers in King County|last=Payne|first=Patti|date=|website=www.bizjournals.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 2, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.columbian.com/news/2020/apr/06/first-doc-inmate-tests-positive-for-virus-in-washington/|title=First DOC inmate tests positive for virus in Washington|website=The Columbian|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 1982, Schultz married Sheri Kersch with whom he has two children.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.yahoo.com/lifestyle/everything-know-howard-schultzs-wife-183800623.html|title=Everything We Know About Howard Schultz's Wife|accessdate=January 31, 2019}}</ref> They live in Seattle's [[Madison Park, Seattle|Madison Park]] neighborhood, having previously lived near [[Madrona, Seattle|Madrona]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Kugiya |first=Hugo |date=December 15, 1996 |title=Seattle's Coffee King |url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19961215&slug=2365201 |work=The Seattle Times}}</ref> \n\n== Books ==\n\n*{{Citation|author1=Schultz, Howard|author2=Yang, Dori Jones|title=Pour Your Heart Into It: How Starbucks Built a Company One Cup at a Time|place=New York|publisher=Hyperion|year=1997|isbn=0786863153|url=https://archive.org/details/pouryourheartint00howa}}\n*{{Citation|author1=Schultz, Howard|author2=Gordon, Joanne|title=Onward: How Starbucks Fought for Its Life without Losing Its Soul|place=New York|publisher=Rodale|year=2011|isbn=9781605292885|url=https://archive.org/details/onwardhowstarbuc00schu}}\n*{{citation|last1=Schultz|first1=Howard|last2=Gordon|first2=Joanne|title=From the Ground Up: A Journey to Reimagine the Promise of America|place=New York|publisher=Random House|year=2019|isbn=9780525509448}}\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Starbucks#History|History fo Starbucks]]\n* [[Northern Michigan University#Notable alumni|List of Northern Michigan University alumni]]\n* [[The World's Billionaires|List of ''Forbes''<nowiki/>' World Billionaires]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|Howard Schultz}}\n\n* [http://www.schultzfamilyfoundation.org/#tab-switcher-1 Schultz Family Foundation]\n*{{C-SPAN|Howard Schultz}}\n* https://web.archive.org/web/20180928005543/https://www.arte.tv/de/videos/073442-000-A/starbucks-ungefiltert/\n* [https://www.npr.org/2017/09/28/551874532/live-episode-starbucks-howard-schultz How I Built This - Live Episode! Starbucks: Howard Schultz] (audio interview)\n\n{{Starbucks}}\n{{Seattle SuperSonics}}\n{{Seattle Storm}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Schultz, Howard}}\n[[Category:1953 births]]\n[[Category:American billionaires]]\n[[Category:American business writers]]\n[[Category:American chairmen of corporations]]\n[[Category:American chief executives of food industry companies]]\n[[Category:American financial company founders]]\n[[Category:American financiers]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from New York City]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Seattle]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople in coffee]]\n[[Category:Canarsie High School alumni]]\n[[Category:Coffee in Seattle]]\n[[Category:Directors of Starbucks]]\n[[Category:Jewish American sportspeople]]\n[[Category:Jewish American writers]]\n[[Category:LGBT rights activists from the United States]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:New York (state) Independents]]\n[[Category:Northern Michigan University alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Canarsie, Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:Seattle Storm owners]]\n[[Category:Seattle SuperSonics owners]]\n[[Category:Starbucks people]]\n[[Category:Washington (state) Independents]]\n[[Category:Women's National Basketball Association executives]]\n[[Category:Writers from New York City]]\n[[Category:Writers from Seattle]]\n[[Category:American people of Austrian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Russian-Jewish descent]]\n", "name_user": "DonSpencer1", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Howard_Schultz"}
{"title_page": "Baba", "text_new": "{{wiktionary|baba|b\u00e1ba|b\u00e0ba|bab\u00e0|bab\u0103}}\n'''Baba''' and similar words may refer to:\n\n{{TOC right}}\n\n== Geography ==\n* [[Baba mountain range]], also known as ''Koh-i-Baba'', in the Hindu Kush of Afghanistan\n* [[Baba Canton]], a canton in Los R\u00edos Province, Ecuador\n* [[Baba, Iran]], a village in Kurdistan Province\n* [[Baba, Kohgiluyeh and Boyer-Ahmad]], a village in Kohgiluyeh and Boyer-Ahmad Province, Iran\n* [[Baba, Masovian Voivodeship]] (east-central Poland)\n* [[Baba, Mogilno County]] in Kuyavian-Pomeranian Voivodeship (north-central Poland)\n* [[Baba, Rypin County]] in Kuyavian-Pomeranian Voivodeship (north-central Poland)\n* [[Baba, Greater Poland Voivodeship]] (west-central Poland)\n* Baba, a village in [[Horea, Alba|Horea]] Commune, Alba County, Romania\n* Baba, a village in [[Coroieni]] Commune, Maramure\u0219 County, Romania\n* Baba, a tributary of the river [[Ghelin\u021ba River|Ghelin\u021ba]] in Covasna County, Romania\n* Baba, a tributary of the river [[Putna (Siret)|Putna]] in Vrancea County, Romania\n* [[Baba River (Ouham)]], in Central African Republic, a tributary of the [[Ouham River]]\n* Baba River, in North Macedonia, noted for [[Kole\u0161ino Falls]]\n* [[Cape Baba]], a cape in Turkey\n\n== Folklore ==\n* [[Baba (goddess)]] or Bau, a Sumerian goddess depicted with the head of a dog\n* [[Baba (Egyptian god)]] or Babi, an Egyptian god in the shape of a baboon\n* [[Baba Yaga]], a mythical older female in Slavic folklore\n\n== Arts and entertainment ==\n=== Films ===\n* [[Baba (2002 film)|''Baba'' (2002 film)]], a Tamil film\n* [[B\u00e1ba (2008 film)|''B\u00e1ba'' (2008 film)]], a Czech short film\n* [[Baba (2012 film)|''Baba'' (2012 film)]], an Egyptian film\n* [[Father (2000 film)|''Father'' (2002 film)]], also known as ''B\u00e0ba'', a Chinese film\n\n=== Fictional characters ===\n* [[Baba (The Kite Runner)|Baba (''The Kite Runner'')]], in ''The Kite Runner'' media\n* [[Baba (Dragon Ball)|Baba (''Dragon Ball'')]], in ''Dragon Ball'' media\n* Baba, in ''[[Redbeard (comics)|Redbeard]]'' comics\n*Baba ([[Baba Is You]])\n\n=== Music ===\n* \"Baba\", a song from ''[[Supposed Former Infatuation Junkie]]'' by Alanis Morissette\n\n== Food ==\n* [[Baba (cake)]] or Babka, a Polish yeast cake\n* [[Baba (bread)]], a type of bread made by the Naxi people of Yunnan, China\n\n== Non-English words and titles for people ==\n* ''baba'', a familiar term for 'father' in many languages, see [[Mama and papa]]\n* [[Baba (honorific)]], an honorific used in several South Asian and Middle Eastern cultures\n* [[Baba (Alevism)]], an Alevi religious leader\n\n== People ==\n* [[Baba (name)]], people with the given name or surname\n* [[Baba clan]], a Japanese samurai family that was associated with Kai Province\n* [[Sanjay Dutt]] (born 1959), also known as Baba, Indian film actor and producer\n* A nickname for [[Raila Odinga]] (born 1945), Kenyan politician and 2nd Prime Minister of Kenya (2008\u20132013)\n\n== Other uses ==\n* [[Paopi]] or Baba, the second month of the Coptic calendar\n* [[Kurgan stelae]], anthropomorphic stone stella commonly known as baba in the East Ukraine\n* [[Baba (yacht)]], a line of yachts built in Taiwan\n* [[Baba (Pillow Pal)]], a Pillow Pal lamb made by Ty, Inc.\n* [[beta-Aminobutyric acid]] (BABA), an isomer of Aminobutyric acid\n* BABA, the New York Stock Exchange stock symbol for the [[Alibaba Group]] Holding Limited\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Babaji (disambiguation)]]\n* [[Bhabha (disambiguation)]]\n* [[Babai (disambiguation)]]\n* [[Babar (disambiguation)]]\n* [[Babu (disambiguation)]]\n* [[Baba Mountain (disambiguation)]]\n* [[Baba Vanga]] (1911\u20131996), a Bulgarian mystic known as Grandmother (Baba) Vanga\n* [[Ali Baba]], a character in ''Ali Baba and the Forty Thieves''\n* [[Standing Baba]], a Hindu who has vowed to stand\n* [[Baba ghanoush]], a Middle Eastern eggplant dish\n* [[Rum baba]], a cake saturated in rum\n* [[Godman (India)]]\n* [[Peranakan]], an ethnic group in Southeast Asia also known as ''Baba-Nyonya''\n* {{lookfrom|baba}}\n* {{intitle|baba}}\n\n{{disambiguation|geo}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Baba}}\n", "text_old": "{{wiktionary|baba|b\u00e1ba|b\u00e0ba|bab\u00e0|bab\u0103}}\n'''Baba''' and similar words may refer to:\n\n{{TOC right}}\n\n== Geography ==\n* [[Baba mountain range]], also known as ''Koh-i-Baba'', in the Hindu Kush of Afghanistan\n* [[Baba Canton]], a canton in Los R\u00edos Province, Ecuador\n* [[Baba, Iran]], a village in Kurdistan Province\n* [[Baba, Kohgiluyeh and Boyer-Ahmad]], a village in Kohgiluyeh and Boyer-Ahmad Province, Iran\n* [[Baba, Masovian Voivodeship]] (east-central Poland)\n* [[Baba, Mogilno County]] in Kuyavian-Pomeranian Voivodeship (north-central Poland)\n* [[Baba, Rypin County]] in Kuyavian-Pomeranian Voivodeship (north-central Poland)\n* [[Baba, Greater Poland Voivodeship]] (west-central Poland)\n* Baba, a village in [[Horea, Alba|Horea]] Commune, Alba County, Romania\n* Baba, a village in [[Coroieni]] Commune, Maramure\u015f County, Romania\n* Baba, a tributary of the river [[Ghelin\u021ba River|Ghelin\u021ba]] in Covasna County, Romania\n* Baba, a tributary of the river [[Putna (Siret)|Putna]] in Vrancea County, Romania\n* [[Baba River (Ouham)]], in Central African Republic, a tributary of the [[Ouham River]]\n* Baba River, in North Macedonia, noted for [[Kole\u0161ino Falls]]\n* [[Cape Baba]], a cape in Turkey\n\n== Folklore ==\n* [[Baba (goddess)]] or Bau, a Sumerian goddess depicted with the head of a dog\n* [[Baba (Egyptian god)]] or Babi, an Egyptian god in the shape of a baboon\n* [[Baba Yaga]], a mythical older female in Slavic folklore\n\n== Arts and entertainment ==\n=== Films ===\n* [[Baba (2002 film)|''Baba'' (2002 film)]], a Tamil film\n* [[B\u00e1ba (2008 film)|''B\u00e1ba'' (2008 film)]], a Czech short film\n* [[Baba (2012 film)|''Baba'' (2012 film)]], an Egyptian film\n* [[Father (2000 film)|''Father'' (2002 film)]], also known as ''B\u