{"title_page": "Tony Burman (footballer)", "text_new": "{{BLP sources|date=October 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2016}}\n{{Infobox football biography \n| name        = Tony Burman\n| image       = \n| image_size  = \n| caption     = \n| fullname    = Anthony Paul Burman\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1958|6|3|df=y}} \n| birth_place = [[Stockwell]], England\n| height      = \n| currentclub =  \n| position    = [[Forward (association football)|Forward]]\n| youthyears1 =\n| youthclubs1 = [[Queens Park Rangers F.C.|Queens Park Rangers]]\n| years1      = 1976\u20131979 | clubs1 = [[Charlton Athletic F.C.|Charlton Athletic]]   | caps1 = 19 | goals1 = 3\n| years2      = 1979\u20131987 | clubs2 = [[Dartford F.C.|Dartford]]                     | caps2 = ?  | goals2 = ?\n| years3      =        | clubs3 = [[Redbridge Forest F.C.|Leytonstone & Ilford]] | caps3 = ?  | goals3 = ?\n| years4      =        | clubs4 = [[Bromley F.C.|Bromley]]                       | caps4 = ?  | goals4 = ?\n| years5      =        | clubs5 = [[Erith & Belvedere F.C.|Erith & Belvedere]]   | caps5 = ?  | goals5 = ?\n| manageryears1 = 1993\u20131996 | managerclubs1 = [[Dartford F.C.|Dartford]]\n| manageryears2 = 2005\u20132018 | managerclubs2 = [[Dartford F.C.|Dartford]]\n| manageryears3 = 2019     | managerclubs3 = [[Dartford F.C.|Dartford]] ''(interim)''\n\n}}\n'''Anthony Paul Burman''' (born 3 June 1958) is an English semi-professional [[Association football|football]] [[Association football manager|manager]] and former player. He was last the interim manager of [[National League South]] club [[Dartford F.C.|Dartford]] in 2019.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Dartford F.C. squad}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Burman, Tony}}\n[[Category:1958 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Footballers from Stockwell]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:Charlton Athletic F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Dartford F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Redbridge Forest F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Bromley F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Erith & Belvedere F.C. players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:English football managers]]\n[[Category:Dartford F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:National League (English football) managers]]\n\n\n{{England-footy-forward-1950s-stub}}\n{{England-footy-manager-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{BLP sources|date=October 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2016}}\n{{Infobox football biography \n| name        = Tony Burman\n| image       = \n| image_size  = \n| caption     = \n| fullname    = Anthony Paul Burman\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1958|6|3|df=y}} \n| birth_place = [[Stockwell]], England\n| height      = \n| currentclub =  \n| position    = [[Forward (association football)|Forward]]\n| youthyears1 =\n| youthclubs1 = [[Queens Park Rangers F.C.|Queens Park Rangers]]\n| years1      = 1976\u20131979 | clubs1 = [[Charlton Athletic F.C.|Charlton Athletic]]   | caps1 = 19 | goals1 = 3\n| years2      = 1979\u20131987 | clubs2 = [[Dartford F.C.|Dartford]]                     | caps2 = ?  | goals2 = ?\n| years3      = ?\u2013?       | clubs3 = [[Redbridge Forest F.C.|Leytonstone & Ilford]] | caps3 = ?  | goals3 = ?\n| years4      = ?\u2013?       | clubs4 = [[Bromley F.C.|Bromley]]                       | caps4 = ?  | goals4 = ?\n| years5      = ?\u2013?       | clubs5 = [[Erith & Belvedere F.C.|Erith & Belvedere]]   | caps5 = ?  | goals5 = ?\n| manageryears1 = 1993\u20131996 | managerclubs1 = [[Dartford F.C.|Dartford]]\n| manageryears2 = 2005\u20132018 | managerclubs2 = [[Dartford F.C.|Dartford]]\n| manageryears3 = 2019     | managerclubs3 = [[Dartford F.C.|Dartford]] ''(interim)''\n\n}}\n'''Anthony Paul Burman''' (born 3 June 1958) is an English semi-professional [[Association football|football]] [[Association football manager|manager]] and former player. He was last the interim manager of [[National League South]] club [[Dartford F.C.|Dartford]] in 2019.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Dartford F.C. squad}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Burman, Tony}}\n[[Category:1958 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Footballers from Stockwell]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:Charlton Athletic F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Dartford F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Redbridge Forest F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Bromley F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Erith & Belvedere F.C. players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:English football managers]]\n[[Category:Dartford F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:National League (English football) managers]]\n\n\n{{England-footy-forward-1950s-stub}}\n{{England-footy-manager-stub}}\n", "name_user": "GiantSnowman", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tony_Burman_(footballer)"}
{"title_page": "Buddy Miller", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2017}}\n{{Infobox musical artist | <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name                = Buddy Miller\n| image               = Buddy-Miller in 2010.jpg\n| caption             = Miller at the [[SXSW]] festival in 2010, Austin, Texas.\n| background          = solo_singer\n| birth_name          =\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|1952|09|06}}\n| birth_place         = [[Fairborn, Ohio|Fairborn]], Ohio\n| instrument          = Vocals, guitar\n| genre               = [[Country music|Country]], [[Americana music|Americana]]\n| occupation          = Musician, singer-songwriter, producer\n| years_active        = 1983\u2013present\n| label               = [[HighTone Records|HighTone]], [[New West Records|New West]]\n| associated_acts     = [[Julie Miller]], [[Sweet Harmony Traveling Revue]], Buddy Miller Band, [[Patty Griffin]], [[Shawn Colvin]], [[Gillian Welch]], [[David Rawlings]], [[Emmylou Harris]], [[Band of Joy]], [[Steve Earle]]\n| website             = {{URL|buddyandjulie.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''Steven Paul \"Buddy\" Miller''' (born September 6, 1952) is an American singer, songwriter, musician, recording artist and producer, currently living in [[Nashville, Tennessee|Nashville]], Tennessee. Miller is married to and has recorded with singer-songwriter [[Julie Miller]].\n\n== Early life and music career ==\nBuddy was born in [[Fairborn, Ohio|Fairborn]], Ohio, near [[Dayton]], and his family ended up settling in [[Princeton, New Jersey|Princeton]], New Jersey.<ref name=BM-nodep-2008>{{cite web|last1=Alden|first1=Grant|title=Buddy Miller \u2013 A disquisition on the centrality of love and faith in the music of Buddy Miller and the several other reasons he is artist of the decade. And stuff.|url=http://nodepression.com/article/buddy-miller-disquisition-centrality-love-and-faith-music-buddy-miller-and-several-other|website=No Depression|publisher=Freshgrass, LLC|accessdate=April 16, 2015}}</ref> His grandfather gave him the nickname \"Buddy.\"<ref name=BM-crossrhythms-1995>{{cite news|last1=staff writer|first1= |title=Buddy Miller: The Nashville-based country singer, musician and producer|url=http://www.crossrhythms.co.uk/articles/music/Buddy_Miller_The_Nashvillebased_country_singer_musician_and_producer/40337/p1/|accessdate=April 4, 2017|work=CrossRhythms|date=August 1, 1995}}</ref>\n\nIn 1975, he moved to [[Austin, Texas|Austin]], Texas and played [[rockabilly]] music in [[Ray Campi]]'s band. He auditioned for and played in a band with Julie Griffin (soon to be his second wife).<ref name=BM-nodep-2008 /><ref name=BM-as-2009>{{cite news|last1=Cooper|first1=Peter|title=Buddy & Julie Miller: The Proof is On the Pizza Boxes or Nothing is Written in Stone|url=https://americansongwriter.com/2009/03/buddy-julie-miller-the-proof-is-on-the-pizza-boxes-or-nothing-is-written-in-stone/|accessdate=March 6, 2017|work=American Songwriter|date=March 1, 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn 1980, they moved to [[New York City]], and Miller formed the Buddy Miller Band,<ref>{{cite web|last1=Dougherty|first1=Steve|title=In Nashville, the Buddy System|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424127887324616604578304381471557880|website=The Wall Street Journal|publisher=The Wall Street Journal|accessdate=April 14, 2015}}</ref> which included singer-songwriter [[Shawn Colvin]] on vocals and guitar. He also performed with [[Jim Lauderdale]] and [[Larry Campbell]].<ref name=BM-as-2009 /> Each Sunday, Miller performed in [[Kinky Friedman]]'s band at the [[Lone Star Cafe]].<ref name=BM-newyorker-2013>{{cite news|last1=Baird\n| first1=Robert|title=Buddy and Jim Take Manhattan|url=http://www.newyorker.com/culture/culture-desk/buddy-and-jim-take-manhattan|accessdate=April 4, 2017|work=The New Yorker|date=March 1, 2013}}</ref>\n\nMiller moved to [[Nashville]] in the 1990s, after a stint in Los Angeles. He worked on recording sessions as a guitar player and vocalist, and began producing his own records in his living room studio named Dogtown.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Rotondi|first1=James|title=Universal Audio|url=http://www.uaudio.com/blog/artist-interview-buddy-miller/|website=Buddy Miller on Making Records with Apollo and UAD-2 Plug-Ins|publisher=Universal Audio|accessdate=April 14, 2015}}</ref><ref name=BM-paste-2002>{{cite news|last1=Winters|first1=Pamela|title=Buddy Miller: Playing with Guitars|url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2002/12/buddy-miller-1.html|accessdate=March 5, 2017|work=Paste Magazine|date=December 24, 2002}}</ref>\n\n== Recordings ==\nIn 1995, Buddy along with the Sacred Cows recorded a gospel album, ''Man on the Moon''.<ref name=BM-CrossRhythms-1995>{{cite news|last1=Brassington|first1=Dave|title=Buddy Miller and the Sacred Cows \u2013 Man on the Moon|url=http://www.crossrhythms.co.uk/products/Buddy_Miller_And_The_Sacred_Cows/Man_On_The_Moon/7594/|accessdate=March 4, 2017|work=CrossRhythms|date=June 1, 1995}}</ref>\n\nHis first solo recording, ''Your Love and Other Lies'', was released in 1995.<ref name=BM-MKOC-2016>{{cite news|last1=Razor X|first1= |title=Album Review: Buddy Miller \u2013 \u2018Your Love and Other Lies\u2019|url=https://mykindofcountry.wordpress.com/2016/02/03/album-review-buddy-miller-your-love-and-other-lies/|accessdate=March 4, 2017|work=My Kind of Country|date=February 3, 2016}}</ref> It was followed by ''Poison Love'' in 1997<ref name=BM-nodep-1997>{{cite news|last1=archive|first1= |title=Buddy Miller \u2013 Poison Love|url=http://nodepression.com/album-review/buddy-miller-poison-love/|accessdate=March 4, 2017\n| work=No Depression|date=August 31, 1997}}</ref> and ''Cruel Moon'' in 1999.<ref name=BM-AVclub-2002\n>{{cite news|last1=Klein|first1=Joshua|title=Buddy Miller: Cruel Moon|url=http://www.avclub.com/review/buddy-miller-emcruel-moonem-21088|accessdate=March 4, 2017|work=A.V. Club|date=March 29, 2002}}</ref>\n\nHe and his wife, Julie Miller, released ''[[Buddy & Julie Miller]]'' in 2001, which won the Album of the Year Award from the Americana Music Association.<ref>{{cite web |title=Recipient Archive |url=http://americanamusic.org/recipient-archive |website=Americana Music Association |publisher=Americana Music |accessdate=April 14, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121018055116/http://americanamusic.org/recipient-archive |archivedate=October 18, 2012 |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\nIn 2002, he released ''Midnight and Lonesome''<ref name=BM-nodep-2002>{{cite news|last1=archive|first1= |title=Buddy Miller \u2013 Midnight And Lonesome|url=http://nodepression.com/album-review/buddy-miller-midnight-and-lonesome|accessdate=March 4, 2017|work=No Depression |date=October 31, 2002}}</ref> and in 2004 he released ''[[Universal United House of Prayer]]''.<ref name=BM-PopMatters-2004>{{cite news|last1=MacNeil|first1=Jason|title=Buddy Miller: Universal United House of Prayer|url=http://www.popmatters.com/review/millerbuddy-universal/|accessdate=March 4, 2017|work=PopMatters|date=October 27, 2004}}</ref>\n\n2009 brought another Buddy and Julie duet album ''Written in Chalk''<ref name=BM-nodep-2009>{{cite news|last1=DLHTown|first1=|title=Buddy & Julie Miller \u2013 'Written in Chalk' (review)|url=http://nodepression.com/article/buddy-julie-miller-written-chalk-review|accessdate=March 4, 2017|work=No Depression|date=March 2, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170305193544/http://nodepression.com/article/buddy-julie-miller-written-chalk-review|archive-date=March 5, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> and in 2011 Buddy collaborated with [[Bill Frisell]], [[Marc Ribot]], and [[Greg Leisz]] to release ''The Majestic Silver Strings''.<ref name=BM-PopMatters-2011>{{cite news|last1=Layman|first1=Will|title=Buddy Miller: The Majestic Silver Strings|url=http://www.popmatters.com/review/137061-buddy-miller-the-majestic-silver-strings/|accessdate=March 4, 2017\n| work=PopMatters|date=March 2, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Buddy and [[Jim Lauderdale]] released the duet album ''Buddy & Jim''<ref name=BM-PopMatters-2013>{{cite news|last1=Berick|first1=Michael|title=Buddy Miller & Jim Lauderdale: Buddy & Jim|url=https://americansongwriter.com/2013/01/buddy-miller-jim-lauderdale-buddy-jim/|accessdate=March 4, 2017|work=American Songwriter|date=January 16, 2013}}</ref> and in 2016, Buddy recorded sessions by [[Kacey Musgraves]], [[Nikki Lane]], [[Lee Ann Womack]], [[Brandi Carlile]], and [[Kris Kristofferson]] on the album ''Cayamo: Sessions at Sea''.<ref name=BM-guardian-2016>{{cite news|last1=Spencer|first1=Neil|title=Buddy Miller & Friends: Cayamo Sessions at Sea review \u2013 country cruising|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2016/jan/24/buddy-miller-and-friends-cayamo-sessions-at-sea-review-kacey-musgraves-kris-kristofferson-colvin|accessdate=March 4, 2017|work=The Guardian|date=January 24, 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Touring and performance ==\nMiller has toured as lead guitarist and backing vocalist for [[Emmylou Harris]]'s [[Spyboy (album)|Spyboy]] band,<ref name=EH-nodep-1998>{{cite news |last1=archive|first1= |title=Emmylou Harris \u2013 Lookin' for the water from a deeper well|url=http://nodepression.com/article/emmylou-harris-lookin-water-deeper-well|accessdate=March 5, 2017|work=No Depression|date=August 31, 1998}}</ref> [[Steve Earle]] on his [[El Coraz\u00f3n (Steve Earle album)|El Corazon]] tour,<ref name=SE-nodep-1998>{{cite news |last1=archive|first1= |title=Steve Earle / Buddy & Julie Miller \u2013 The Phoenix (Toronto, Ontario)|url=http://nodepression.com/live-review/steve-earle-buddy-julie-miller-phoenix-toronto-ontario/|accessdate=March 5, 2017|work=No Depression|date=February 28, 1998}}</ref> and Emmylou Harris and [[Linda Ronstadt]] on their [[Western Wall: The Tucson Sessions|Western Wall]] tour.<ref name=EH-austinchron-1999>{{cite news |last1=Lynch|first1=David|title=Linda Ronstadt & Emmylou Harris, Bass Concert Hall, October 10|url=http://www.austinchronicle.com/music/1999-10-22/74342/|accessdate=March 5, 2017|work=The Austin Chronicle|date=October 22, 1999}}</ref>\n\nIn 2002, Miller toured as part of the [[Down from the Mountain]] Tour along with [[Alison Krauss and Union Station]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Drennen|first1=Eileen|title=The Secret Is Out on the Millers|url=http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/2002-01-16/lifestyle/0201150339_1_buddy-and-julie-emmylou-harris-julie-miller|website=Orlando Sentinel|publisher=Orlando Sentinel|accessdate=April 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2004, Miller toured with Emmylou Harris, [[Patty Griffin]], [[Gillian Welch]] and [[David Rawlings]] as the [[Sweet Harmony Traveling Revue]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Jackson|first1=Josh|title=The Sweet Harmony Traveling Revue|url=http://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2004/08/the-sweet-harmony-traveling-revue-1.html|website=Paste Magazine|publisher=Paste Media Group}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, Miller toured as part of the band on [[Robert Plant]] and [[Alison Krauss]]'s [[Raising Sand]] tour of the U.S. and Europe.<ref name=BM-nashscene-2010>{{cite news|last1=Neal|first1=Chris|title=How Buddy Miller brought Robert Plant's Band of Joy into the heart of Americana|url=http://www.nashvillescene.com/news/article/13035342/how-buddy-miller-brought-robert-plants-band-of-joy-into-the-heart-of-americana|accessdate=March 4, 2017|work=Nashville Scene|date=September 2, 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, Buddy joined Emmylou Harris, Patty Griffin and Shawn Colvin on tour as Three Girls and Their Buddy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nonesuch.com/journal/emmylou-harris-shawn-colvin-announce-three-girls-and-their-buddy-tour-pre-order-event-2009-03-16|title=Emmylou Harris, Shawn Colvin Announce \"Three Girls and Their Buddy\" Tour, Pre-Order Event-Nonesuch Records|website=Nonesuch Records Official Website|language=en|access-date=January 24, 2017}}</ref> While on that tour, following a performance in Baltimore on February 19, 2009, Miller suffered a heart attack. He underwent successful triple bypass surgery at Johns Hopkins Hospital on February 20.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Betts|first1=Stephen|title=Buddy Miller Recovering from Heart Surgery|url=http://theboot.com/buddy-miller-recovering-from-heart-surgery/|website=The Boot|publisher=Taste of Country|accessdate=April 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, Miller again joined Robert Plant and Patty Griffin with Plant's [[Band of Joy]], touring the U.S. and Europe.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Neal|first1=Chris|title=How Buddy Miller brought Robert Plant's Band of Joy into the heart of Americana|url=http://www.nashvillescene.com/nashville/how-buddy-miller-brought-robert-plants-band-of-joy-into-the-heart-of-americana/Content?oid=1798568|website=Nashville Scene|publisher=City Press LLC|accessdate=April 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Buddy toured with [[Jim Lauderdale]] on the Buddy and Jim Tour.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Parker|first1=Eric|title=Buddy Miller And Jim Lauderdale Announce Tour|url=http://www.musicrow.com/2012/11/buddy-miller-and-jim-lauderdale-announce-duet-tour/|website=MusicRow|publisher=MusicRow \u2013 Nashville's Music Industry Publication|accessdate=April 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Buddy was part of the Lampedusa: Concerts for Refugees tour featuring [[Patty Griffin]], Emmylou Harris, Steve Earle, and the Milk Carton Kids.<ref name=EH-highroad-2016>{{cite news |last1=uncredited|first1= |title=Concert Tour Featuring Emmylou Harris, Patty Griffin, Buddy Miller and More will Benefit Refugee Education|url=http://www.highroadtouring.com/concert-tour-featuring-emmylou-harris-patty-griffin-buddy-miller-and-more-will-benefit-refugee-education/|accessdate=March 5, 2017|work=High Road Touring|date=September 6, 2016}}</ref>\n\nFor the past decade, Buddy has often been a part of the Cayamo Cruise, which sails from [[Miami]] to [[St. Maarten]] and [[Tortola]]. Each year, prominent Americana musicians are on board, and Buddy often collaborates and records with them.<ref name=BM-bsit-2016>{{cite news|last1=uncredited|title=The Producers: Buddy Miller|url=http://www.thebluegrasssituation.com/read/producers-buddy-miller/|accessdate=March 10, 2016|work=The Bluegrass Situation|date=March 4, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160307060420/http://www.thebluegrasssituation.com/read/producers-buddy-miller|archive-date=March 7, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nHe is a regular performer at the annual [[Hardly Strictly Bluegrass]] music festival in [[San Francisco]] where, billed as Buddy Miller's Cavalcade of Stars, he features a changing roster of guest performers.{{citation needed|date=December 2018}}\n\n== Recording work for others ==\n=== Record producer ===\n\nMiller has produced albums for artists including [[Richard Thompson (musician)|Richard Thompson]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Richard Thompson: Trio Album Produced by Buddy Miller|url=http://www.jambase.com/Articles/108508/Richard-Thompson-Trio-Album-Produced-by-Buddy-Miller|website=JamBase|publisher=JamBase Inc|accessdate=April 17, 2015}}</ref> [[Shawn Colvin]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Bio|url=http://shawncolvin.com/info/bio/|website=Shawn Colvin|publisher=Shawn Colvin|accessdate=April 17, 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150417232503/http://shawncolvin.com/info/bio/|archivedate=April 17, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref> [[The Devil Makes Three (band)|The Devil Makes Three]],<ref>{{cite web|last1=Bailey|first1=Rachel|title=The Devil Makes Three to Release Buddy Miller-Produced Album|url=http://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2013/07/vermont-americana-trio-the-devil.html|website=Paste Magazine|publisher=Paste Media Group|accessdate=April 17, 2015}}</ref> [[Allison Moorer]],<ref>{{cite web|last1=Bialas|first1=Michael|title=All Aboard: This Roller Coaster Gets Down to Believing in Allison Moorer|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/michael-bialas/all-aboard-this-roller-co_b_6789260.html|website=Huffington Post|publisher=TheHuffingtonPost.com|accessdate=April 17, 2015}}</ref> [[the Wood Brothers]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Bio|url=http://www.thewoodbros.com/bio/|website=The Wood Brothers|publisher=The Wood Brothers|accessdate=April 17, 2015}}</ref> the [[Carolina Chocolate Drops]],<ref>{{cite web|title=About|url=http://www.carolinachocolatedrops.com/band/about.html|website=Carolina Chocolate Drops|accessdate=April 17, 2015}}</ref> [[the McCrarys]],<ref>{{cite web|last1=Dauphin|first1=Chuck|title=Exclusive Album Premiere: Listen to the McCrary Sisters' 'Let's Go' Now|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/the-615/6495048/mccrary-sisters-lets-go-album-premiere|website=Billboard|publisher=Billboard|accessdate=April 17, 2015}}</ref> and [[Ralph Stanley]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Betts|first1=Stephen|title=Ralph Stanley on His All-Star Album With Robert Plant, Dierks Bentley|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/features/ralph-stanley-on-his-all-star-album-with-robert-plant-dierks-bentley-20150122|website=Rolling Stone|accessdate=April 17, 2015}}</ref> He has co-produced records with [[Robert Plant]], [[Jim Lauderdale]] and [[Jimmie Dale Gilmore]].\n\nIn 2006 [[Solomon Burke]] recorded his country album ''Nashville'' with Miller. [[Emmylou Harris]], [[Patty Griffin]], [[Gillian Welch]] and [[Dolly Parton]] appear as duet partners.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Fink|first1=Matt|title=SOLOMON BURKE: Nashville Calling|url=http://www.americansongwriter.com/2007/01/solomon-burke-nashville-calling/|website=American Songwriter|publisher=ForASong Media|accessdate=April 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\nMiller produced [[Patty Griffin]]'s [[Downtown Church]]<ref>{{cite web|last1=Ayers|first1=Michael|title=Patty Griffin Returns With Gospel Inspired 'Downtown Church'|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/960787/patty-griffin-returns-with-gospel-inspired-downtown-church|website=Billboard|publisher=Billboard|accessdate=April 14, 2015}}</ref> that was released in 2010 and won a [[Grammy Award]] for Best Traditional Gospel Album on February 13, 2011.<ref>{{cite web|title=Winners|url=http://www.grammy.com/nominees/search?year=2010|website=Grammy.com|accessdate=April 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\nMiller has produced his own solo albums as well as recordings for and with his wife, singer-songwriter [[Julie Miller]].\n\n=== Session work ===\nHe co-produced and performed on [[Jimmie Dale Gilmore]]'s 2000 album ''One Endless Night''.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Gettelman|first1=Perry|title=Gilmore Is Great on 'One Endless Night'|url=http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/2000-03-10/entertainment/0003090384_1_jimmie-dale-dale-gilmore-braver-newer|website=Orlando Sentinel|publisher=Orlando Sentinel|accessdate=April 14, 2015}}</ref> He also played on [[Lucinda Williams]]'s ''[[Car Wheels on a Gravel Road]]'' album.<ref name=LW-nodep-2009>{{cite news|last1=Giddens|first1=Jeff|title=Throwback Thursday \u2013 Lucinda Williams \u2013 Car Wheels on a Gravel Road|url=http://nodepression.com/article/throwback-thursday-\u2013-lucinda-williams-car-wheels-gravel-road|accessdate=March 4, 2017|work=No Depression|date=September 5, 2009}}</ref>\n\nMiller has worked as an instrumentalist or vocalist on records by [[Johnny Cash]], [[Levon Helm]], [[Lee Ann Womack]], [[Patty Griffin]], [[Emmylou Harris]], [[Victoria Williams]], [[Shawn Colvin]], [[Bobby Bare]], [[Chris Knight (musician)|Chris Knight]], [[John Fogerty]], the [[The Chieftains|Chieftains]], [[Frank Black]], [[Rodney Crowell]], [[Dixie Chicks]], [[Elvis Costello]], [[Alison Krauss]] and [[Robert Plant]].{{Citation needed|date=April 2015}} He has also worked as a recording engineer, mixer or mastering engineer on records by [[Willie Nelson]], [[Emmylou Harris]], [[Shawn Colvin]], [[Jim Lauderdale]], and [[Patty Griffin]].{{Citation needed|date=April 2015}}\n\n=== Songwriting ===\n{{Unsourced BLP section|date=April 2015}}\n[[Levon Helm]], Patty Griffin, Emmylou Harris, [[Lee Ann Womack]], [[Dixie Chicks]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/song/hole-in-my-head-mt0052994163|title=Hole in my Head|date=5 August 2019|website=Allmusic}}</ref> [[Hank Williams III]], [[Dierks Bentley]], [[Patty Loveless]], [[Tab Benoit]] and [[Brooks & Dunn]] have recorded songs written by Miller.\n\n=== Film and TV ===\n\nMiller signed on as a producer for the ABC TV series [[Nashville (2012 TV series)|Nashville]] in 2012.  He was the executive music producer for the show in seasons two and three.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Gold|first1=Adam|title=T Bone Burnett Not Returning to Nashville, Buddy Miller to Take Over as Show's Music Producer|url=http://www.nashvillescene.com/nashvillecream/archives/2013/06/20/t-bone-burnett-not-returning-to-nashville-buddy-miller-to-take-over-as-shows-music-producer|website=Nashville Scene|publisher=City Press, LLC|accessdate=April 14, 2015}}</ref> He also was music producer and musical director for Nashville: On The Record Live Specials.<ref>{{cite web|last1=MusicLounge|title=Nashville: On The Record Special|url=http://abc.go.com/music-lounge/news/nashville-on-the-record/nashville-otr-special|website=ABC Music Lounge|publisher=ABC|accessdate=April 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\nAlong with Don Was, Miller was the musical director for The Life and Songs of Emmylou Harris tribute concert.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Dunham|first1=Nancy|title=199 390 1131 Print The Five Best Things We Saw at the Life & Songs of Emmylou Harris Concert|url=http://www.countryweekly.com/news/five-best-things-we-saw-life-songs-emmylou-harris-concert|website=Country Weekly|publisher=Cumulus Media|accessdate=April 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\nMiller was musical director and bandleader for the Americana Music Association's Honors & Awards shows broadcast on AXS TV and PBS.<ref>{{cite web|title=Americana Music Honors & Awards to Air on PBS's ''Austin City Limits'', Featuring Robert Plant, Ry Cooder|url=http://www.nonesuch.com/journal/americana-music-honors-awards-pbs-austin-city-limits-robert-plant-ry-cooder-2014-11-20|website=Nonesuch Records|publisher=Nonesuch Records|accessdate=April 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\nBuddy has covered Tom T. Hall's song, \"That's How I Got to Memphis\", which [[Jeff Daniels]] sang in the final episode of HBO's ''The Newsroom'' in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kienzle|first1=Rich|title='The Newsroom's' Country Interlude: 'That's How I Got To Memphis'|url=http://communityvoices.post-gazette.com/arts-entertainment-living/get-rhythm/item/38608-the-newsroom-s-country-interlude-that-s-how-i-got-to-memphis|website=Post-Gazette|publisher=PG Publishing, Co|accessdate=April 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\nStarz political drama Boss used the Plant-Miller produced \"Satan, Your Kingdom Must Come Down\" as its theme song.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Neal|first1=Chris|title=How Buddy Miller brought Robert Plant's Band of Joy into the heart of Americana|url=http://www.nashvillescene.com/nashville/how-buddy-miller-brought-robert-plants-band-of-joy-into-the-heart-of-americana/Content?oid=1798568|website=Nashville Scene|publisher=City Press, LLC|accessdate=April 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\nMiller produced the track \"Beyond the Blue\" featuring [[Emmylou Harris]] and [[Patty Griffin]] for the 2000 film ''[[Where the Heart Is (2000 film)|Where the Heart Is]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Where The Heart Is|url=http://www.tcm.com/tcmdb/title/454044/Where-the-Heart-Is/music.html|website=Turner Classic Movies|publisher=Turner Entertainment Networks, Inc.|accessdate=April 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015 he appeared on [[Christina Aguilera]]'s song, \"Shotgun\", which was written for her appearance on ''[[Nashville (2012 TV series)|Nashville]]''.<ref name=CA-nodep-2015>{{cite news|last1=Miller|first1=Jordan|title=Listen: Christina Aguilera\u2019's Country Ballad \"Shotgun\"|url=http://www.breatheheavy.com/listen-christina-aguileras-country-ballad-shotgun/|accessdate=March 4, 2017|work=Breathe Heavy|date=April 21, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Miller contributed his cover of [[Mark Heard]]'s song \"Treasure of the Broken Land\" to the tribute album ''Treasure of the Broken Land: the Songs of Mark Heard''.<ref name=BM-rollingstone-2017>{{cite news|last1=Betts|first1=Stephen L.|title=Hear Buddy Miller's Intense New Song From Mark Heard Tribute Album|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/country/premieres/hear-buddy-millers-new-song-from-mark-heard-tribute-album-w478430|accessdate=April 24, 2017|work=Rolling Stone|date=April 24, 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Awards, accolades, and other activities ==\nBetween 2002 and 2013, Miller won twelve [[Americana Music Honors & Awards]] and was nominated for seven others.<ref>{{cite web |title=Recipient Archive |url=http://americanamusic.org/recipient-archive |website=Americana Music Association |publisher=Americana Music |accessdate=April 15, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121018055116/http://americanamusic.org/recipient-archive |archivedate=October 18, 2012 |df=mdy }}</ref> Since 2005, he has led the Americana All Star Band, which performs with nominated artists during the [[Americana Music Honors & Awards]] ceremonies, held annually at the [[Ryman Auditorium]].<ref>{{cite web |title=About The Awards |url=http://americanamusic.org/about-awards |website=Americana Music Association |publisher=Americana Music |accessdate=April 15, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150420081843/http://americanamusic.org/about-awards |archivedate=April 20, 2015 |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\nNo Depression magazine named him Artist of the Decade in 2008.<ref name=BM-nodep-2008 />\n\n=== Americana Music Awards ===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Category\n! Work\n! Result\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|2002\n| Artist of the Year\n| Buddy and Julie Miller\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Album of the Year\n| ''Buddy & Julie Miller''\n| {{win}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|2003\n| Instrumentalist of the Year\n| Buddy Miller\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Album of the Year\n|''Midnight & Lonesome''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"|2005\n| Artist of the Year\n| Buddy Miller\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Song of the Year\n|''Worry Too Much''\n| {{win}}\n|-\n| Album of the Year\n|''[[Universal United House of Prayer]]''\n| {{win}}\n|-\n| 2007\n| rowspan=\"3\"|Instrumentalist of the Year\n| rowspan=\"3\"| Buddy Miller\n| {{win}}\n|-\n| 2008\n| {{win}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"5\"|2009\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Album of the Year\n| \"Written In Chalk\"\n| {{win}}\n|-\n| Song of the Year\n| \"Chalk\"\n| {{win}}\n|-\n| Duo/Group of the Year\n| Buddy and Julie Miller\n| {{win}}\n|-\n| Artist of the Year\n| rowspan=\"5\"|Buddy Miller\n| {{win}}\n|-\n| 2010\n| rowspan=\"2\"|Instrumentalist of the Year\n| {{win}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|2011\n| {{win}}\n|-\n| Artist of the Year\n| {{win}}\n|-\n| 2012\n| Instrumentalist of the Year\n| {{win}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"|2013\n| Duo/Group of the Year\n| Buddy Miller and [[Jim Lauderdale]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Artist of the Year\n| Buddy Miller\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Album of the Year\n|''Buddy & Jim''\n| {{nom}}\n|}\n\n=== Grammy Awards ===\nMiller is a four-time Grammy nominee, winning once in 2010 for producing ''[[Downtown Church]]'' by [[Patty Griffin]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/artists/buddy-miller|title=Buddy Miller|date=June 4, 2019|website=Grammy.com}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Category\n! Work\n! Result\n|-\n| [[44th Annual Grammy Awards|2001]]\n| [[Grammy Award for Best Contemporary Folk Album|Best Contemporary Folk Album]]\n| ''[[Buddy & Julie Miller]]''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[47th Annual Grammy Awards|2004]]\n| [[Best Southern, Country or Bluegrass Gospel Album]]\n| ''[[Universal United House of Prayer]]''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[53rd Annual Grammy Awards|2010]]\n| [[Grammy Award for Best Traditional Gospel Album|Best Traditional Gospel Album]]\n| ''[[Downtown Church]]''\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[56th Annual Grammy Awards|2013]]\n| [[Grammy Award for Best Americana Album|Best Americana Album]]\n| ''Buddy & Jim''\n| {{nom}}\n|}\n\n== Radio ==\nMiller and his longtime friend and collaborator [[Jim Lauderdale]] teamed up in 2012 to produce ''The Buddy & Jim Radio Show'', broadcast on [[Outlaw Country (Sirius XM)|Sirius XM Outlaw Country]].<ref name=BM-songwriter-2012>{{cite news|last1=Schlansky|first1=Evan|title=Buddy Miller and Jim Lauderdale Launch Radio Show; Listen To Lucinda Williams' Guest Spot|url=https://americansongwriter.com/2012/08/buddy-miller-and-jim-lauderdale-launch-radio-show-listen-to-lucinda-williams-guest-spot/|accessdate=March 4, 2017|work=American Songwriter|date=August 1, 2012}}</ref>\n\n== Music gear ==\n[[Fender Musical Instruments Corporation|Fender]] produces a Buddy Miller signature acoustic guitar.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Bryant|first1=Will|title=Fender Acoustic > Buddy Miller Signature Guitar|url=http://www.americansongwriter.com/2009/06/fender-acoustic-buddy-miller-signature-guitar/|website=American Songwriter|publisher=ForASong Media, LLC|accessdate=April 16, 2015}}</ref>\n\nBuddy frequently uses vintage Wandr\u00e9 electric guitars<ref name=BM-paste-2004>{{cite news|last1=Scoppa|first1=Bud|title=Buddy Miller: Fancy is as Fancy Does|url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2004/10/buddy-miller.html|accessdate=March 4, 2017|work=[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]]|date=October 1, 2004}}</ref> and TEO mando-guitars.<ref name=\"BM\n-TEO-2017\">{{cite web | url=http://www.teoguitars.com/artists.html | title=TEO Guitars: Artists | work=TEO Guitars website| accessdate= March 4, 2017| author=uncredited}}</ref>\n\nIn his studio, Buddy uses a pair of Swart amplifiers: Atomic Space Tones and Atomic Space Tone Pros, and two tremolos panned in stereo at conflicting settings.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite news|last1=Chandler|first1=Stacy|title=SPOTLIGHT: Come Along as Buddy Miller shows Aaron Lee Tasjan around His Home Studio|url=https://www.nodepression.com/spotlight-come-along-as-buddy-miller-shows-aaron-lee-tasjan-around-his-home-studio/|accessdate=June 26, 2019|work=No Depression|date=June 24, 2019}}</ref> Onstage, he often uses a Swart Atomic Space Tones amplifier and a Fulltone Supa-Trem2 pedal.<ref name=BM-premier-2016>{{cite news|last1=Drozdowski|first1=Ted|title=Session Sages: Nick Raskulinecz, Dave Cobb, and Buddy Miller on Recording Guitars|url=https://www.premierguitar.com/articles/24816-session-sages-nick-raskulinecz-dave-cobb-amp-buddy-miller-on-recording-guitars|accessdate=April 24, 2017|work=Premier Guitar|date=November 16, 2016}}</ref>\n\nHe mostly records using [[Pro Tools]], but in his recording studio Buddy treasures a 1970s Trident B Range 28\u00d724 analog recording console that previously belonged to Mark Heard.<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref name=BM-rollingstone-2017 />\n\n== Compositions  ==\n{{Main| Compositions by Buddy and Julie Miller}}\n\n== Discography ==\n{{Main| Buddy Miller discography}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|Buddy Miller}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.buddyandjulie.com/}}\n* {{Allmusic | id= buddy-miller-mn0000640419 | label= Buddy Miller}}\n* {{discogs artist|275416-Buddy-Miller|Buddy Miller}}\n{{Buddy Miller|state=autocollapse}} \n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Miller, Buddy}}\n[[Category:American country singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:American country guitarists]]\n[[Category:American male guitarists]]\n[[Category:American male singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:American record producers]]\n[[Category:American audio engineers]]\n[[Category:1952 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Nashville, Tennessee]]\n[[Category:People from Fairborn, Ohio]]\n[[Category:New West Records artists]]\n[[Category:Songwriters from Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Songwriters from Ohio]]\n[[Category:Guitarists from Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Engineers from Ohio]]\n[[Category:Engineers from Tennessee]]\n[[Category:20th-century American guitarists]]\n[[Category:Band of Joy members]]\n[[Category:Guitarists from Ohio]]\n[[Category:Country musicians from Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Country musicians from Ohio]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male musicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2017}}\n{{Infobox musical artist | <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name                = Buddy Miller\n| image               = Buddy-Miller in 2010.jpg\n| caption             = Miller at the [[SXSW]] festival in 2010, Austin, Texas.\n| background          = solo_singer\n| birth_name          =\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|1952|09|06}}\n| birth_place         = [[Fairborn, Ohio|Fairborn]], Ohio\n| instrument          = Vocals, guitar\n| genre               = [[Country music|Country]], [[Americana music|Americana]]\n| occupation          = Musician, singer-songwriter, producer\n| years_active        = 1983\u2013present\n| label               = [[HighTone Records|HighTone]], [[New West Records|New West]]\n| associated_acts     = [[Julie Miller]], [[Sweet Harmony Traveling Revue]], Buddy Miller Band, [[Patty Griffin]], [[Shawn Colvin]], [[Gillian Welch]], [[David Rawlings]], [[Emmylou Harris]], [[Band of Joy]], [[Steve Earle]]\n| website             = {{URL|buddyandjulie.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''Steven Paul \"Buddy\" Miller''' (born September 6, 1952) is an American singer, songwriter, musician, recording artist and producer, currently living in [[Nashville, Tennessee|Nashville]], Tennessee. Miller is married to and has recorded with singer-songwriter [[Julie Miller]].\n\n== Early life and music career ==\nBuddy was born in [[Fairborn, Ohio|Fairborn]], Ohio, near [[Dayton]], and his family ended up settling in [[Princeton, New Jersey|Princeton]], New Jersey.<ref name=BM-nodep-2008>{{cite web|last1=Alden|first1=Grant|title=Buddy Miller - A disquisition on the centrality of love and faith in the music of Buddy Miller and the several other reasons he is artist of the decade. And stuff.|url=http://nodepression.com/article/buddy-miller-disquisition-centrality-love-and-faith-music-buddy-miller-and-several-other|website=No Depression|publisher=Freshgrass, LLC|accessdate=April 16, 2015}}</ref> His grandfather gave him the nickname \"Buddy.\"<ref name=BM-crossrhythms-1995>{{cite news|last1=staff writer|first1= |title=Buddy Miller: The Nashville-based country singer, musician and producer|url=http://www.crossrhythms.co.uk/articles/music/Buddy_Miller_The_Nashvillebased_country_singer_musician_and_producer/40337/p1/|accessdate=April 4, 2017|work=CrossRhythms|date=August 1, 1995}}</ref>\n\nIn 1975, he moved to [[Austin, Texas|Austin]], Texas and played [[rockabilly]] music in [[Ray Campi]]'s band. He auditioned for and played in a band with Julie Griffin (soon to be his second wife).<ref name=BM-nodep-2008 /><ref name=BM-as-2009>{{cite news|last1=Cooper|first1=Peter|title=Buddy & Julie Miller: The Proof is On the Pizza Boxes or Nothing is Written in Stone|url=https://americansongwriter.com/2009/03/buddy-julie-miller-the-proof-is-on-the-pizza-boxes-or-nothing-is-written-in-stone/|accessdate=March 6, 2017|work=American Songwriter|date=March 1, 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn 1980, they moved to [[New York City]], and Miller formed the Buddy Miller Band,<ref>{{cite web|last1=Dougherty|first1=Steve|title=In Nashville, the Buddy System|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424127887324616604578304381471557880|website=Wall Street Journal|publisher=Wall Street Journal|accessdate=April 14, 2015}}</ref> which included singer-songwriter [[Shawn Colvin]] on vocals and guitar. He also performed with [[Jim Lauderdale]] and [[Larry Campbell]].<ref name=BM-as-2009 /> Each Sunday, Miller performed in [[Kinky Friedman]]'s band at the [[Lone Star Cafe]].<ref name=BM-newyorker-2013>{{cite news|last1=Baird\n| first1=Robert|title=Buddy and Jim Take Manhattan|url=http://www.newyorker.com/culture/culture-desk/buddy-and-jim-take-manhattan|accessdate=April 4, 2017|work=The New Yorker|date=March 1, 2013}}</ref>\n\nMiller moved to [[Nashville]] in the 1990s, after a stint in Los Angeles. He worked on recording sessions as a guitar player and vocalist, and began producing his own records in his living room studio named Dogtown.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Rotondi|first1=James|title=Universal Audio|url=http://www.uaudio.com/blog/artist-interview-buddy-miller/|website=Buddy Miller on Making Records with Apollo and UAD-2 Plug-Ins|publisher=Universal Audio|accessdate=April 14, 2015}}</ref><ref name=BM-paste-2002>{{cite news|last1=Winters|first1=Pamela|title=Buddy Miller: Playing with Guitars|url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2002/12/buddy-miller-1.html|accessdate=March 5, 2017|work=Paste Magazine|date=December 24, 2002}}</ref>\n\n== Recordings ==\nIn 1995, Buddy along with the Sacred Cows recorded a gospel album, ''Man on the Moon''.<ref name=BM-CrossRhythms-1995>{{cite news|last1=Brassington|first1=Dave|title=Buddy Miller and the Sacred Cows - Man on the Moon|url=http://www.crossrhythms.co.uk/products/Buddy_Miller_And_The_Sacred_Cows/Man_On_The_Moon/7594/|accessdate=March 4, 2017|work=CrossRhythms|date=June 1, 1995}}</ref>\n\nHis first solo recording, ''Your Love and Other Lies'', was released in 1995.<ref name=BM-MKOC-2016>{{cite news|last1=Razor X|first1= |title=Album Review: Buddy Miller \u2013 \u2018Your Love and Other Lies\u2019|url=https://mykindofcountry.wordpress.com/2016/02/03/album-review-buddy-miller-your-love-and-other-lies/|accessdate=March 4, 2017|work=My Kind of Country|date=February 3, 2016}}</ref> It was followed by ''Poison Love'' in 1997<ref name=BM-nodep-1997>{{cite news|last1=archive|first1= |title=Buddy Miller - Poison Love|url=http://nodepression.com/album-review/buddy-miller-poison-love/|accessdate=March 4, 2017\n| work=No Depression|date=August 31, 1997}}</ref> and ''Cruel Moon'' in 1999.<ref name=BM-AVclub-2002\n>{{cite news|last1=Klein|first1=Joshua|title=Buddy Miller: Cruel Moon|url=http://www.avclub.com/review/buddy-miller-emcruel-moonem-21088|accessdate=March 4, 2017|work=A.V. Club|date=March 29, 2002}}</ref>\n\nHe and his wife, Julie Miller, released ''[[Buddy & Julie Miller]]'' in 2001, which won the Album of the Year Award from the Americana Music Association.<ref>{{cite web |title=Recipient Archive |url=http://americanamusic.org/recipient-archive |website=Americana Music Association |publisher=Americana Music |accessdate=April 14, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121018055116/http://americanamusic.org/recipient-archive |archivedate=October 18, 2012 |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\nIn 2002, he released ''Midnight and Lonesome''<ref name=BM-nodep-2002>{{cite news|last1=archive|first1= |title=Buddy Miller - Midnight And Lonesome|url=http://nodepression.com/album-review/buddy-miller-midnight-and-lonesome|accessdate=March 4, 2017|work=No Depression |date=October 31, 2002}}</ref> and in 2004 he released ''[[Universal United House of Prayer]]''.<ref name=BM-PopMatters-2004>{{cite news|last1=MacNeil|first1=Jason|title=Buddy Miller: Universal United House of Prayer|url=http://www.popmatters.com/review/millerbuddy-universal/|accessdate=March 4, 2017|work=PopMatters|date=October 27, 2004}}</ref>\n\n2009 brought another Buddy and Julie duet album ''Written in Chalk''<ref name=BM-nodep-2009>{{cite news|last1=DLHTown|first1=|title=Buddy & Julie Miller - 'Written in Chalk' (review)|url=http://nodepression.com/article/buddy-julie-miller-written-chalk-review|accessdate=March 4, 2017|work=No Depression|date=March 2, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170305193544/http://nodepression.com/article/buddy-julie-miller-written-chalk-review|archive-date=March 5, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> and in 2011 Buddy collaborated with [[Bill Frisell]], [[Marc Ribot]], and [[Greg Leisz]] to release ''The Majestic Silver Strings''.<ref name=BM-PopMatters-2011>{{cite news|last1=Layman|first1=Will|title=Buddy Miller: The Majestic Silver Strings|url=http://www.popmatters.com/review/137061-buddy-miller-the-majestic-silver-strings/|accessdate=March 4, 2017\n| work=PopMatters|date=March 2, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Buddy and [[Jim Lauderdale]] released the duet album ''Buddy & Jim''<ref name=BM-PopMatters-2013>{{cite news|last1=Berick|first1=Michael|title=Buddy Miller & Jim Lauderdale: Buddy & Jim|url=https://americansongwriter.com/2013/01/buddy-miller-jim-lauderdale-buddy-jim/|accessdate=March 4, 2017|work=American Songwriter|date=January 16, 2013}}</ref> and in 2016, Buddy recorded sessions by [[Kacey Musgraves]], [[Nikki Lane]], [[Lee Ann Womack]], [[Brandi Carlile]], and [[Kris Kristofferson]] on the album ''Cayamo: Sessions at Sea''.<ref name=BM-guardian-2016>{{cite news|last1=Spencer|first1=Neil|title=Buddy Miller & Friends: Cayamo Sessions at Sea review \u2013 country cruising|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2016/jan/24/buddy-miller-and-friends-cayamo-sessions-at-sea-review-kacey-musgraves-kris-kristofferson-colvin|accessdate=March 4, 2017|work=The Guardian|date=January 24, 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Touring and performance ==\nMiller has toured as lead guitarist and backing vocalist for [[Emmylou Harris]]'s [[Spyboy (album)|Spyboy]] band,<ref name=EH-nodep-1998>{{cite news |last1=archive|first1= |title=Emmylou Harris - Lookin' for the water from a deeper well|url=http://nodepression.com/article/emmylou-harris-lookin-water-deeper-well|accessdate=March 5, 2017|work=No Depression|date=August 31, 1998}}</ref> [[Steve Earle]] on his [[El Coraz\u00f3n (Steve Earle album)|El Corazon]] tour,<ref name=SE-nodep-1998>{{cite news |last1=archive|first1= |title=Steve Earle / Buddy & Julie Miller - The Phoenix (Toronto, Ontario)|url=http://nodepression.com/live-review/steve-earle-buddy-julie-miller-phoenix-toronto-ontario/|accessdate=March 5, 2017|work=No Depression|date=February 28, 1998}}</ref> and Emmylou Harris and [[Linda Ronstadt]] on their [[Western Wall: The Tucson Sessions|Western Wall]] tour.<ref name=EH-austinchron-1999>{{cite news |last1=Lynch|first1=David|title=Linda Ronstadt & Emmylou Harris, Bass Concert Hall, October 10|url=http://www.austinchronicle.com/music/1999-10-22/74342/|accessdate=March 5, 2017|work=The Austin Chronicle|date=October 22, 1999}}</ref>\n\nIn 2002, Miller toured as part of the [[Down from the Mountain]] Tour along with [[Alison Krauss and Union Station]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Drennen|first1=Eileen|title=The Secret Is Out on the Millers|url=http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/2002-01-16/lifestyle/0201150339_1_buddy-and-julie-emmylou-harris-julie-miller|website=Orlando Sentinel|publisher=Orlando Sentinel|accessdate=April 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2004, Miller toured with Emmylou Harris, [[Patty Griffin]], [[Gillian Welch]] and [[David Rawlings]] as the [[Sweet Harmony Traveling Revue]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Jackson|first1=Josh|title=The Sweet Harmony Traveling Revue|url=http://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2004/08/the-sweet-harmony-traveling-revue-1.html|website=Paste Magazine|publisher=Paste Media Group}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, Miller toured as part of the band on [[Robert Plant]] and [[Alison Krauss]]'s [[Raising Sand]] tour of the U.S. and Europe.<ref name=BM-nashscene-2010>{{cite news|last1=Neal|first1=Chris|title=How Buddy Miller brought Robert Plant's Band of Joy into the heart of Americana|url=http://www.nashvillescene.com/news/article/13035342/how-buddy-miller-brought-robert-plants-band-of-joy-into-the-heart-of-americana|accessdate=March 4, 2017|work=Nashville Scene|date=September 2, 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, Buddy joined Emmylou Harris, Patty Griffin and Shawn Colvin on tour as Three Girls and Their Buddy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nonesuch.com/journal/emmylou-harris-shawn-colvin-announce-three-girls-and-their-buddy-tour-pre-order-event-2009-03-16|title=Emmylou Harris, Shawn Colvin Announce \"Three Girls and Their Buddy\" Tour, Pre-Order Event-Nonesuch Records|website=Nonesuch Records Official Website|language=en|access-date=January 24, 2017}}</ref> While on that tour, following a performance in Baltimore on February 19, 2009, Miller suffered a heart attack. He underwent successful triple bypass surgery at Johns Hopkins Hospital on February 20.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Betts|first1=Stephen|title=Buddy Miller Recovering from Heart Surgery|url=http://theboot.com/buddy-miller-recovering-from-heart-surgery/|website=The Boot|publisher=Taste of Country|accessdate=April 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, Miller again joined Robert Plant and Patty Griffin with Plant's [[Band of Joy]], touring the U.S. and Europe.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Neal|first1=Chris|title=How Buddy Miller brought Robert Plant's Band of Joy into the heart of Americana|url=http://www.nashvillescene.com/nashville/how-buddy-miller-brought-robert-plants-band-of-joy-into-the-heart-of-americana/Content?oid=1798568|website=Nashville Scene|publisher=City Press LLC|accessdate=April 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Buddy toured with [[Jim Lauderdale]] on the Buddy and Jim Tour.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Parker|first1=Eric|title=Buddy Miller And Jim Lauderdale Announce Tour|url=http://www.musicrow.com/2012/11/buddy-miller-and-jim-lauderdale-announce-duet-tour/|website=MusicRow|publisher=MusicRow - Nashville's Music Industry Publication|accessdate=April 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Buddy was part of the Lampedusa: Concerts for Refugees tour featuring [[Patty Griffin]], Emmylou Harris, Steve Earle, and the Milk Carton Kids.<ref name=EH-highroad-2016>{{cite news |last1=uncredited|first1= |title=Concert Tour Featuring Emmylou Harris, Patty Griffin, Buddy Miller and More will Benefit Refugee Education|url=http://www.highroadtouring.com/concert-tour-featuring-emmylou-harris-patty-griffin-buddy-miller-and-more-will-benefit-refugee-education/|accessdate=March 5, 2017|work=High Road Touring|date=September 6, 2016}}</ref>\n\nFor the past decade, Buddy has often been a part of the Cayamo Cruise, which sails from [[Miami]] to [[St. Maarten]] and [[Tortola]]. Each year, prominent Americana musicians are on board, and Buddy often collaborates and records with them.<ref name=BM-bsit-2016>{{cite news|last1=uncredited|title=The Producers: Buddy Miller|url=http://www.thebluegrasssituation.com/read/producers-buddy-miller/|accessdate=March 10, 2016|work=The Bluegrass Situation|date=March 4, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160307060420/http://www.thebluegrasssituation.com/read/producers-buddy-miller|archive-date=March 7, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nHe is a regular performer at the annual [[Hardly Strictly Bluegrass]] music festival in [[San Francisco]] where, billed as Buddy Miller's Cavalcade of Stars, he features a changing roster of guest performers.{{citation needed|date=December 2018}}\n\n== Recording work for others ==\n=== Record producer ===\n\nMiller has produced albums for artists including [[Richard Thompson (musician)|Richard Thompson]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Richard Thompson: Trio Album Produced by Buddy Miller|url=http://www.jambase.com/Articles/108508/Richard-Thompson-Trio-Album-Produced-by-Buddy-Miller|website=JamBase|publisher=JamBase Inc|accessdate=April 17, 2015}}</ref> [[Shawn Colvin]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Bio|url=http://shawncolvin.com/info/bio/|website=Shawn Colvin|publisher=Shawn Colvin|accessdate=April 17, 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150417232503/http://shawncolvin.com/info/bio/|archivedate=April 17, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref> [[The Devil Makes Three (band)|The Devil Makes Three]],<ref>{{cite web|last1=Bailey|first1=Rachel|title=The Devil Makes Three to Release Buddy Miller-Produced Album|url=http://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2013/07/vermont-americana-trio-the-devil.html|website=Paste Magazine|publisher=Paste Media Group|accessdate=April 17, 2015}}</ref> [[Allison Moorer]],<ref>{{cite web|last1=Bialas|first1=Michael|title=All Aboard: This Roller Coaster Gets Down to Believing in Allison Moorer|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/michael-bialas/all-aboard-this-roller-co_b_6789260.html|website=Huffington Post|publisher=TheHuffingtonPost.com|accessdate=April 17, 2015}}</ref> [[the Wood Brothers]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Bio|url=http://www.thewoodbros.com/bio/|website=The Wood Brothers|publisher=The Wood Brothers|accessdate=April 17, 2015}}</ref> the [[Carolina Chocolate Drops]],<ref>{{cite web|title=About|url=http://www.carolinachocolatedrops.com/band/about.html|website=Carolina Chocolate Drops|accessdate=April 17, 2015}}</ref> [[the McCrarys]],<ref>{{cite web|last1=Dauphin|first1=Chuck|title=Exclusive Album Premiere: Listen to the McCrary Sisters' 'Let's Go' Now|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/the-615/6495048/mccrary-sisters-lets-go-album-premiere|website=Billboard|publisher=Billboard|accessdate=April 17, 2015}}</ref> and [[Ralph Stanley]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Betts|first1=Stephen|title=Ralph Stanley on His All-Star Album With Robert Plant, Dierks Bentley|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/features/ralph-stanley-on-his-all-star-album-with-robert-plant-dierks-bentley-20150122|website=Rolling Stone|accessdate=April 17, 2015}}</ref> He has co-produced records with [[Robert Plant]], [[Jim Lauderdale]] and [[Jimmie Dale Gilmore]].\n\nIn 2006 [[Solomon Burke]] recorded his country album ''Nashville'' with Miller. [[Emmylou Harris]], [[Patty Griffin]], [[Gillian Welch]] and [[Dolly Parton]] appear as duet partners.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Fink|first1=Matt|title=SOLOMON BURKE: Nashville Calling|url=http://www.americansongwriter.com/2007/01/solomon-burke-nashville-calling/|website=American Songwriter|publisher=ForASong Media|accessdate=April 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\nMiller produced [[Patty Griffin]]'s [[Downtown Church]]<ref>{{cite web|last1=Ayers|first1=Michael|title=Patty Griffin Returns With Gospel Inspired 'Downtown Church'|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/960787/patty-griffin-returns-with-gospel-inspired-downtown-church|website=Billboard|publisher=Billboard|accessdate=April 14, 2015}}</ref> that was released in 2010 and won a [[Grammy Award]] for Best Traditional Gospel Album on February 13, 2011.<ref>{{cite web|title=Winners|url=http://www.grammy.com/nominees/search?year=2010|website=Grammy.com|accessdate=April 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\nMiller has produced his own solo albums as well as recordings for and with his wife, singer-songwriter [[Julie Miller]].\n\n=== Session work ===\nHe co-produced and performed on [[Jimmie Dale Gilmore]]'s 2000 album ''One Endless Night''.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Gettelman|first1=Perry|title=Gilmore Is Great on 'One Endless Night'|url=http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/2000-03-10/entertainment/0003090384_1_jimmie-dale-dale-gilmore-braver-newer|website=Orlando Sentinel|publisher=Orlando Sentinel|accessdate=April 14, 2015}}</ref> He also played on [[Lucinda Williams]]'s ''[[Car Wheels on a Gravel Road]]'' album.<ref name=LW-nodep-2009>{{cite news|last1=Giddens|first1=Jeff|title=Throwback Thursday \u2013 Lucinda Williams - Car Wheels on a Gravel Road|url=http://nodepression.com/article/throwback-thursday-\u2013-lucinda-williams-car-wheels-gravel-road|accessdate=March 4, 2017|work=No Depression|date=September 5, 2009}}</ref>\n\nMiller has worked as an instrumentalist or vocalist on records by [[Johnny Cash]], [[Levon Helm]], [[Lee Ann Womack]], [[Patty Griffin]], [[Emmylou Harris]], [[Victoria Williams]], [[Shawn Colvin]], [[Bobby Bare]], [[Chris Knight (musician)|Chris Knight]], [[John Fogerty]], the [[The Chieftains|Chieftains]], [[Frank Black]], [[Rodney Crowell]], [[Dixie Chicks]], [[Elvis Costello]], [[Alison Krauss]] and [[Robert Plant]].{{Citation needed|date=April 2015}} He has also worked as a recording engineer, mixer or mastering engineer on records by [[Willie Nelson]], [[Emmylou Harris]], [[Shawn Colvin]], [[Jim Lauderdale]], and [[Patty Griffin]].{{Citation needed|date=April 2015}}\n\n=== Songwriting ===\n{{Unsourced BLP section|date=April 2015}}\n[[Levon Helm]], Patty Griffin, Emmylou Harris, [[Lee Ann Womack]], [[Dixie Chicks]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/song/hole-in-my-head-mt0052994163|title=Hole in my Head|date=5 August 2019|website=Allmusic}}</ref> [[Hank Williams III]], [[Dierks Bentley]], [[Patty Loveless]], [[Tab Benoit]] and [[Brooks & Dunn]] have recorded songs written by Miller.\n\n=== Film and TV ===\n\nMiller signed on as a producer for the ABC TV series [[Nashville (2012 TV series)|Nashville]] in 2012.  He was the executive music producer for the show in seasons two and three.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Gold|first1=Adam|title=T Bone Burnett Not Returning to Nashville, Buddy Miller to Take Over as Show's Music Producer|url=http://www.nashvillescene.com/nashvillecream/archives/2013/06/20/t-bone-burnett-not-returning-to-nashville-buddy-miller-to-take-over-as-shows-music-producer|website=Nashville Scene|publisher=City Press, LLC|accessdate=April 14, 2015}}</ref> He also was music producer and musical director for Nashville: On The Record Live Specials.<ref>{{cite web|last1=MusicLounge|title=Nashville: On The Record Special|url=http://abc.go.com/music-lounge/news/nashville-on-the-record/nashville-otr-special|website=ABC Music Lounge|publisher=ABC|accessdate=April 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\nAlong with Don Was, Miller was the musical director for The Life and Songs of Emmylou Harris tribute concert.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Dunham|first1=Nancy|title=199 390 1131 Print The Five Best Things We Saw at the Life & Songs of Emmylou Harris Concert|url=http://www.countryweekly.com/news/five-best-things-we-saw-life-songs-emmylou-harris-concert|website=Country Weekly|publisher=Cumulus Media|accessdate=April 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\nMiller was musical director and bandleader for the Americana Music Association's Honors & Awards shows broadcast on AXS TV and PBS.<ref>{{cite web|title=Americana Music Honors & Awards to Air on PBS's ''Austin City Limits'', Featuring Robert Plant, Ry Cooder|url=http://www.nonesuch.com/journal/americana-music-honors-awards-pbs-austin-city-limits-robert-plant-ry-cooder-2014-11-20|website=Nonesuch Records|publisher=Nonesuch Records|accessdate=April 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\nBuddy has covered Tom T. Hall's song, \"That's How I Got to Memphis\", which [[Jeff Daniels]] sang in the final episode of HBO's ''The Newsroom'' in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kienzle|first1=Rich|title='The Newsroom's' Country Interlude: 'That's How I Got To Memphis'|url=http://communityvoices.post-gazette.com/arts-entertainment-living/get-rhythm/item/38608-the-newsroom-s-country-interlude-that-s-how-i-got-to-memphis|website=Post-Gazette|publisher=PG Publishing, Co|accessdate=April 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\nStarz political drama Boss used the Plant-Miller produced \"Satan, Your Kingdom Must Come Down\" as its theme song.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Neal|first1=Chris|title=How Buddy Miller brought Robert Plant's Band of Joy into the heart of Americana|url=http://www.nashvillescene.com/nashville/how-buddy-miller-brought-robert-plants-band-of-joy-into-the-heart-of-americana/Content?oid=1798568|website=Nashville Scene|publisher=City Press, LLC|accessdate=April 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\nMiller produced the track \"Beyond the Blue\" featuring [[Emmylou Harris]] and [[Patty Griffin]] for the 2000 film ''[[Where the Heart Is (2000 film)|Where the Heart Is]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Where The Heart Is|url=http://www.tcm.com/tcmdb/title/454044/Where-the-Heart-Is/music.html|website=Turner Classic Movies|publisher=Turner Entertainment Networks, Inc.|accessdate=April 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015 he appeared on [[Christina Aguilera]]'s song, \"Shotgun\", which was written for her appearance on ''[[Nashville (2012 TV series)|Nashville]]''.<ref name=CA-nodep-2015>{{cite news|last1=Miller|first1=Jordan|title=Listen: Christina Aguilera\u2019's Country Ballad \"Shotgun\"|url=http://www.breatheheavy.com/listen-christina-aguileras-country-ballad-shotgun/|accessdate=March 4, 2017|work=Breathe Heavy|date=April 21, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Miller contributed his cover of [[Mark Heard]]'s song \"Treasure of the Broken Land\" to the tribute album ''Treasure of the Broken Land: the Songs of Mark Heard''.<ref name=BM-rollingstone-2017>{{cite news|last1=Betts|first1=Stephen L.|title=Hear Buddy Miller's Intense New Song From Mark Heard Tribute Album|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/country/premieres/hear-buddy-millers-new-song-from-mark-heard-tribute-album-w478430|accessdate=April 24, 2017|work=Rolling Stone|date=April 24, 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Awards, accolades, and other activities ==\nBetween 2002 and 2013, Miller won twelve [[Americana Music Honors & Awards]] and was nominated for seven others.<ref>{{cite web |title=Recipient Archive |url=http://americanamusic.org/recipient-archive |website=Americana Music Association |publisher=Americana Music |accessdate=April 15, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121018055116/http://americanamusic.org/recipient-archive |archivedate=October 18, 2012 |df=mdy }}</ref> Since 2005, he has led the Americana All Star Band, which performs with nominated artists during the [[Americana Music Honors & Awards]] ceremonies, held annually at the [[Ryman Auditorium]].<ref>{{cite web |title=About The Awards |url=http://americanamusic.org/about-awards |website=Americana Music Association |publisher=Americana Music |accessdate=April 15, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150420081843/http://americanamusic.org/about-awards |archivedate=April 20, 2015 |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\nNo Depression magazine named him Artist of the Decade in 2008.<ref name=BM-nodep-2008 />\n\n=== Americana Music Awards ===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Category\n! Work\n! Result\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|2002\n| Artist of the Year\n| Buddy and Julie Miller\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Album of the Year\n| ''Buddy & Julie Miller''\n| {{win}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|2003\n| Instrumentalist of the Year\n| Buddy Miller\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Album of the Year\n|''Midnight & Lonesome''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"|2005\n| Artist of the Year\n| Buddy Miller\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Song of the Year\n|''Worry Too Much''\n| {{win}}\n|-\n| Album of the Year\n|''[[Universal United House of Prayer]]''\n| {{win}}\n|-\n| 2007\n| rowspan=\"3\"|Instrumentalist of the Year\n| rowspan=\"3\"| Buddy Miller\n| {{win}}\n|-\n| 2008\n| {{win}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"5\"|2009\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Album of the Year\n| \"Written In Chalk\"\n| {{win}}\n|-\n| Song of the Year\n| \"Chalk\"\n| {{win}}\n|-\n| Duo/Group of the Year\n| Buddy and Julie Miller\n| {{win}}\n|-\n| Artist of the Year\n| rowspan=\"5\"|Buddy Miller\n| {{win}}\n|-\n| 2010\n| rowspan=\"2\"|Instrumentalist of the Year\n| {{win}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|2011\n| {{win}}\n|-\n| Artist of the Year\n| {{win}}\n|-\n| 2012\n| Instrumentalist of the Year\n| {{win}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"|2013\n| Duo/Group of the Year\n| Buddy Miller and [[Jim Lauderdale]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Artist of the Year\n| Buddy Miller\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Album of the Year\n|''Buddy & Jim''\n| {{nom}}\n|}\n\n=== Grammy Awards ===\nMiller is a four-time Grammy nominee, winning once in 2010 for producing ''[[Downtown Church]]'' by [[Patty Griffin]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/artists/buddy-miller|title=Buddy Miller|date=June 4, 2019|website=Grammy.com}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Category\n! Work\n! Result\n|-\n| [[44th Annual Grammy Awards|2001]]\n| [[Grammy Award for Best Contemporary Folk Album|Best Contemporary Folk Album]]\n| ''[[Buddy & Julie Miller]]''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[47th Annual Grammy Awards|2004]]\n| [[Best Southern, Country or Bluegrass Gospel Album]]\n| ''[[Universal United House of Prayer]]''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[53rd Annual Grammy Awards|2010]]\n| [[Grammy Award for Best Traditional Gospel Album|Best Traditional Gospel Album]]\n| ''[[Downtown Church]]''\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[56th Annual Grammy Awards|2013]]\n| [[Grammy Award for Best Americana Album|Best Americana Album]]\n| ''Buddy & Jim''\n| {{nom}}\n|}\n\n== Radio ==\nMiller and his longtime friend and collaborator [[Jim Lauderdale]] teamed up in 2012 to produce ''The Buddy & Jim Radio Show'', broadcast on [[Outlaw Country (Sirius XM)|Sirius XM Outlaw Country]].<ref name=BM-songwriter-2012>{{cite news|last1=Schlansky|first1=Evan|title=Buddy Miller and Jim Lauderdale Launch Radio Show; Listen To Lucinda Williams' Guest Spot|url=https://americansongwriter.com/2012/08/buddy-miller-and-jim-lauderdale-launch-radio-show-listen-to-lucinda-williams-guest-spot/|accessdate=March 4, 2017|work=American Songwriter|date=August 1, 2012}}</ref>\n\n== Music gear ==\n[[Fender Musical Instruments Corporation|Fender]] produces a Buddy Miller signature acoustic guitar.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Bryant|first1=Will|title=Fender Acoustic > Buddy Miller Signature Guitar|url=http://www.americansongwriter.com/2009/06/fender-acoustic-buddy-miller-signature-guitar/|website=American Songwriter|publisher=ForASong Media, LLC|accessdate=April 16, 2015}}</ref>\n\nBuddy frequently uses vintage Wandr\u00e9 electric guitars<ref name=BM-paste-2004>{{cite news|last1=Scoppa|first1=Bud|title=Buddy Miller: Fancy is as Fancy Does|url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2004/10/buddy-miller.html|accessdate=March 4, 2017|work=[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]]|date=October 1, 2004}}</ref> and TEO mando-guitars.<ref name=\"BM\n-TEO-2017\">{{cite web | url=http://www.teoguitars.com/artists.html | title=TEO Guitars: Artists | work=TEO Guitars website| accessdate= March 4, 2017| author=uncredited}}</ref>\n\nIn his studio, Buddy uses a pair of Swart amplifiers: Atomic Space Tones and Atomic Space Tone Pros, and two tremolos panned in stereo at conflicting settings.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite news|last1=Chandler|first1=Stacy|title=SPOTLIGHT: Come Along as Buddy Miller shows Aaron Lee Tasjan around His Home Studio|url=https://www.nodepression.com/spotlight-come-along-as-buddy-miller-shows-aaron-lee-tasjan-around-his-home-studio/|accessdate=June 26, 2019|work=No Depression|date=June 24, 2019}}</ref> Onstage, he often uses a Swart Atomic Space Tones amplifier and a Fulltone Supa-Trem2 pedal.<ref name=BM-premier-2016>{{cite news|last1=Drozdowski|first1=Ted|title=Session Sages: Nick Raskulinecz, Dave Cobb, and Buddy Miller on Recording Guitars|url=https://www.premierguitar.com/articles/24816-session-sages-nick-raskulinecz-dave-cobb-amp-buddy-miller-on-recording-guitars|accessdate=April 24, 2017|work=Premier Guitar|date=November 16, 2016}}</ref>\n\nHe mostly records using [[Pro Tools]], but in his recording studio Buddy treasures a 1970s Trident B Range 28\u00d724 analog recording console that previously belonged to Mark Heard.<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref name=BM-rollingstone-2017 />\n\n== Compositions  ==\n{{Main| Compositions by Buddy and Julie Miller}}\n\n== Discography ==\n{{Main| Buddy Miller discography}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|Buddy Miller}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.buddyandjulie.com/}}\n* {{Allmusic | id= buddy-miller-mn0000640419 | label= Buddy Miller}}\n* {{discogs artist|275416-Buddy-Miller|Buddy Miller}}\n{{Buddy Miller|state=autocollapse}} \n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Miller, Buddy}}\n[[Category:American country singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:American country guitarists]]\n[[Category:American male guitarists]]\n[[Category:American male singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:American record producers]]\n[[Category:American audio engineers]]\n[[Category:1952 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Nashville, Tennessee]]\n[[Category:People from Fairborn, Ohio]]\n[[Category:New West Records artists]]\n[[Category:Songwriters from Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Songwriters from Ohio]]\n[[Category:Guitarists from Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Engineers from Ohio]]\n[[Category:Engineers from Tennessee]]\n[[Category:20th-century American guitarists]]\n[[Category:Band of Joy members]]\n[[Category:Guitarists from Ohio]]\n[[Category:Country musicians from Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Country musicians from Ohio]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male musicians]]\n", "name_user": "Chris the speller", "label": "safe", "comment": "replaced: -  \u2192  \u2013  (9), =Wall Street Journal \u2192 =The Wall Street Journal (2)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Buddy_Miller"}
